ch 16, 2014  }}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"EP release \u2013 The Unmaking\">\n{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00ZGJ86B0 |title=The Unmaking \u2013 EP by Nichole Nordeman |publisher=Amazon.com |accessdate=August 30, 2015  }}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"Allmusic \u2013 Biography\">\n{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/nichole-nordeman-mn0000396144/biography |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6O6Uh2Tu1?url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/nichole-nordeman-mn0000396144/biography |title=Nichole Nordeman \u2013 Biography |work=[[Allmusic]] |publisher=[[All Media Network]] |accessdate=March 16, 2014 |archivedate=March 16, 2014 }}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"Single release \u2013 Tremble\">\n{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/tremble-mw0000063843/releases |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6O6VGon7r?url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/tremble-mw0000063843/releases |title=Tremble \u2013 single by Nichole Nordeman |work=Allmusic |publisher=All Media Network |accessdate=March 16, 2014 |archivedate=March 16, 2014 }}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"Single release \u2013 Every Season\">\n{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/every-season-mw0000063687/releases |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6O6VM5wM5?url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/every-season-mw0000063687/releases |title=Every Season \u2013 single by Nichole Nordeman |work=Allmusic |publisher=All Media Network |accessdate=March 16, 2014 |archivedate=March 16, 2014 }}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"Single release \u2013 Holy\">\n{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/holy-mw0002036227/releases |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6O6VdR31o?url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/holy-mw0002036227/releases |title=Holy \u2013 single by Nichole Nordeman |work=Allmusic |publisher=All Media Network |accessdate=March 16, 2014 |archivedate=March 16, 2014 }}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"Single release \u2013 Legacy/This Mystery\">\n{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/legacy-this-mystery-mw0000026034/releases |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6O6VVplms?url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/legacy-this-mystery-mw0000026034/releases |title=Legacy/This Mystery \u2013 single by Nichole Nordeman |work=Allmusic |publisher=All Media Network |accessdate=March 16, 2014 |archivedate=March 16, 2014 }}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"Single release \u2013 Beautiful For Me\">\n{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/beautiful-for-me-single/id715978727 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6O6WMpVlZ?url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/beautiful-for-me-single/id715978727 |title=Beautiful For Me \u2013 single by Nichole Nordeman |work=[[iTunes Store]] |publisher=[[Apple Inc.]] |accessdate=March 16, 2014 |archivedate=March 16, 2014 }}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"Single release \u2013 Beautiful For Me\">\n{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/beautiful-for-me-single/id715978727 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6O6WMpVlZ?url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/beautiful-for-me-single/id715978727 |title=Beautiful For Me \u2013 single by Nichole Nordeman |work=[[iTunes Store]] |publisher=[[Apple Inc.]] |accessdate=March 16, 2014 |archivedate=March 16, 2014 }}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"Single release \u2013 Turn Your Eyes Upon Jesus\">\n{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/turn-your-eyes-upon-jesus/id715702579 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6O6WWJ5aY?url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/turn-your-eyes-upon-jesus/id715702579 |title=Turn Your Eyes Upon Jesus (Look Up)  \u2013 single by Nichole Nordeman |work=[[iTunes Store]] |publisher=[[Apple Inc.]] |accessdate=March 16, 2014 |archivedate=March 16, 2014 }}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"Single release \u2013 Real\">\n{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/real-single/id705326580 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6O6WYP6kd?url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/real-single/id705326580 |title=Real \u2013 single by Nichole Nordeman |work=[[iTunes Store]] |publisher=[[Apple Inc.]] |accessdate=March 16, 2014 |archivedate=March 16, 2014 }}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"Other appearance \u2013 32 Great Hymns of the Faith\">\n{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B000T067JE |title=32 Great Hymns of the Faith \u2013 album by London Festival Orchestra |publisher=Amazon.com |accessdate=March 16, 2014  }}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"Other appearance \u2013 Heaven & Earth: A Tapestry of Worship\">\n{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0000296XM |title=Heaven & Earth: A Tapestry of Worship \u2013 album by Jennifer Knapp, Nichole Nordeman, Michelle Tumes, Rebecca St. James |publisher=Amazon.com |accessdate=March 16, 2014  }}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"Other appearance \u2013 City on a Hill: Sing Alleluia\">\n{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00005Y4OR |title=City on a Hill: Sing Alleluia \u2013 album by various artists |publisher=Amazon.com |accessdate=March 16, 2014  }}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"Other appearance \u2013 Girls of Grace\">\n{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00006FIC4 |title=Girls of Grace \u2013 album by Point of Grace and various artists |publisher=Amazon.com |accessdate=March 16, 2014  }}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"Other appearance \u2013 WOW Christmas\">\n{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00006JOG8 |title=WOW Christmas \u2013 album by various artists |publisher=Amazon.com |accessdate=March 16, 2014  }}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"Other appearance \u2013 In the Name of Love\">\n{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00016MCCC |title=In the Name of Love: Artists United for Africa \u2013 album by various artists |publisher=Amazon.com |accessdate=March 16, 2014  }}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"Other appearance \u2013 Music Inspired by The Chronicles of Narnia\">\n{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B000AXWH26 |title=Music Inspired by The Chronicles of Narnia: The Lion, the Witch and the Wardrobe \u2013 album by various artists |publisher=Amazon.com |accessdate=March 16, 2014  }}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"Other appearance \u2013 Sing Over Me\">\n{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B000GEU6FO |title=Sing Over Me: Worship Songs & Lullabies \u2013 album by various artists |publisher=Amazon.com |accessdate=March 16, 2014  }}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"Other appearance \u2013 Amazing Grace\">\n{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B000LW7UUK |title=Amazing Grace: Music Inspired by the Motion Picture \u2013 album by various artists |publisher=Amazon.com |accessdate=March 16, 2014  }}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"Music video \u2013 Legacy\">\n{{cite AV media |url=http://www.newreleasetuesday.com/videodetail.php?video_id=2340 |people=[[Nichole Nordeman|Nordeman, Nichole]] | date=2002 | title=Legacy | medium=music video |work==New Release Tuesday | publisher=NRT Media Inc}}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"Music video \u2013 Finally Free\">\n{{cite AV media |url=http://www.godtube.com/watch/?v=JB0F2FNU |people=Nordeman, Nichole | date=2008 | title=Finally Free | medium=music video |work=[[Godtube]] | publisher=[[Salem Web Network]]}}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"Music video \u2013 Beautiful for Me\">\n{{cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=orc4TuIO56s |people=Nordeman, Nichole | date=2010 | title=Beautiful for Me | medium=music video |work=[[YouTube]] | publisher=YouTube, LLC }}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"CBN \u2013 Recollection\">\n{{cite web |url=https://www.cbn.com/cbnmusic/interviews/jej_NicholeNordeman050507.aspx |title=Nichole Nordeman's Legacy |first=Jennifer |last=Jones |publisher=[[Christian Broadcasting Network]] |accessdate=March 16, 2014  }}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"Beliefnet \u2013 The Story\">\n{{cite web |url=http://www.beliefnet.com/columnists/wholenotes/2011/10/nichole-nordeman-talks-about-life-away-from.html |title=Dove Award winning singer/songwriter Nichole Nordeman talks about life away from full-time music and writing songs for \"The Story\" |first=Chad |last=Bonham |work=[[Beliefnet]] |publisher=BN Media Associates |accessdate=March 16, 2014  }}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"Nichole Nordeman Instagram\">\n{{cite web |url=http://instagram.com/p/kkEErJLH-H/ |title=Nichole Nordeman: I'm writing for a new record  |publisher=[[Instagram]] |accessdate=March 16, 2014  }}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"Amazon Bio \u2013 Nichole Nordeman\">\n{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/-/e/B008XLHXT4 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6O6dFsbtl?url=http://www.amazon.com/Nichole-Nordeman/e/B008XLHXT4 |title=About Nichole Nordeman |publisher=Amazon.com |accessdate=March 16, 2014 |archivedate=March 16, 2014  }}\n</ref>\n<ref name=\"Hits Daily Double\">\n{{cite web |url=http://hitsdailydouble.com/new_album_releases |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150829191011/http://hitsdailydouble.com/new_album_releases |title=Upcoming Releases |publisher=Hits Digital Ventures |accessdate=August 29, 2015 |archivedate=August 29, 2015 }}\n</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=mn0000396144|tab=discography|label=Nichole Nordeman discography}}\n\n{{Nichole Nordeman}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nordeman, Nichole}}\n[[Category:Discographies of American artists]]\n[[Category:Christian music discographies]]\n", "name_user": "Sandstein", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing link(s):Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/Gospel Music Associationclosed as delete (XFDcloser)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nichole_Nordeman_discography"}
{"title_page": "Derek Minor", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Derek Minor\n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Derek Laurence Johnson, Jr.\n| alias            = PRo\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1984|12|16}}\n| birth_place      = [[Pontiac, Michigan]]\n| origin           = [[Middle Tennessee]], United States\n| genre            = [[Christian hip hop]]\n| occupation       = [[Rapper]], [[record producer]], [[actor]], [[screenwriter]]\n| instrument       = \n| years_active     = 2006\u2013present\n| label            = Reflection, [[Reach Records|Reach]], Scyon\n| associated_acts  = [[116 Clique]], Andal\u00e9, [[Canon (rapper)|Canon]], [[Chad Jones (rapper)|Chad Jones]], [[Chris Cobbins]], DJ Wade O, [[Json (rapper)|Json]], [[Lecrae]], [[R.M.G.]], [[Tony Tillman]]\n| website          = {{URL|derekminor.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Derek Johnson, Jr.''', better known by his stage name '''Derek Minor''' and former stage name '''PRo''', (born December 16, 1984) is an American [[Christian hip hop]] artist, [[record producer]], [[entrepreneur]], [[actor]], and [[screenwriter]]. He co-founded the hip-hop record label Reflection Music Group (RMG) with Doc Watson, and signed to [[Reach Records]] in a joint venture between the two labels in 2011. In 2012, Johnson announced that he had changed his stage name from Pro to Derek Minor. In 2014, he announced that as his two-album contract with Reach was complete, he would no longer be publishing releases through that label.\n\nHe is a founding member of the hip-hop group R.M.G. on Reflection, and was formerly a member of the Reach hip-hop collective [[116 Clique]]. Johnson has released six studio albums and six mixtapes as a solo artist, as well as one studio album each with the groups R.M.G. and 116 Clique. His second studio album, ''Redemption'', charted at No. 8 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' Gospel chart and No. 31 on the ''Billboard'' [[Christian Albums|Top Christian]] chart. His third studio album, ''Dying to Live'', debuted at No. 66 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], No. 1 on the Top Christian chart, No. 2 on the Gospel Albums chart, No. 7 on the Top [[Independent Albums]] chart, and No. 11 on the [[Rap Albums|Top Rap]] chart. His fourth album, ''Minorville'', released in 2013 debuted at No. 5 on Billboard's Rap Albums chart and No. 7 on the Top Christian chart. He partnered with Entertainment One to release his fifth album, ''Empire'', that debuted at No. 6 on the Billboard Rap Albums chart and No. 1 on the Top Christian chart. His sixth album, ''Reflection'', entered the Billboard Rap Albums chart at No. 5 and the Top Christian chart at No. 7. ''Reflection''<nowiki/>'s single \"Change the World\" featuring Hollyn reached No. 1 on Billboard's Hot AC/CHR chart.<ref name=\"Sarachik\">{{Cite news|url=http://rapzilla.com/rz/news/38-backstage/14977-derek-minor-s-change-the-world-ft-hollyn-hits-no-1-on-billboard-chart|title=Derek Minor's 'Change the World' ft. Hollyn Hits No. 1 on Billboard Chart|last=Sarachik|first=Justin|work=Rapzilla.com|access-date=July 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\nJohnson's film and television work includes the three-part [[webseries]] \"Dying to Live\" and the short documentary films ''Redemption'' and ''Welcome to the Family Documentary''. Johnson also was featured as the title character in the video game ''Altered Pro'', released under Reach Records.\n\n== Life and career ==\n\n=== Early ===\n\nDerek Johnson, Jr. was born in [[Pontiac, Michigan]] on December 16, 1984, but at a young age relocated to [[Middle Tennessee]] with his mother.<ref name=bio>{{cite web|title=Derek Minor (PRo)|url=http://reflectionmusicgroup.com/artists/derek-minor-pro|work=Artists|publisher=Reflection Music Group|accessdate=January 13, 2013|author=Reflection Music Group|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130115080720/http://reflectionmusicgroup.com/artists/derek-minor-pro|archive-date=January 15, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=fbpro>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/thederekminor/posts/10152484947544128|title=Thanks to everyone for the birthday...|author=PRo|date=December 16, 2013|publisher=Derek Minor|accessdate=May 18, 2014}}</ref> His relationship with his birth father was distant, and his relationship with his stepfather became increasingly tense.<ref name=bio /> Furthermore, Johnson's stepfather was a drug user while his mother was a strict, devout Christian with a rigorous work schedule and homelife. Johnson decided to help his mother by becoming rich through either education or music.<ref name=bio />\n\nJohnson had grown up with music, as Gospel songs were played at his house and his mother was in choir and sang around the city.<ref name=bio /> Johnson's father, a [[jazz]] musician, provided the inspiration for him to go into music. When Johnson was 12, he visited his father in the summer and started rapping about God and adolescence, with his father producing beats with an [[Ensoniq ASR-10]].<ref name=bio /> Johnson was also introduced to [[DJ Quik]] that summer, and went home with piles of [[Compact Cassette|tape]]s.<ref name=bio />\n\nAfter visiting to [[Middle Tennessee State University]] at age 15, Johnson decided to enroll in the music program there and make his ambitions a reality.<ref name=bio /> His mother helped him by buying him production equipment, and by the time he entered college, Johnson was in a rap duo and got a job to pay for studio time.<ref name=bio /> He graduated in 2006 with a bachelor's degree in Recording Industry Management.<ref name=dasouthinterview>{{cite web|title=Pro - The Making of a Professional|url=http://ns1.dasouth.com/features/interviews/623-pro-the-making-of-a-professional|work=DaSouth.com|accessdate=January 13, 2013|author=Zee|date=February 16, 2009|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130215192525/http://ns1.dasouth.com/features/interviews/623-pro-the-making-of-a-professional|archive-date=February 15, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Johnson recalls that before he turned 21 he used a bunk bed as a mic stand and signed a record deal with an independent label.<ref name=bio /> While on the label, he released a mix tape, but the company folded and his life took a turn for the worse.<ref name=bio /> Removed from his strict home environment, Johnson rebelled. He pursued music, women and money until '\"the season of death\"' shook up his life.<ref name=bio /> Within a short time span, Johnson lost his grandfather, grandmother and godmother. This loss sparked a realization of the fleeting nature of life, and Johnson decided to dedicate his life and talents to God.<ref name=bio />\n\n=== Reflection Music Group (2008\u20132010) ===\n\nJohnson co-founded Reflection Music Group, then-called Christ Like Entertainment, with his friend Doc Watson, who he met while working on a second mixtape, ''Transformers''.<ref name=bio /><ref name=dasouthinterview /> Johnson released his debut album ''The Blackout'' in 2008.<ref name=bio /> According to DaSouth.com, the \"braggidocious, swagtastic approach\" that Johnson took on the album met with controversy in the Christian hip hop community.<ref name=dasouthredemption>{{cite web|last=Hill|first=Kellus|title=Review: PRo \"Redemption\"|url=http://www.dasouth.com/reviews/3596-review-pro-qredemptionq|work=DaSouth.com|accessdate=January 14, 2013|date=July 9, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101227145631/http://www.dasouth.com/reviews/3596-review-pro-qredemptionq|archive-date=December 27, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> Johnson took a break from rapping, and was challenged and influenced by a new friend, BJ, that he met at his new church in [[Memphis, Tennessee]], and was further challenged by Christian hip-hop artist [[Lecrae]].<ref name=bio /><ref name=redemptionfilm>{{cite web|title=Pro Presents Redemption (The Short Film) (@mynameispro @reachrecords)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=32laK9znEoU|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=January 13, 2013|format=Web/Video|date=February 1, 2011}}</ref> Johnson reflected that his first album was mostly about haters and how good an emcee he was, and was convinced that it should have been more focused on God.<ref name=redemptionfilm /> In January 2010, Johnson released the mixtape ''PSA'', which he considers his first full-length installment of \"mature\" Christian music.<ref name=bio /> That year, Johnson went on the \"Urban Missionary Tour\" with Thi'sl, k-Drama, and J'Son, including a stop in the [[United Kingdom]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Rood|first=Philip|title=Urban Missionary Tour 2010 feat. Thi'sl, k-Drama, J'Son, Pro|url=http://www.rapzilla.com/rz/news/38-backstage/2025-urban-missionary-tour-2010-feat-thisl-k-drama-json-pro|work=[[Rapzilla]]|publisher=Philip Rood and Chad Horton|accessdate=January 14, 2013|date=April 14, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=London Rap Concert featuring DJ Morphiziz, J'Son, K-Drama, Pro & Thi'sl, Sunday Sept. 26th|url=http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/4221-london-rap-concert-featuring-dj-morphiziz-json-k-drama-pro-a-thisl-sunday-sept-26th|work=DaSouth.com|accessdate=January 14, 2013|author=DJ D-Lite|date=September 24, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101229055751/http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/4221-london-rap-concert-featuring-dj-morphiziz-json-k-drama-pro-a-thisl-sunday-sept-26th|archive-date=December 29, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> In preparation for his second studio album, ''Redemption'', Johnson wrote a short autobiographical film entitled \"Redemption\", and it was released as a [[web film]] in May.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rood|first=Philip|title=PRo presents Redemption - the short film|url=http://rapzilla.com/rz/news/38-backstage/2175-pro-presents-redemption-the-short-film|work=[[Rapzilla]]|publisher=Philip Rood and Chad Horton|accessdate=January 14, 2013|date=June 2, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Video: PRo presents \"Redemption\" 20-minute short film|url=http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/3337-video-pro-presents-qredemptionq-20-minute-short-film|work=Dasouth.com|accessdate=January 14, 2013|author=DaSouth.com|date=May 29, 2010|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130215191901/http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/3337-video-pro-presents-qredemptionq-20-minute-short-film|archive-date=February 15, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> The album ''Redemption'' was released July 13, 2010, and peaked at No. 8 on the ''Billboard'' Top Gospel Albums and No. 31 on the [[Top Christian Albums]] charts.<ref name=redemptionchart>{{cite web|title=Gospel Albums|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2010-07-31/gospel-albums|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Nielsen Business Media]]|accessdate=January 13, 2013|date=July 31, 2010}}</ref> This release was followed by an announcement in August that Johnson would be featured as a special guest on the [[116 Clique]] \"Unashamed 2010\" tour, which ran October through November.<ref>{{cite web|title=Reach Records announces Unashamed 2010: The Movement Tour - Now booking|url=http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/3748-reach-records-announces-unashamed-2010-the-movement-tour-now-booking|work=DaSouth.com|accessdate=January 14, 2013|author=DaSouth.com|date=August 5, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708233730/http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/3748-reach-records-announces-unashamed-2010-the-movement-tour-now-booking|archivedate=July 8, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Also in August, Johnson received a write-up in ''[[Jet (magazine)|Jet]]'' and was featured on the front page of the magazine's website.<ref>{{cite web|last=Horton|first=Chad|title=PRo Featured in JET Magazine|url=http://rapzilla.com/rz/news/38-backstage/2354-pro-featured-in-jet-magazine|work=[[Rapzilla]]|publisher=Philip Rood and Chad Horton|accessdate=January 14, 2013|date=August 10, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=JET features PRo on site with major write-up|url=http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/3764-jet-features-pro-on-site-with-major-write-up|work=DaSouth.com|accessdate=January 14, 2013|date=August 10, 2010|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130215235601/http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/3764-jet-features-pro-on-site-with-major-write-up|archive-date=February 15, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== Reach Records and name change (2011\u20132013) ===\n\nOn January 25, 2011, [[Reach Records]] announced that it had signed Johnson as a joint venture with Reflection Music Group, and the same day Johnson released the single \"116\", featuring [[KB (rapper)|KB]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Rood|first=Philip|title=Reach Records signs PRo|url=http://rapzilla.com/rz/news/38-backstage/2834-reach-records-signs-pro|work=[[Rapzilla]]|publisher=Philip Rood and Chad Horton|accessdate=January 14, 2013|date=January 25, 2011}}</ref> On March 8, Johnson released the mixtape ''PSA: Vol. 2''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wilson|first=Marcel|title=Free Download: Reach Records releases PRo's mixtape \"PSA: Volume 2\"|url=http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/5496-free-download-reach-records-releases-pros-mixtape-qpsa-volume-2q|work=DaSouth.com|accessdate=January 14, 2013|date=March 8, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316051419/http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/5496-free-download-reach-records-releases-pros-mixtape-qpsa-volume-2q|archive-date=March 16, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> On July 10, Johnson announced the launch of a three-part [[webseries]] \"Dying to Live\" to promote his upcoming studio album of the same name.<ref>{{cite web|title=Video: PRo launching online mini series July 12th|url=http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/6414-video-pro-launching-online-mini-series-july-12th|work=DaSouth.com|accessdate=January 14, 2013|author=DaSouth.com|date=July 10, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712202454/http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/6414-video-pro-launching-online-mini-series-july-12th|archive-date=July 12, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> In the months of August and October, Pro toured with 116 Clique as part of the group's \"Man Up\" campaign.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rood|first=Philip|title=Reach Records' Upcoming Tours, Rehab, Man Up, & Unashamed Africa|url=http://rapzilla.com/rz/news/38-backstage/3372-reach-records-upcoming-tours-rehab-man-up-unashamed-africa|work=[[Rapzilla]]|publisher=Philip Rood and Chad Horton|accessdate=January 14, 2013|date=July 15, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Recap: Man Up Tour \u2013 Houston|url=http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/7277-recap-man-up-tour-houston|work=DaSouth.com|accessdate=January 14, 2013|author=Sketch the Journalist|date=November 4, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120106083010/http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/7277-recap-man-up-tour-houston|archive-date=January 6, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Man Up Tour <nowiki>|| 10.22.11 ||</nowiki> Houston, TX|url=http://www.dasouth.com/manuphouston/|work=DaSouth.com|accessdate=January 14, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706235229/http://www.dasouth.com/manuphouston/|archive-date=July 6, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> On August 9, Reach Records released the [[web game]] ''Altered Pro'', a zombie game based off the [[Sega]] classic ''[[Altered Beast]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rood|first=Philip|title=PRo \"Altered Pro\" - Video Game|url=http://www.rapzilla.com/rz/news/38-backstage/3448-altered-pro-video-game|work=[[Rapzilla]]|publisher=Philip Rood and Chad Horton|accessdate=January 14, 2013|date=August 9, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Reach Records releases online video game Altered PRo - PLAY NOW!|url=http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/6590-reach-records-releases-online-video-game-altered-pro-play-now|work=DaSouth.com|accessdate=January 14, 2013|author=DaSouth.com|date=August 9, 2011|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130215200356/http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/6590-reach-records-releases-online-video-game-altered-pro-play-now|archive-date=February 15, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> The full-length studio album, ''Dying to Live'', was released on August 23. The album debuted at No. 1 on the [[Christian Albums]] chart, No. 2 on the Gospel Albums chart, No. 7 on the [[Independent Albums]], No. 11 on the [[Rap Albums]] chart and No. 66 on the ''Billboard'' 200.<ref name=dietolivechart>{{cite web|title=Christian Albums|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2011-09-10/christian-albums|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Nielsen Business Media]]|accessdate=January 14, 2013|date=September 10, 2011}}</ref> The album was also the featured banner on the [[iTunes]] homepage as well in the Christian & Religious and Hip Hop/Rap departments.<ref>{{cite web|last=Horton|first=Chad|title=PRo 'Dying To Live' Featured Throughout iTunes|url=http://rapzilla.com/rz/news/38-backstage/3534-pro-dying-to-live-featured-throughout-itunes|work=[[Rapzilla]]|publisher=Philip Rood and Chad Horton|accessdate=January 14, 2013|date=August 26, 2011}}</ref> In September, Johnson performed at the 2011 Flavor Fest, and on September 27, 2011, the album ''Man Up'' by 116 Clique was released.<ref>{{cite web|last=Solis|first=Steven|title=Flavor Fest 2011 National Artists Lineup|url=http://www.rapzilla.com/rz/news/38-backstage/3617-flavor-fest-2011-national-artists-lineup|work=[[Rapzilla]]|publisher=Philip Rood and Chad Horton|accessdate=January 14, 2013|date=September 13, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Jeffries|first=David|title=Man Up|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/man-up-mw0002242981|work=[[Allmusic]]|publisher=[[Rovi Corporation]]|accessdate=January 14, 2013}}</ref> In October, Johnson was included with [[Bryan Winchester|Braille]] and 116 Clique as some of the artists in the iTunes Indie Spotlight for hip hop music.<ref>{{cite web|last=Horton|first=Chad|title=iTunes Indie Spotlight: Hip-Hop - October 2011 Features 116, PRo, & Braille|url=http://rapzilla.com/rz/news/38-backstage/3760-itunes-indie-spotlight-hip-hop-october-2011-features-116-pro-a-braille|work=[[Rapzilla]]|publisher=Philip Rood and Chad Horton|accessdate=January 14, 2013|date=October 29, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2012, Reflection Music Group announced the formation of the hip-hop group R.M.G., consisting of the artists Pro, Canon, Tony Tillman (formerly known as Brothatone), and Chad Jones (formerly known as Conviction).<ref name=r.m.g.>{{cite web|last=Horton|first=Chad|title=Reflection Music Group Signees R.M.G. Get \"Geeked Up\"|url=http://allhiphop.com/2012/02/23/reach-records-signees-r-m-g-get-geeked-up/|work=[[AllHipHop]]|publisher=AHH Holdings LLC|accessdate=January 14, 2013|date=February 23, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"geeked up\">{{cite web|last=Horton|first=Chad|title=RMG (PRo, Canon, Brothatone, Chad Jones) - Geeked Up|url=http://www.rapzilla.com/rz/news/38-backstage/4208-rmg-pro-canon-brothatone-chad-jones-geeked-up|work=[[Rapzilla]]|publisher=Philip Rood and Chad Horton|accessdate=January 14, 2013|date=February 18, 2012}}</ref> With this announcement came the release of R.M.G.'s debut single \"Geeked Up\" on February 21.<ref name=r.m.g. /><ref name=\"geeked up\" /> On March 21, the group released an online documentary film entitled \"Welcome to the Family Documentary\" in preparation for its debut album ''Welcome to the Family'', which was released March 27.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mini Doc: RMG - Welcome to the Family|url=http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/8880-video-rmg-qwelcome-to-the-familyq-documentary|work=DaSouth.com|accessdate=January 14, 2013|author=DaSouth.com|date=March 21, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120525170800/http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/8880-video-rmg-qwelcome-to-the-familyq-documentary|archive-date=May 25, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome to the Family (feat. Pro, Canon, Tony Tillman & Chad Jones) by R.M.G|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/welcome-to-family-feat.-pro/id509557508|publisher=[[iTunes]]|accessdate=January 14, 2013|author=R.M.G.}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, 2012, Johnson performed at the 2012 [[South by Southwest]] festival as part of the Reach Records showcase along with Lecrae, [[Trip Lee]], [[Tedashii]], [[Andy Mineo]], and KB.<ref>{{cite web|title=Christian rap returns to SXSW in 2012: Reach Records & DaSouth.com showcases|url=http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/8272-christian-rap-returns-to-sxsw-in-2012-reach-records-a-dasouthcom-showcases|work=DaSouth.com|accessdate=January 14, 2013|author=Sketch the Journalist|date=February 7, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130117175406/http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/8272-christian-rap-returns-to-sxsw-in-2012-reach-records-a-dasouthcom-showcases|archive-date=January 17, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> On August 6, 2012, Johnson revealed the cover art for his upcoming mixtape, ''PSA Vol. 3: Who Is Derek Minor?'', and with it revealed that he had changed his stage name from Pro to Derek Minor.<ref>{{cite web|last=Solis|first=Steven|title=Derek Minor fka PRo 'PSA Vol. 3' Cover Revealed|url=http://rapzilla.com/rz/news/38-backstage/4853-derek-minor-fka-pro-psa-vol-3-cover-revealed|work=[[Rapzilla]]|publisher=Philip Rood and Chad Horton|accessdate=January 14, 2013|date=August 6, 2012}}</ref> From October through November, Johnson toured with 116 Clique on the \"Unashamed 2012: Come Alive\" tour.<ref>{{cite web|last=Horton|first=Chad|title=Reach Records Artists Come Alive Via The \"Unashamed Tour 2012\"|url=http://allhiphop.com/2012/07/08/reach-records-artists-come-alive-via-the-unashamed-tour-2012/|work=[[AllHipHop]]|publisher=AHH Holdings|accessdate=January 14, 2013|date=July 8, 2012}}</ref> On November 8, 2012, South by Southwest announced that Reach Records would again hold a showcase with its entire roster, including Derek Minor, in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lecrae and other Reach Booking artists among first acts announced for SXSW 2013|url=http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/10394-lecrae-and-other-reach-booking-artists-among-first-acts-announced-for-sxsw-2013|work=DaSouth.com|accessdate=January 14, 2013|author=Sketch the Journalist|date=November 9, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130112180012/http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/10394-lecrae-and-other-reach-booking-artists-among-first-acts-announced-for-sxsw-2013|archive-date=January 12, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with [[Rapzilla]] on May 5, 2013, Kyle Dettman, video director for Reach Records, revealed that Reach Records is preparing promotional material for Derek Minor's upcoming album ''Minorville''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rood|first=Philip|title=Kyle Dettman Live Interview - Lecrae Confe$$ions Music Video|url=http://rapzilla.com/rz/features/interviews/6203-kyle-dettman-live-interview-reach-records-director-of-video|work=[[Rapzilla]]|publisher=Philip Rood and Chad Horton|accessdate=May 4, 2013|format=Video/Web|date=May 2, 2013}}</ref> On June 6, 2013, Minor released a lyric video for a single from ''Minorville'', \"Dear Mr. Christian\" featuring [[Dee-1]] and Lecrae, followed by an actual release of the single the next day.<ref>{{cite web|title=\nDerek Minor - Dear Mr. Christian, (Lyric Video) ft. Dee-1 & Lecrae|url=http://rapzilla.com/rz/video-page2/6414-derek-minor-dear-mr-christian-lyric-video-ft-dee-1-a-lecrae|work=[[Rapzilla]]|publisher=Philip Rood and Chad Horton|accessdate=July 3, 2013|format=Video/Web|date=June 6, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Derek Minor - Dear Mr. Christian, ft. Dee-1 & Lecrae|url=http://www.rapzilla.com/rz/music/6440-derek-minor-dear-mr-christian|work=[[Rapzilla]]|publisher=Philip Rood and Chad Horton|accessdate=June 11, 2013|date=May 2, 2013}}</ref> Later, on June 21, Reach Records released the album cover for ''Minorville'' by a video showing the album cover making-process, and also announced the release date, September 10, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|last=Solis|first=Steven|title=Derek Minor - In God We Trust ft. Thi'sl|url=http://rapzilla.com/rz/video-page2/6562-derek-minor-in-god-we-trust-ft-thisl|work=[[Rapzilla]]|publisher=Philip Rood and Chad Horton|accessdate=July 3, 2013|format=Web/Video|date=July 2, 2013}}</ref> The promotion for the album continued on July 2, when Minor dropped a teaser video for a track called \"In God We Trust\" featuring Thi'sl.<ref>{{cite web|title=Derek Minor 'Minorville' Album Cover & Release Date Revealed|url=http://rapzilla.com/rz/news/38-backstage/6502-derek-minor-minorville-album-cover-a-release-date-revealed|work=[[Rapzilla]]|publisher=Philip Rood and Chad Horton|accessdate=July 3, 2013|date=June 20, 2013}}</ref> The album debuted at No. 40 on the ''Billboard'' 200, No. 1 on the Gospel Albums Chart, No. 2 on the Christian Albums Chart, No. 6 on the Independent Albums Chart and No. 6 on the Rap Albums Chart, making it his best chart performing album to date.\n\nOn March 18, 2014, [[Rapzilla]] announced that Derek Minor had parted ways with Reach Records, as his two-album contract with Reach had expired.<ref name=leavingreach >{{cite web|url = http://www.rapzilla.com/rz/news/1/7996|title = Derek Minor No Longer With Reach Records|date = March 18, 2014|accessdate = June 9, 2014|website = [[Rapzilla]]|publisher = Philip Rood and Chad Horton|last = Nyamu|first = Vincent}}</ref> Minor was quoted, \"I've grown as an artist, business owner and a man. The beauty of the relationship we've established is that business wasn't its primary agenda and I'm excited to see what the future holds for both RMG and Reach.\"<ref name=leavingreach />\n\n=== Independent route and distribution deals (2014\u2013present) ===\n{{Prose|section|date=July 2017}}\nIn October 2014 at the [[Dove Awards]] he announced that his fifth album will be titled ''Empire'' and will be released in the first quarter of 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rapzilla.com/rz/videos/live/9264-video-derek-minor-reveals-new-album-title|title=Video: Derek Minor Reveals New Album 'Empire'|author=Roman Flores|publisher=|accessdate=October 20, 2014}}</ref> On October 22, 2014, it was announced that Derek Minor had signed a distribution deal with [[Entertainment One]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christianpost.com/news/lecraes-former-label-mate-derek-minor-signs-to-popular-secular-music-company-eone-128491/|title=Lecrae's Former Label-Mate Derek Minor Signs to Popular Secular Music Company eOne|work=Christian Post}}</ref> The first single off the album \"Who You Know\" was released on November 14, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/who-you-know-single/id937861329|title=iTunes - Music - Who You Know - Single by Derek Minor|work=iTunes}}</ref> The second single \"Party People\" featuring Social Club was released on December 9, 2014. ''Empire'' was released on January 27, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/empire/id945090463|title=iTunes - Music - Empire by Derek Minor|work=iTunes}}</ref> The album debuted at No. 54 on the ''Billboard'' 200.\n\nOn July 29, 2016, he announced that he would be releasing his sixth studio album, ''Reflection'', on October 14, 2016. A few days later he released a free EP, ''1014'', to those who pre-ordered the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newreleasetoday.com/news_detail.php?newsid=1683 |title=Derek Minor Releases Free '1014' EP |publisher=Newreleasetoday.com |date=July 29, 2016 |accessdate=October 29, 2016}}</ref> ''Reflection'' debuted at No. 7 on the Billboard [[Christian Albums]] chart, No. 5 on the [[Rap Albums]] chart, and No. 15 on the [[Independent Albums]] chart. His music video for ''Reflection'' album cut \"Until I'm Gone\" featuring B.J. the Chicago Kid premiered on Billboard.com.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/7525612/derek-minor-until-im-gone-video-bj-the-chicago-kid|title=Derek Minor Debuts Soulful 'Until I'm Gone' Video Feat. BJ The Chicago Kid: Premiere|work=Billboard|access-date=July 4, 2017}}</ref> The visual for \"Look at Me Now\" premiered on BET.com.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bet.com/video/bet-gospel/2016/exclusives/world-premiere-derek-minor-look-at-me-now.html|title=BET Gospel: World Premiere {{!}} Derek Minor \u2013 \u2018Look at Me Now\u2019|website=BET.com|access-date=July 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, his song \"Change the World\" featuring Hollyn reached No. 1 on Billboard's Hot AC/CHR chart.<ref name=\"Sarachik\" /> That same month, Minor embarked on the Rock and Worship Roadshow with Steven Curtis Chapman, Francesca Battistelli, Rend Collective, Passion and others.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://todayschristianent.com/tour-news-compassion-international-announces-9th-annual-rock-worship-roadshow/|title=Tour News: Compassion International Announces The 9th Annual Rock & Worship Roadshow - Today's Christian Entertainment|website=todayschristianent.com|access-date=July 4, 2017}}</ref> In the spring of 2017, broadcast of the We Love Christian Music Awards, Minor's ''Reflection'' album received the Rap/Urban Album of the Year honor.<ref>{{Citation|last=We Love Christian Music Awards|title=Derek Minor Wins Rap/Urban Album of the Year - 5th Annual WLAs (Seg 11 of 20)|date=May 28, 2017|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?list=PLdQvHg0R72_KFqTdMaxLmSBwV6LM7GMgC&v=Myjg_ff1Fek|accessdate=July 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn mid-2017, Minor premiered the stand-alone single \"Fresh Prince\" on HipHopSince1987.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://hiphopsince1987.com/2017/music/derek-minor-fresh-prince/|title=Derek Minor \u2013 Fresh Prince (Premiere)|date=June 30, 2017|work=Home of Hip Hop Videos & Rap Music, News, Video, Mixtapes & more|access-date=July 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\nHis next installment of music was the ''Up and Away'' series, which featured four projects: the EPs ''Your Soul Must Fly'' and ''High Above'', which were released in the late 2017, and two full-length albums ''The Trap'' and ''By Any Means'', which were released in 2018. The titles form a sentence, \"Your soul must fly high above the trap by any means\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wadeoradio.com/derek-minor-reveals-the-titles-for-parts-3-4-of-up-and-away-series/|title=Derek Minor Reveals the Titles for Parts 3 & 4 of 'Up and Away' Series {{!}} Wade-O Radio|website=wadeoradio.com|access-date=April 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n{{Main|Derek Minor discography}}\n<!--Please only list studio albums here. EPs, Mix Tapes and other works go into the discography article-->\n* ''[[The Blackout (album)|The Blackout]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[Redemption (Derek Minor album)|Redemption]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Dying to Live (Derek Minor album)|Dying to Live]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[Minorville (album)|Minorville]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[Empire (Derek Minor album)|Empire]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Reflection (Derek Minor album)|Reflection]]'' (2016)\n* ''The Trap'' (2018)\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n=== Short films ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Film\n! Director\n! Producer\n! Writer\n! Actor\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2010<ref name=redemptionfilm />\n| ''Redemption''\n| {{n/a}}\n| {{n/a}}\n| {{yes}}<ref name=redemptionfilm />\n| {{yes}}<ref name=redemptionfilm />\n| [[Web film]]\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''Welcome to the Family Documentary''\n| {{no}}\n| {{n/a}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| [[Documentary film|Documentary]] web film\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''Everything Must Go''<ref name=everythingmustgo>{{cite web|title=Andy Mineo - Everything Must Go (@AndyMineo @reachrecords)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8qqnyC1c28c|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=April 9, 2013|author=Reach Records|date=April 9, 2013}}</ref>\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| Documentary web film\n|}\n\n=== Webseries ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Program\n! Credit\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''Dying to Live''\n| Writer, actor\n| 3-part promotional series\n|}\n\n=== Video games ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| 2011 || ''Altered Pro'' || Himself || [[Voice acting|Voice]]-only\n|}\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\nGMA Dove Awards\n\nA Dove Award is an accolade by the Gospel Music Association (GMA) of the United States to recognize outstanding achievement in the [[Christian music industry]]. \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Nominee/work\n!Award\n!Result\n!Ref.\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2014\n|\"Dear Mr. Christian\" (featuring [[Dee-1]] and [[Lecrae]])\n|Rap/Hip Hop Recorded Song of the Year\n|Nominated\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.rapzilla.com/rz/news/38-backstage/8907-45th-dove-awards-2014-nominees|title=45th Dove Awards 2014 Nominees|last=Rood|first=Philip|work=Rapzilla.com|access-date=July 4, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Minorville (album)|Minorville]]''\n|Rap/Hip Hop Album of the Year\n|Won\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.rapzilla.com/rz/news/38-backstage/8907-45th-dove-awards-2014-nominees|title=45th Dove Awards 2014 Nominees|last=Rood|first=Philip|work=Rapzilla.com|access-date=July 4, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|2016\n|\"[[No quiero escuchar|No Quit\"]]\n|Rap/Hip Hop Recorded Song of the Year\n|Nominated\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://doveawards.com/awards/2015-winners/|title=2015 Winners {{!}} The 48th Annual GMA Dove Awards|website=doveawards.com|access-date=July 4, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180927030315/http://doveawards.com/awards/2015-winners/|archive-date=September 27, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|}\n\nGrammy Awards\n\nA Grammy Award is an honor awarded by [[The Recording Academy]] to recognize outstanding achievement in the mainly English-language [[music industry]]. \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Nominee/work\n!Award\n!Result\n!Ref.\n|-\n|2013\n|''[[Gravity (Lecrae album)|Gravity]]'' (as producer)\n|[[Best Gospel Album]]\n|Won\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/awards/55th-annual-grammy-awards|title=55th Annual GRAMMY Awards|date=June 24, 2013|work=The Recording Academy|access-date=July 4, 2017}}</ref>\n|}\nStellar Awards\n\n'''The Stellar Awards''' is a Gospel Music Awards in the U.S., honoring Gospel Music artists, writers, and industry professionals.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Nominee/work\n!Award\n!Result\n!Ref.\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[Anomaly (Lecrae album)|Anomaly]]'' (as producer)\n|Rap Hip Hop Gospel CD of the Year\n|Won\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://rapzilla.com/rz/news/38-backstage/10497-lecrae-wins-2015-stellar-award-for-anomaly|title=Lecrae wins 2015 Stellar Award for 'Anomaly'|last=Daniels|first=David|work=Rapzilla.com|access-date=July 4, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[Empire (Derek Minor album)|Empire]]''\n|Rap Hip Hop Gospel CD of the Year\n|Won\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://jamthehype.com/derek-minor-wins-2016-stellar-award/|title=Derek Minor Wins 2016 Stellar Award|date=February 22, 2016|work=Jam the Hype|access-date=July 4, 2017}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Derek Minor|state=autocollapse}}\n{{116 Clique}}\n{{R.M.G.}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Minor, Derek}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American rappers]]\n[[Category:African-American Christians]]\n[[Category:African-American record producers]]\n[[Category:American hip hop record producers]]\n[[Category:Performers of Christian hip hop music]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Middle Tennessee State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:African-American male actors]]\n[[Category:African-American screenwriters]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Reach Records artists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American rappers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Derek Minor\n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Derek Laurence Johnson, Jr.\n| alias            = PRo\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1984|12|16}}\n| birth_place      = [[Pontiac, Michigan]]\n| origin           = [[Middle Tennessee]], United States\n| genre            = [[Christian hip hop]]\n| occupation       = [[Rapper]], [[record producer]], [[actor]], [[screenwriter]]\n| instrument       = \n| years_active     = 2006\u2013present\n| label            = Reflection, [[Reach Records|Reach]], Scyon\n| associated_acts  = [[116 Clique]], Andal\u00e9, [[Canon (rapper)|Canon]], [[Chad Jones (rapper)|Chad Jones]], [[Chris Cobbins]], DJ Wade O, [[Json (rapper)|Json]], [[Lecrae]], [[R.M.G.]], [[Tony Tillman]]\n| website          = {{URL|derekminor.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Derek Johnson, Jr.''', better known by his stage name '''Derek Minor''' and former stage name '''PRo''', (born December 16, 1984) is an American [[Christian hip hop]] artist, [[record producer]], [[entrepreneur]], [[actor]], and [[screenwriter]]. He co-founded the hip-hop record label Reflection Music Group (RMG) with Doc Watson, and signed to [[Reach Records]] in a joint venture between the two labels in 2011. In 2012, Johnson announced that he had changed his stage name from Pro to Derek Minor. In 2014, he announced that as his two-album contract with Reach was complete, he would no longer be publishing releases through that label.\n\nHe is a founding member of the hip-hop group R.M.G. on Reflection, and was formerly a member of the Reach hip-hop collective [[116 Clique]]. Johnson has released six studio albums and six mixtapes as a solo artist, as well as one studio album each with the groups R.M.G. and 116 Clique. His second studio album, ''Redemption'', charted at No. 8 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' Gospel chart and No. 31 on the ''Billboard'' [[Christian Albums|Top Christian]] chart. His third studio album, ''Dying to Live'', debuted at No. 66 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], No. 1 on the Top Christian chart, No. 2 on the Gospel Albums chart, No. 7 on the Top [[Independent Albums]] chart, and No. 11 on the [[Rap Albums|Top Rap]] chart. His fourth album, ''Minorville'', released in 2013 debuted at No. 5 on Billboard's Rap Albums chart and No. 7 on the Top Christian chart. He partnered with Entertainment One to release his fifth album, ''Empire'', that debuted at No. 6 on the Billboard Rap Albums chart and No. 1 on the Top Christian chart. His sixth album, ''Reflection'', entered the Billboard Rap Albums chart at No. 5 and the Top Christian chart at No. 7. ''Reflection''<nowiki/>'s single \"Change the World\" featuring Hollyn reached No. 1 on Billboard's Hot AC/CHR chart.<ref name=\"Sarachik\">{{Cite news|url=http://rapzilla.com/rz/news/38-backstage/14977-derek-minor-s-change-the-world-ft-hollyn-hits-no-1-on-billboard-chart|title=Derek Minor's 'Change the World' ft. Hollyn Hits No. 1 on Billboard Chart|last=Sarachik|first=Justin|work=Rapzilla.com|access-date=July 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\nJohnson's film and television work includes the three-part [[webseries]] \"Dying to Live\" and the short documentary films ''Redemption'' and ''Welcome to the Family Documentary''. Johnson also was featured as the title character in the video game ''Altered Pro'', released under Reach Records.\n\n== Life and career ==\n\n=== Early ===\n\nDerek Johnson, Jr. was born in [[Pontiac, Michigan]] on December 16, 1984, but at a young age relocated to [[Middle Tennessee]] with his mother.<ref name=bio>{{cite web|title=Derek Minor (PRo)|url=http://reflectionmusicgroup.com/artists/derek-minor-pro|work=Artists|publisher=Reflection Music Group|accessdate=January 13, 2013|author=Reflection Music Group|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130115080720/http://reflectionmusicgroup.com/artists/derek-minor-pro|archive-date=January 15, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=fbpro>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/thederekminor/posts/10152484947544128|title=Thanks to everyone for the birthday...|author=PRo|date=December 16, 2013|publisher=Derek Minor|accessdate=May 18, 2014}}</ref> His relationship with his birth father was distant, and his relationship with his stepfather became increasingly tense.<ref name=bio /> Furthermore, Johnson's stepfather was a drug user while his mother was a strict, devout Christian with a rigorous work schedule and homelife. Johnson decided to help his mother by becoming rich through either education or music.<ref name=bio />\n\nJohnson had grown up with music, as Gospel songs were played at his house and his mother was in choir and sang around the city.<ref name=bio /> Johnson's father, a [[jazz]] musician, provided the inspiration for him to go into music. When Johnson was 12, he visited his father in the summer and started rapping about God and adolescence, with his father producing beats with an [[Ensoniq ASR-10]].<ref name=bio /> Johnson was also introduced to [[DJ Quik]] that summer, and went home with piles of [[Compact Cassette|tape]]s.<ref name=bio />\n\nAfter visiting to [[Middle Tennessee State University]] at age 15, Johnson decided to enroll in the music program there and make his ambitions a reality.<ref name=bio /> His mother helped him by buying him production equipment, and by the time he entered college, Johnson was in a rap duo and got a job to pay for studio time.<ref name=bio /> He graduated in 2006 with a bachelor's degree in Recording Industry Management.<ref name=dasouthinterview>{{cite web|title=Pro - The Making of a Professional|url=http://ns1.dasouth.com/features/interviews/623-pro-the-making-of-a-professional|work=DaSouth.com|accessdate=January 13, 2013|author=Zee|date=February 16, 2009|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130215192525/http://ns1.dasouth.com/features/interviews/623-pro-the-making-of-a-professional|archive-date=February 15, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Johnson recalls that before he turned 21 he used a bunk bed as a mic stand and signed a record deal with an independent label.<ref name=bio /> While on the label, he released a mix tape, but the company folded and his life took a turn for the worse.<ref name=bio /> Removed from his strict home environment, Johnson rebelled. He pursued music, women and money until '\"the season of death\"' shook up his life.<ref name=bio /> Within a short time span, Johnson lost his grandfather, grandmother and godmother. This loss sparked a realization of the fleeting nature of life, and Johnson decided to dedicate his life and talents to God.<ref name=bio />\n\n=== Reflection Music Group (2008\u20132010) ===\n\nJohnson co-founded Reflection Music Group, then-called Christ Like Entertainment, with his friend Doc Watson, who he met while working on a second mixtape, ''Transformers''.<ref name=bio /><ref name=dasouthinterview /> Johnson released his debut album ''The Blackout'' in 2008.<ref name=bio /> According to DaSouth.com, the \"braggidocious, swagtastic approach\" that Johnson took on the album met with controversy in the Christian hip hop community.<ref name=dasouthredemption>{{cite web|last=Hill|first=Kellus|title=Review: PRo \"Redemption\"|url=http://www.dasouth.com/reviews/3596-review-pro-qredemptionq|work=DaSouth.com|accessdate=January 14, 2013|date=July 9, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101227145631/http://www.dasouth.com/reviews/3596-review-pro-qredemptionq|archive-date=December 27, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> Johnson took a break from rapping, and was challenged and influenced by a new friend, BJ, that he met at his new church in [[Memphis, Tennessee]], and was further challenged by Christian hip-hop artist [[Lecrae]].<ref name=bio /><ref name=redemptionfilm>{{cite web|title=Pro Presents Redemption (The Short Film) (@mynameispro @reachrecords)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=32laK9znEoU|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=January 13, 2013|format=Web/Video|date=February 1, 2011}}</ref> Johnson reflected that his first album was mostly about haters and how good an emcee he was, and was convinced that it should have been more focused on God.<ref name=redemptionfilm /> In January 2010, Johnson released the mixtape ''PSA'', which he considers his first full-length installment of \"mature\" Christian music.<ref name=bio /> That year, Johnson went on the \"Urban Missionary Tour\" with Thi'sl, k-Drama, and J'Son, including a stop in the [[United Kingdom]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Rood|first=Philip|title=Urban Missionary Tour 2010 feat. Thi'sl, k-Drama, J'Son, Pro|url=http://www.rapzilla.com/rz/news/38-backstage/2025-urban-missionary-tour-2010-feat-thisl-k-drama-json-pro|work=[[Rapzilla]]|publisher=Philip Rood and Chad Horton|accessdate=January 14, 2013|date=April 14, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=London Rap Concert featuring DJ Morphiziz, J'Son, K-Drama, Pro & Thi'sl, Sunday Sept. 26th|url=http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/4221-london-rap-concert-featuring-dj-morphiziz-json-k-drama-pro-a-thisl-sunday-sept-26th|work=DaSouth.com|accessdate=January 14, 2013|author=DJ D-Lite|date=September 24, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101229055751/http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/4221-london-rap-concert-featuring-dj-morphiziz-json-k-drama-pro-a-thisl-sunday-sept-26th|archive-date=December 29, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> In preparation for his second studio album, ''Redemption'', Johnson wrote a short autobiographical film entitled \"Redemption\", and it was released as a [[web film]] in May.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rood|first=Philip|title=PRo presents Redemption - the short film|url=http://rapzilla.com/rz/news/38-backstage/2175-pro-presents-redemption-the-short-film|work=[[Rapzilla]]|publisher=Philip Rood and Chad Horton|accessdate=January 14, 2013|date=June 2, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Video: PRo presents \"Redemption\" 20-minute short film|url=http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/3337-video-pro-presents-qredemptionq-20-minute-short-film|work=Dasouth.com|accessdate=January 14, 2013|author=DaSouth.com|date=May 29, 2010|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130215191901/http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/3337-video-pro-presents-qredemptionq-20-minute-short-film|archive-date=February 15, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> The album ''Redemption'' was released July 13, 2010, and peaked at No. 8 on the ''Billboard'' Top Gospel Albums and No. 31 on the [[Top Christian Albums]] charts.<ref name=redemptionchart>{{cite web|title=Gospel Albums|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2010-07-31/gospel-albums|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Nielsen Business Media]]|accessdate=January 13, 2013|date=July 31, 2010}}</ref> This release was followed by an announcement in August that Johnson would be featured as a special guest on the [[116 Clique]] \"Unashamed 2010\" tour, which ran October through November.<ref>{{cite web|title=Reach Records announces Unashamed 2010: The Movement Tour - Now booking|url=http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/3748-reach-records-announces-unashamed-2010-the-movement-tour-now-booking|work=DaSouth.com|accessdate=January 14, 2013|author=DaSouth.com|date=August 5, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708233730/http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/3748-reach-records-announces-unashamed-2010-the-movement-tour-now-booking|archivedate=July 8, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Also in August, Johnson received a write-up in ''[[Jet (magazine)|Jet]]'' and was featured on the front page of the magazine's website.<ref>{{cite web|last=Horton|first=Chad|title=PRo Featured in JET Magazine|url=http://rapzilla.com/rz/news/38-backstage/2354-pro-featured-in-jet-magazine|work=[[Rapzilla]]|publisher=Philip Rood and Chad Horton|accessdate=January 14, 2013|date=August 10, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=JET features PRo on site with major write-up|url=http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/3764-jet-features-pro-on-site-with-major-write-up|work=DaSouth.com|accessdate=January 14, 2013|date=August 10, 2010|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130215235601/http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/3764-jet-features-pro-on-site-with-major-write-up|archive-date=February 15, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== Reach Records and name change (2011\u20132013) ===\n\nOn January 25, 2011, [[Reach Records]] announced that it had signed Johnson as a joint venture with Reflection Music Group, and the same day Johnson released the single \"116\", featuring [[KB (rapper)|KB]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Rood|first=Philip|title=Reach Records signs PRo|url=http://rapzilla.com/rz/news/38-backstage/2834-reach-records-signs-pro|work=[[Rapzilla]]|publisher=Philip Rood and Chad Horton|accessdate=January 14, 2013|date=January 25, 2011}}</ref> On March 8, Johnson released the mixtape ''PSA: Vol. 2''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wilson|first=Marcel|title=Free Download: Reach Records releases PRo's mixtape \"PSA: Volume 2\"|url=http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/5496-free-download-reach-records-releases-pros-mixtape-qpsa-volume-2q|work=DaSouth.com|accessdate=January 14, 2013|date=March 8, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316051419/http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/5496-free-download-reach-records-releases-pros-mixtape-qpsa-volume-2q|archive-date=March 16, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> On July 10, Johnson announced the launch of a three-part [[webseries]] \"Dying to Live\" to promote his upcoming studio album of the same name.<ref>{{cite web|title=Video: PRo launching online mini series July 12th|url=http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/6414-video-pro-launching-online-mini-series-july-12th|work=DaSouth.com|accessdate=January 14, 2013|author=DaSouth.com|date=July 10, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712202454/http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/6414-video-pro-launching-online-mini-series-july-12th|archive-date=July 12, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> In the months of August and October, Pro toured with 116 Clique as part of the group's \"Man Up\" campaign.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rood|first=Philip|title=Reach Records' Upcoming Tours, Rehab, Man Up, & Unashamed Africa|url=http://rapzilla.com/rz/news/38-backstage/3372-reach-records-upcoming-tours-rehab-man-up-unashamed-africa|work=[[Rapzilla]]|publisher=Philip Rood and Chad Horton|accessdate=January 14, 2013|date=July 15, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Recap: Man Up Tour \u2013 Houston|url=http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/7277-recap-man-up-tour-houston|work=DaSouth.com|accessdate=January 14, 2013|author=Sketch the Journalist|date=November 4, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120106083010/http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/7277-recap-man-up-tour-houston|archive-date=January 6, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Man Up Tour <nowiki>|| 10.22.11 ||</nowiki> Houston, TX|url=http://www.dasouth.com/manuphouston/|work=DaSouth.com|accessdate=January 14, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706235229/http://www.dasouth.com/manuphouston/|archive-date=July 6, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> On August 9, Reach Records released the [[web game]] ''Altered Pro'', a zombie game based off the [[Sega]] classic ''[[Altered Beast]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rood|first=Philip|title=PRo \"Altered Pro\" - Video Game|url=http://www.rapzilla.com/rz/news/38-backstage/3448-altered-pro-video-game|work=[[Rapzilla]]|publisher=Philip Rood and Chad Horton|accessdate=January 14, 2013|date=August 9, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Reach Records releases online video game Altered PRo - PLAY NOW!|url=http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/6590-reach-records-releases-online-video-game-altered-pro-play-now|work=DaSouth.com|accessdate=January 14, 2013|author=DaSouth.com|date=August 9, 2011|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130215200356/http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/6590-reach-records-releases-online-video-game-altered-pro-play-now|archive-date=February 15, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> The full-length studio album, ''Dying to Live'', was released on August 23. The album debuted at No. 1 on the [[Christian Albums]] chart, No. 2 on the Gospel Albums chart, No. 7 on the [[Independent Albums]], No. 11 on the [[Rap Albums]] chart and No. 66 on the ''Billboard'' 200.<ref name=dietolivechart>{{cite web|title=Christian Albums|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2011-09-10/christian-albums|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Nielsen Business Media]]|accessdate=January 14, 2013|date=September 10, 2011}}</ref> The album was also the featured banner on the [[iTunes]] homepage as well in the Christian & Religious and Hip Hop/Rap departments.<ref>{{cite web|last=Horton|first=Chad|title=PRo 'Dying To Live' Featured Throughout iTunes|url=http://rapzilla.com/rz/news/38-backstage/3534-pro-dying-to-live-featured-throughout-itunes|work=[[Rapzilla]]|publisher=Philip Rood and Chad Horton|accessdate=January 14, 2013|date=August 26, 2011}}</ref> In September, Johnson performed at the 2011 Flavor Fest, and on September 27, 2011, the album ''Man Up'' by 116 Clique was released.<ref>{{cite web|last=Solis|first=Steven|title=Flavor Fest 2011 National Artists Lineup|url=http://www.rapzilla.com/rz/news/38-backstage/3617-flavor-fest-2011-national-artists-lineup|work=[[Rapzilla]]|publisher=Philip Rood and Chad Horton|accessdate=January 14, 2013|date=September 13, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Jeffries|first=David|title=Man Up|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/man-up-mw0002242981|work=[[Allmusic]]|publisher=[[Rovi Corporation]]|accessdate=January 14, 2013}}</ref> In October, Johnson was included with [[Bryan Winchester|Braille]] and 116 Clique as some of the artists in the iTunes Indie Spotlight for hip hop music.<ref>{{cite web|last=Horton|first=Chad|title=iTunes Indie Spotlight: Hip-Hop - October 2011 Features 116, PRo, & Braille|url=http://rapzilla.com/rz/news/38-backstage/3760-itunes-indie-spotlight-hip-hop-october-2011-features-116-pro-a-braille|work=[[Rapzilla]]|publisher=Philip Rood and Chad Horton|accessdate=January 14, 2013|date=October 29, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2012, Reflection Music Group announced the formation of the hip-hop group R.M.G., consisting of the artists Pro, Canon, Tony Tillman (formerly known as Brothatone), and Chad Jones (formerly known as Conviction).<ref name=r.m.g.>{{cite web|last=Horton|first=Chad|title=Reflection Music Group Signees R.M.G. Get \"Geeked Up\"|url=http://allhiphop.com/2012/02/23/reach-records-signees-r-m-g-get-geeked-up/|work=[[AllHipHop]]|publisher=AHH Holdings LLC|accessdate=January 14, 2013|date=February 23, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"geeked up\">{{cite web|last=Horton|first=Chad|title=RMG (PRo, Canon, Brothatone, Chad Jones) - Geeked Up|url=http://www.rapzilla.com/rz/news/38-backstage/4208-rmg-pro-canon-brothatone-chad-jones-geeked-up|work=[[Rapzilla]]|publisher=Philip Rood and Chad Horton|accessdate=January 14, 2013|date=February 18, 2012}}</ref> With this announcement came the release of R.M.G.'s debut single \"Geeked Up\" on February 21.<ref name=r.m.g. /><ref name=\"geeked up\" /> On March 21, the group released an online documentary film entitled \"Welcome to the Family Documentary\" in preparation for its debut album ''Welcome to the Family'', which was released March 27.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mini Doc: RMG - Welcome to the Family|url=http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/8880-video-rmg-qwelcome-to-the-familyq-documentary|work=DaSouth.com|accessdate=January 14, 2013|author=DaSouth.com|date=March 21, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120525170800/http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/8880-video-rmg-qwelcome-to-the-familyq-documentary|archive-date=May 25, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome to the Family (feat. Pro, Canon, Tony Tillman & Chad Jones) by R.M.G|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/welcome-to-family-feat.-pro/id509557508|publisher=[[iTunes]]|accessdate=January 14, 2013|author=R.M.G.}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, 2012, Johnson performed at the 2012 [[South by Southwest]] festival as part of the Reach Records showcase along with Lecrae, [[Trip Lee]], [[Tedashii]], [[Andy Mineo]], and KB.<ref>{{cite web|title=Christian rap returns to SXSW in 2012: Reach Records & DaSouth.com showcases|url=http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/8272-christian-rap-returns-to-sxsw-in-2012-reach-records-a-dasouthcom-showcases|work=DaSouth.com|accessdate=January 14, 2013|author=Sketch the Journalist|date=February 7, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130117175406/http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/8272-christian-rap-returns-to-sxsw-in-2012-reach-records-a-dasouthcom-showcases|archive-date=January 17, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> On August 6, 2012, Johnson revealed the cover art for his upcoming mixtape, ''PSA Vol. 3: Who Is Derek Minor?'', and with it revealed that he had changed his stage name from Pro to Derek Minor.<ref>{{cite web|last=Solis|first=Steven|title=Derek Minor fka PRo 'PSA Vol. 3' Cover Revealed|url=http://rapzilla.com/rz/news/38-backstage/4853-derek-minor-fka-pro-psa-vol-3-cover-revealed|work=[[Rapzilla]]|publisher=Philip Rood and Chad Horton|accessdate=January 14, 2013|date=August 6, 2012}}</ref> From October through November, Johnson toured with 116 Clique on the \"Unashamed 2012: Come Alive\" tour.<ref>{{cite web|last=Horton|first=Chad|title=Reach Records Artists Come Alive Via The \"Unashamed Tour 2012\"|url=http://allhiphop.com/2012/07/08/reach-records-artists-come-alive-via-the-unashamed-tour-2012/|work=[[AllHipHop]]|publisher=AHH Holdings|accessdate=January 14, 2013|date=July 8, 2012}}</ref> On November 8, 2012, South by Southwest announced that Reach Records would again hold a showcase with its entire roster, including Derek Minor, in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lecrae and other Reach Booking artists among first acts announced for SXSW 2013|url=http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/10394-lecrae-and-other-reach-booking-artists-among-first-acts-announced-for-sxsw-2013|work=DaSouth.com|accessdate=January 14, 2013|author=Sketch the Journalist|date=November 9, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130112180012/http://www.dasouth.com/news/24-news/10394-lecrae-and-other-reach-booking-artists-among-first-acts-announced-for-sxsw-2013|archive-date=January 12, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with [[Rapzilla]] on May 5, 2013, Kyle Dettman, video director for Reach Records, revealed that Reach Records is preparing promotional material for Derek Minor's upcoming album ''Minorville''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rood|first=Philip|title=Kyle Dettman Live Interview - Lecrae Confe$$ions Music Video|url=http://rapzilla.com/rz/features/interviews/6203-kyle-dettman-live-interview-reach-records-director-of-video|work=[[Rapzilla]]|publisher=Philip Rood and Chad Horton|accessdate=May 4, 2013|format=Video/Web|date=May 2, 2013}}</ref> On June 6, 2013, Minor released a lyric video for a single from ''Minorville'', \"Dear Mr. Christian\" featuring [[Dee-1]] and Lecrae, followed by an actual release of the single the next day.<ref>{{cite web|title=\nDerek Minor - Dear Mr. Christian, (Lyric Video) ft. Dee-1 & Lecrae|url=http://rapzilla.com/rz/video-page2/6414-derek-minor-dear-mr-christian-lyric-video-ft-dee-1-a-lecrae|work=[[Rapzilla]]|publisher=Philip Rood and Chad Horton|accessdate=July 3, 2013|format=Video/Web|date=June 6, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Derek Minor - Dear Mr. Christian, ft. Dee-1 & Lecrae|url=http://www.rapzilla.com/rz/music/6440-derek-minor-dear-mr-christian|work=[[Rapzilla]]|publisher=Philip Rood and Chad Horton|accessdate=June 11, 2013|date=May 2, 2013}}</ref> Later, on June 21, Reach Records released the album cover for ''Minorville'' by a video showing the album cover making-process, and also announced the release date, September 10, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|last=Solis|first=Steven|title=Derek Minor - In God We Trust ft. Thi'sl|url=http://rapzilla.com/rz/video-page2/6562-derek-minor-in-god-we-trust-ft-thisl|work=[[Rapzilla]]|publisher=Philip Rood and Chad Horton|accessdate=July 3, 2013|format=Web/Video|date=July 2, 2013}}</ref> The promotion for the album continued on July 2, when Minor dropped a teaser video for a track called \"In God We Trust\" featuring Thi'sl.<ref>{{cite web|title=Derek Minor 'Minorville' Album Cover & Release Date Revealed|url=http://rapzilla.com/rz/news/38-backstage/6502-derek-minor-minorville-album-cover-a-release-date-revealed|work=[[Rapzilla]]|publisher=Philip Rood and Chad Horton|accessdate=July 3, 2013|date=June 20, 2013}}</ref> The album debuted at No. 40 on the ''Billboard'' 200, No. 1 on the Gospel Albums Chart, No. 2 on the Christian Albums Chart, No. 6 on the Independent Albums Chart and No. 6 on the Rap Albums Chart, making it his best chart performing album to date.\n\nOn March 18, 2014, [[Rapzilla]] announced that Derek Minor had parted ways with Reach Records, as his two-album contract with Reach had expired.<ref name=leavingreach >{{cite web|url = http://www.rapzilla.com/rz/news/1/7996|title = Derek Minor No Longer With Reach Records|date = March 18, 2014|accessdate = June 9, 2014|website = [[Rapzilla]]|publisher = Philip Rood and Chad Horton|last = Nyamu|first = Vincent}}</ref> Minor was quoted, \"I've grown as an artist, business owner and a man. The beauty of the relationship we've established is that business wasn't its primary agenda and I'm excited to see what the future holds for both RMG and Reach.\"<ref name=leavingreach />\n\n=== Independent route and distribution deals (2014\u2013present) ===\n{{Prose|section|date=July 2017}}\nIn October 2014 at the [[Dove Awards]] he announced that his fifth album will be titled ''Empire'' and will be released in the first quarter of 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rapzilla.com/rz/videos/live/9264-video-derek-minor-reveals-new-album-title|title=Video: Derek Minor Reveals New Album 'Empire'|author=Roman Flores|publisher=|accessdate=October 20, 2014}}</ref> On October 22, 2014, it was announced that Derek Minor had signed a distribution deal with [[Entertainment One]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christianpost.com/news/lecraes-former-label-mate-derek-minor-signs-to-popular-secular-music-company-eone-128491/|title=Lecrae's Former Label-Mate Derek Minor Signs to Popular Secular Music Company eOne|work=Christian Post}}</ref> The first single off the album \"Who You Know\" was released on November 14, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/who-you-know-single/id937861329|title=iTunes - Music - Who You Know - Single by Derek Minor|work=iTunes}}</ref> The second single \"Party People\" featuring Social Club was released on December 9, 2014. ''Empire'' was released on January 27, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/empire/id945090463|title=iTunes - Music - Empire by Derek Minor|work=iTunes}}</ref> The album debuted at No. 54 on the ''Billboard'' 200.\n\nOn July 29, 2016, he announced that he would be releasing his sixth studio album, ''Reflection'', on October 14, 2016. A few days later he released a free EP, ''1014'', to those who pre-ordered the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newreleasetoday.com/news_detail.php?newsid=1683 |title=Derek Minor Releases Free '1014' EP |publisher=Newreleasetoday.com |date=July 29, 2016 |accessdate=October 29, 2016}}</ref> ''Reflection'' debuted at No. 7 on the Billboard [[Christian Albums]] chart, No. 5 on the [[Rap Albums]] chart, and No. 15 on the [[Independent Albums]] chart. His music video for ''Reflection'' album cut \"Until I'm Gone\" featuring B.J. the Chicago Kid premiered on Billboard.com.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/7525612/derek-minor-until-im-gone-video-bj-the-chicago-kid|title=Derek Minor Debuts Soulful 'Until I'm Gone' Video Feat. BJ The Chicago Kid: Premiere|work=Billboard|access-date=July 4, 2017}}</ref> The visual for \"Look at Me Now\" premiered on BET.com.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bet.com/video/bet-gospel/2016/exclusives/world-premiere-derek-minor-look-at-me-now.html|title=BET Gospel: World Premiere {{!}} Derek Minor \u2013 \u2018Look at Me Now\u2019|website=BET.com|access-date=July 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, his song \"Change the World\" featuring Hollyn reached No. 1 on Billboard's Hot AC/CHR chart.<ref name=\"Sarachik\" /> That same month, Minor embarked on the Rock and Worship Roadshow with Steven Curtis Chapman, Francesca Battistelli, Rend Collective, Passion and others.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://todayschristianent.com/tour-news-compassion-international-announces-9th-annual-rock-worship-roadshow/|title=Tour News: Compassion International Announces The 9th Annual Rock & Worship Roadshow - Today's Christian Entertainment|website=todayschristianent.com|access-date=July 4, 2017}}</ref> In the spring of 2017, broadcast of the We Love Christian Music Awards, Minor's ''Reflection'' album received the Rap/Urban Album of the Year honor.<ref>{{Citation|last=We Love Christian Music Awards|title=Derek Minor Wins Rap/Urban Album of the Year - 5th Annual WLAs (Seg 11 of 20)|date=May 28, 2017|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?list=PLdQvHg0R72_KFqTdMaxLmSBwV6LM7GMgC&v=Myjg_ff1Fek|accessdate=July 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn mid-2017, Minor premiered the stand-alone single \"Fresh Prince\" on HipHopSince1987.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://hiphopsince1987.com/2017/music/derek-minor-fresh-prince/|title=Derek Minor \u2013 Fresh Prince (Premiere)|date=June 30, 2017|work=Home of Hip Hop Videos & Rap Music, News, Video, Mixtapes & more|access-date=July 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\nHis next installment of music was the ''Up and Away'' series, which featured four projects: the EPs ''Your Soul Must Fly'' and ''High Above'', which were released in the late 2017, and two full-length albums ''The Trap'' and ''By Any Means'', which were released in 2018. The titles form a sentence, \"Your soul must fly high above the trap by any means\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wadeoradio.com/derek-minor-reveals-the-titles-for-parts-3-4-of-up-and-away-series/|title=Derek Minor Reveals the Titles for Parts 3 & 4 of 'Up and Away' Series {{!}} Wade-O Radio|website=wadeoradio.com|access-date=April 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n{{Main|Derek Minor discography}}\n<!--Please only list studio albums here. EPs, Mix Tapes and other works go into the discography article-->\n* ''[[The Blackout (album)|The Blackout]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[Redemption (Derek Minor album)|Redemption]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Dying to Live (Derek Minor album)|Dying to Live]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[Minorville (album)|Minorville]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[Empire (Derek Minor album)|Empire]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Reflection (Derek Minor album)|Reflection]]'' (2016)\n* ''The Trap'' (2018)\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n=== Short films ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Film\n! Director\n! Producer\n! Writer\n! Actor\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2010<ref name=redemptionfilm />\n| ''Redemption''\n| {{n/a}}\n| {{n/a}}\n| {{yes}}<ref name=redemptionfilm />\n| {{yes}}<ref name=redemptionfilm />\n| [[Web film]]\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''Welcome to the Family Documentary''\n| {{no}}\n| {{n/a}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| [[Documentary film|Documentary]] web film\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''Everything Must Go''<ref name=everythingmustgo>{{cite web|title=Andy Mineo - Everything Must Go (@AndyMineo @reachrecords)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8qqnyC1c28c|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=April 9, 2013|author=Reach Records|date=April 9, 2013}}</ref>\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| Documentary web film\n|}\n\n=== Webseries ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Program\n! Credit\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''Dying to Live''\n| Writer, actor\n| 3-part promotional series\n|}\n\n=== Video games ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| 2011 || ''Altered Pro'' || Himself || [[Voice acting|Voice]]-only\n|}\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\nGMA Dove Awards\n\nA Dove Award is an accolade by the [[Gospel Music Association]] (GMA) of the United States to recognize outstanding achievement in the [[Christian music industry]]. \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Nominee/work\n!Award\n!Result\n!Ref.\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2014\n|\"Dear Mr. Christian\" (featuring [[Dee-1]] and [[Lecrae]])\n|Rap/Hip Hop Recorded Song of the Year\n|Nominated\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.rapzilla.com/rz/news/38-backstage/8907-45th-dove-awards-2014-nominees|title=45th Dove Awards 2014 Nominees|last=Rood|first=Philip|work=Rapzilla.com|access-date=July 4, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Minorville (album)|Minorville]]''\n|Rap/Hip Hop Album of the Year\n|Won\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.rapzilla.com/rz/news/38-backstage/8907-45th-dove-awards-2014-nominees|title=45th Dove Awards 2014 Nominees|last=Rood|first=Philip|work=Rapzilla.com|access-date=July 4, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|2016\n|\"[[No quiero escuchar|No Quit\"]]\n|Rap/Hip Hop Recorded Song of the Year\n|Nominated\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://doveawards.com/awards/2015-winners/|title=2015 Winners {{!}} The 48th Annual GMA Dove Awards|website=doveawards.com|access-date=July 4, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180927030315/http://doveawards.com/awards/2015-winners/|archive-date=September 27, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|}\n\nGrammy Awards\n\nA Grammy Award is an honor awarded by [[The Recording Academy]] to recognize outstanding achievement in the mainly English-language [[music industry]]. \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Nominee/work\n!Award\n!Result\n!Ref.\n|-\n|2013\n|''[[Gravity (Lecrae album)|Gravity]]'' (as producer)\n|[[Best Gospel Album]]\n|Won\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/awards/55th-annual-grammy-awards|title=55th Annual GRAMMY Awards|date=June 24, 2013|work=The Recording Academy|access-date=July 4, 2017}}</ref>\n|}\nStellar Awards\n\n'''The Stellar Awards''' is a Gospel Music Awards in the U.S., honoring Gospel Music artists, writers, and industry professionals.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Nominee/work\n!Award\n!Result\n!Ref.\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[Anomaly (Lecrae album)|Anomaly]]'' (as producer)\n|Rap Hip Hop Gospel CD of the Year\n|Won\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://rapzilla.com/rz/news/38-backstage/10497-lecrae-wins-2015-stellar-award-for-anomaly|title=Lecrae wins 2015 Stellar Award for 'Anomaly'|last=Daniels|first=David|work=Rapzilla.com|access-date=July 4, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[Empire (Derek Minor album)|Empire]]''\n|Rap Hip Hop Gospel CD of the Year\n|Won\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://jamthehype.com/derek-minor-wins-2016-stellar-award/|title=Derek Minor Wins 2016 Stellar Award|date=February 22, 2016|work=Jam the Hype|access-date=July 4, 2017}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Derek Minor|state=autocollapse}}\n{{116 Clique}}\n{{R.M.G.}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Minor, Derek}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American rappers]]\n[[Category:African-American Christians]]\n[[Category:African-American record producers]]\n[[Category:American hip hop record producers]]\n[[Category:Performers of Christian hip hop music]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Middle Tennessee State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:African-American male actors]]\n[[Category:African-American screenwriters]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Reach Records artists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American rappers]]\n", "name_user": "Sandstein", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing link(s):Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/Gospel Music Associationclosed as delete (XFDcloser)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Derek_Minor"}
{"title_page": "List of awards and nominations received by MercyMe", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox musician awards\n| name       = MercyMe\n| image      = MercyMe Shelby.jpg\n| caption    = MercyMe performing on August 12, 2012 in [[Shelby, North Carolina]]\n\n| wins = 8\n| nominations = 27\n\n| customs = {{Infobox musician awards/customs|[[American Music Award]]s|2|4}}\n{{Infobox musician awards/customs|[[Billboard Music Award]]s|0|4}}\n{{Infobox musician awards/customs|[[GMA Dove Award|Dove Award]]s|6|28}}\n{{Infobox musician awards/customs|[[Grammy Award]]s|0|1}}\n}}\n\n[[MercyMe]] is an American [[contemporary Christian music]] band based in [[Greenville, Texas]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.timesrecordnews.com/news/2012/feb/10/mercyme-happily/|title=MercyMe, happily|last=Sweeten-Shults|first=Lana|date=February 10, 2012|work=[[Times Record News]]|publisher=[[E. W. Scripps Company|The E. W. Scripps Company]] |accessdate=May 2, 2014}}</ref> The band formed in 1994<ref name=\"MercyMe puts on a show\">{{cite web|url=http://newyork.mets.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20120810&content_id=36481848&vkey=news_nym&c_id=nym|title=MercyMe puts on a show for fans at Citi Field|last=Rosenbloom|first=Adam|date=October 10, 2012|publisher=[[New York Mets|Mets.com]]|accessdate=August 15, 2012}}</ref> and released six independent records from 1995-2000 before signing with [[INO Records]] and releasing their major-label debut, ''[[Almost There (album)|Almost There]]'', in 2001.<ref name=\"JFH\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jesusfreakhideout.com/artists/MercyMe.asp|title=MercyMe discography|publisher=Jesus Freak Hideout|accessdate=August 15, 2012}}</ref> They have since released six other studio albums as well as a holiday album.\n\nMercyMe has been awarded the [[American Music Award]] for [[American Music Award for Favorite Contemporary Inspirational Artist|Favorite Contemporary Inspirational Artist]] twice, in 2004 and 2010. At the [[35th GMA Dove Awards]], the band received the awards for Artist of the Year and Group of the Year, while their song \"[[Word of God Speak]]\" received the award for Pop/Contemporary Song of the Year; they also received that award in 2001 with their song \"[[I Can Only Imagine (MercyMe song)|I Can Only Imagine]]\". Their album \"[[Undone (MercyMe album)|Undone]]\" received the award for [[Dove Award for Pop/Contemporary Album of the Year]] in 2005. ''[[Coming Up to Breathe]]'' was nominated for the Dove Award for Pop/Contemporary Album of the Year as well as the [[Grammy Award for Best Pop/Contemporary Gospel Album]].\n\n==American Music Awards==\nThe [[American Music Awards]] are awarded for achievements in the American record industry. MercyMe has been nominated for four awards, winning two of them.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/2003/amas2.htm|title=31st American Music Awards |publisher=Rock on the Net|accessdate=August 15, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/2004/amas.htm|title=32nd American Music Awards |publisher=Rock on the Net|accessdate=August 15, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/2008/amas.htm|title=36th American Music Awards |publisher=Rock on the Net|accessdate=August 15, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/2010/amas.htm|title=38th American Music Awards |publisher=Rock on the Net|accessdate=August 15, 2012}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"65%\"\n|-\n!scope=col width=\"6%\"| Year\n!scope=col width=\"48%\"| Award\n!scope=col width=\"11%\"| Result\n|-\n| {{ama|2003 (November)}} || [[American Music Award for Favorite Contemporary Inspirational Artist|Contemporary Inspirational Artist]] || {{nom}}\n|-\n| {{ama|2004}} || Contemporary Inspirational Artist || {{won}}\n|-\n| {{ama|2008}} || Contemporary Inspirational Artist || {{nom}}\n|-\n| {{ama|2010}} || Contemporary Inspirational Artist || {{won}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Billboard Music Awards==\nThe [[Billboard Music Awards]] reflect ''Billboard'' \"chart rankings based on key fan interactions with music, including album sales and downloads, track downloads, radio airplay and touring as well as streaming and social interactions on Facebook, Twitter, Vevo, YouTube, Spotify and other popular online destinations for music\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/bbma/news/adele-rihanna-lil-wayne-lead-2012-billboard-music-awards-finalists|title=Adele, Rihanna, Lil Wayne Lead 2012 Billboard Music Awards Finalists|date=April 19, 2012|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=August 18, 2012}}</ref> MercyMe has been nominated for four awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/472097/full-2011-billboard-music-awards-finalists-list|title=Full 2011 Billboard Music Awards Finalists List|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=18 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/bbma/winners?page=4|title=2012 Billboard Music Awards Winners|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|pages=4|accessdate=August 18, 2012}}</ref>\n\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| [[2011 Billboard Music Awards|2011]] ||rowspan=\"1\"| ''[[The Generous Mr. Lovewell]]'' || Top Christian Album|| {{nom}}\n|-\n| &ndash; || Top Christian Artist|| {{nom}}\n|-\n| \"[[All of Creation (song)|All of Creation]]\" || Top Christian Song|| {{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| [[2012 Billboard Music Awards|2012]] ||rowspan=\"1\"| &ndash; || Top Christian Artist|| {{nom}}\n|-\n|colspan=\"10\" style=\"font-size:8pt\"| \"\u2014\" denotes nomination was not for a work\n{{end}}\n\n==Dove Awards==\nThe [[GMA Dove Award]]s honor artists in the genres of [[Christian music]] and [[Gospel music]]. MercyMe has been nominated for 18 awards, winning 6 of them.<ref name=\"Dove Award nominations and wins\">Sources:\n*{{cite web|title=Nominees for the 33rd Annual Dove Awards |publisher={{subst:^|<strong>}}Gospel Music Association{{subst:^|</strong>}} |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020408155924/http://doveawards.com/categories/ |archivedate=April 8, 2002 |accessdate=August 17, 2012 |url=http://doveawards.com/categories/ |url-status=dead }}\n*{{cite web|title=Nominees for the 34th Annual Dove Awards |publisher={{subst:^|<strong>}}Gospel Music Association{{subst:^|</strong>}} |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030618103534/http://www.doveawards.com/categories/nominees.cfm |archivedate=June 18, 2003 |accessdate=August 17, 2012 |url=http://www.doveawards.com/categories/nominees.cfm |url-status=dead }}\n*{{cite web|title=Nominees for the GMA's 35th Annual Music Awards |publisher={{subst:^|<strong>}}Gospel Music Association{{subst:^|</strong>}} |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040626085557/http://www.doveawards.com/categories/nominees.cfm |archivedate=June 26, 2004 |accessdate=August 16, 2012 |url=http://www.doveawards.com/categories/nominees.cfm |url-status=dead }}\n*{{cite web|title=Nominees for the 36th Annual GMA Music Awards |publisher={{subst:^|<strong>}}Gospel Music Association{{subst:^|</strong>}} |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050322094922/http://www.doveawards.com/categories/ |archivedate=March 22, 2005 |accessdate=August 16, 2012 |url=http://www.doveawards.com/categories/ |url-status=dead }}\n*{{cite web|title=Nominees for the 37th Annual GMA Music Awards |publisher={{subst:^|<strong>}}Gospel Music Association{{subst:^|</strong>}} |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060317022956/http://www.doveawards.com/categories/ |archivedate=March 17, 2006 |accessdate=August 16, 2012 |url=http://www.doveawards.com/categories/ |url-status=dead }}\n*{{cite web|title=Nominees for the 38th Annual GMA Dove Awards |publisher={{subst:^|<strong>}}Gospel Music Association{{subst:^|</strong>}} |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070315062926/http://www.doveawards.com/categories/ |archivedate=March 1