ards|2008]] ||rowspan=\"1\"| &ndash;  || Group of the Year || {{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[42nd GMA Dove Awards|2010]] ||rowspan=\"1\"| &ndash;  || Group of the Year || {{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| \"[[All of Creation (song)|All of Creation]]\" || Pop/Contemporary Recorded Song of the Year || {{nom}}\n|-\n|colspan=\"10\" style=\"font-size:8pt\"| \"\u2014\" denotes that award was not for a work\n{{end}}\n\n==Grammy Awards==\nThe [[Grammy Award]]s are awarded annually by [[National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences|The Recording Academy]] and honor \"artistic achievement, technical proficiency and overall excellence in the recording industry, without regard to album sales or chart position\".<ref name=\"Overview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.grammy.org/recording-academy|title=Overview|publisher=Grammy.org.[[National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences|The Recording Academy]]|accessdate=June 30, 2012}}</ref> MercyMe has been nominated for one award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.grammy.com/GRAMMY_Awards/49th_Show/list.aspx |title=49th Annual Grammy Awards Winners List |publisher=Grammy.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5mpxAz2DS?url=http://www2.grammy.com/GRAMMY_Awards/49th_Show/list.aspx |archivedate=January 17, 2010 |url-status=dead |accessdate=May 2, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| {{grammy|2007}} ||rowspan=\"1\"| ''[[Coming Up to Breathe]]'' || [[Grammy Award for Best Pop/Contemporary Gospel Album|Best Pop/Contemporary Gospel Album]] || {{nom}}\n|-\n{{end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{MercyMe}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of awards received by American musician|MercyMe]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox musician awards\n| name       = MercyMe\n| image      = MercyMe Shelby.jpg\n| caption    = MercyMe performing on August 12, 2012 in [[Shelby, North Carolina]]\n\n| wins = 8\n| nominations = 27\n\n| customs = {{Infobox musician awards/customs|[[American Music Award]]s|2|4}}\n{{Infobox musician awards/customs|[[Billboard Music Award]]s|0|4}}\n{{Infobox musician awards/customs|[[GMA Dove Award|Dove Award]]s|6|28}}\n{{Infobox musician awards/customs|[[Grammy Award]]s|0|1}}\n}}\n\n[[MercyMe]] is an American [[contemporary Christian music]] band based in [[Greenville, Texas]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.timesrecordnews.com/news/2012/feb/10/mercyme-happily/|title=MercyMe, happily|last=Sweeten-Shults|first=Lana|date=February 10, 2012|work=[[Times Record News]]|publisher=[[E. W. Scripps Company|The E. W. Scripps Company]] |accessdate=May 2, 2014}}</ref> The band formed in 1994<ref name=\"MercyMe puts on a show\">{{cite web|url=http://newyork.mets.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20120810&content_id=36481848&vkey=news_nym&c_id=nym|title=MercyMe puts on a show for fans at Citi Field|last=Rosenbloom|first=Adam|date=October 10, 2012|publisher=[[New York Mets|Mets.com]]|accessdate=August 15, 2012}}</ref> and released six independent records from 1995-2000 before signing with [[INO Records]] and releasing their major-label debut, ''[[Almost There (album)|Almost There]]'', in 2001.<ref name=\"JFH\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jesusfreakhideout.com/artists/MercyMe.asp|title=MercyMe discography|publisher=Jesus Freak Hideout|accessdate=August 15, 2012}}</ref> They have since released six other studio albums as well as a holiday album.\n\nMercyMe has been awarded the [[American Music Award]] for [[American Music Award for Favorite Contemporary Inspirational Artist|Favorite Contemporary Inspirational Artist]] twice, in 2004 and 2010. At the [[35th GMA Dove Awards]], the band received the awards for Artist of the Year and Group of the Year, while their song \"[[Word of God Speak]]\" received the award for Pop/Contemporary Song of the Year; they also received that award in 2001 with their song \"[[I Can Only Imagine (MercyMe song)|I Can Only Imagine]]\". Their album \"[[Undone (MercyMe album)|Undone]]\" received the award for [[Dove Award for Pop/Contemporary Album of the Year]] in 2005. ''[[Coming Up to Breathe]]'' was nominated for the Dove Award for Pop/Contemporary Album of the Year as well as the [[Grammy Award for Best Pop/Contemporary Gospel Album]].\n\n==American Music Awards==\nThe [[American Music Awards]] are awarded for achievements in the American record industry. MercyMe has been nominated for four awards, winning two of them.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/2003/amas2.htm|title=31st American Music Awards |publisher=Rock on the Net|accessdate=August 15, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/2004/amas.htm|title=32nd American Music Awards |publisher=Rock on the Net|accessdate=August 15, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/2008/amas.htm|title=36th American Music Awards |publisher=Rock on the Net|accessdate=August 15, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/2010/amas.htm|title=38th American Music Awards |publisher=Rock on the Net|accessdate=August 15, 2012}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"65%\"\n|-\n!scope=col width=\"6%\"| Year\n!scope=col width=\"48%\"| Award\n!scope=col width=\"11%\"| Result\n|-\n| {{ama|2003 (November)}} || [[American Music Award for Favorite Contemporary Inspirational Artist|Contemporary Inspirational Artist]] || {{nom}}\n|-\n| {{ama|2004}} || Contemporary Inspirational Artist || {{won}}\n|-\n| {{ama|2008}} || Contemporary Inspirational Artist || {{nom}}\n|-\n| {{ama|2010}} || Contemporary Inspirational Artist || {{won}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Billboard Music Awards==\nThe [[Billboard Music Awards]] reflect ''Billboard'' \"chart rankings based on key fan interactions with music, including album sales and downloads, track downloads, radio airplay and touring as well as streaming and social interactions on Facebook, Twitter, Vevo, YouTube, Spotify and other popular online destinations for music\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/bbma/news/adele-rihanna-lil-wayne-lead-2012-billboard-music-awards-finalists|title=Adele, Rihanna, Lil Wayne Lead 2012 Billboard Music Awards Finalists|date=April 19, 2012|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=August 18, 2012}}</ref> MercyMe has been nominated for four awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/472097/full-2011-billboard-music-awards-finalists-list|title=Full 2011 Billboard Music Awards Finalists List|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=18 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/bbma/winners?page=4|title=2012 Billboard Music Awards Winners|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|pages=4|accessdate=August 18, 2012}}</ref>\n\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| [[2011 Billboard Music Awards|2011]] ||rowspan=\"1\"| ''[[The Generous Mr. Lovewell]]'' || Top Christian Album|| {{nom}}\n|-\n| &ndash; || Top Christian Artist|| {{nom}}\n|-\n| \"[[All of Creation (song)|All of Creation]]\" || Top Christian Song|| {{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| [[2012 Billboard Music Awards|2012]] ||rowspan=\"1\"| &ndash; || Top Christian Artist|| {{nom}}\n|-\n|colspan=\"10\" style=\"font-size:8pt\"| \"\u2014\" denotes nomination was not for a work\n{{end}}\n\n==Dove Awards==\nThe [[GMA Dove Award]]s honor artists in the genres of [[Christian music]] and [[Gospel music]]. MercyMe has been nominated for 18 awards, winning 6 of them.<ref name=\"Dove Award nominations and wins\">Sources:\n*{{cite web|title=Nominees for the 33rd Annual Dove Awards |publisher=[[Gospel Music Association]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020408155924/http://doveawards.com/categories/ |archivedate=April 8, 2002 |accessdate=August 17, 2012 |url=http://doveawards.com/categories/ |url-status=dead }}\n*{{cite web|title=Nominees for the 34th Annual Dove Awards |publisher=[[Gospel Music Association]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030618103534/http://www.doveawards.com/categories/nominees.cfm |archivedate=June 18, 2003 |accessdate=August 17, 2012 |url=http://www.doveawards.com/categories/nominees.cfm |url-status=dead }}\n*{{cite web|title=Nominees for the GMA's 35th Annual Music Awards |publisher=[[Gospel Music Association]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040626085557/http://www.doveawards.com/categories/nominees.cfm |archivedate=June 26, 2004 |accessdate=August 16, 2012 |url=http://www.doveawards.com/categories/nominees.cfm |url-status=dead }}\n*{{cite web|title=Nominees for the 36th Annual GMA Music Awards |publisher=[[Gospel Music Association]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050322094922/http://www.doveawards.com/categories/ |archivedate=March 22, 2005 |accessdate=August 16, 2012 |url=http://www.doveawards.com/categories/ |url-status=dead }}\n*{{cite web|title=Nominees for the 37th Annual GMA Music Awards |publisher=[[Gospel Music Association]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060317022956/http://www.doveawards.com/categories/ |archivedate=March 17, 2006 |accessdate=August 16, 2012 |url=http://www.doveawards.com/categories/ |url-status=dead }}\n*{{cite web|title=Nominees for the 38th Annual GMA Dove Awards |publisher=[[Gospel Music Association]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070315062926/http://www.doveawards.com/categories/ |archivedate=March 15, 2007 |accessdate=August 16, 2012 |url=http://www.doveawards.com/categories/ |url-status=dead }}\n*{{cite web|title=The 2008 Nominees |publisher=[[Gospel Music Association]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080406132108/http://www.doveawards.com/doveawards/nominees.php |archivedate=April 6, 2008 |accessdate=August 16, 2012 |url=http://www.doveawards.com/doveawards/nominees.php |url-status=dead }}\n*{{cite web|title=2009 Nominees |publisher=[[Gospel Music Association]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090312054226/http://www.doveawards.com/doveawards/nominees.php |archivedate=March 12, 2009 |accessdate=August 16, 2012 |url=http://www.doveawards.com/doveawards/nominees.php |url-status=dead }}\n*{{cite web|title=41st Annual GMA Dove Award Nominees |publisher=[[Gospel Music Association]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100414095534/http://www.gmclife.com/41st-dove-award-nominees |archivedate=April 14, 2010 |accessdate=August 16, 2012 |url=http://www.gmclife.com/41st-dove-award-nominees |url-status=dead }}\n*{{cite web|title=42nd Annual GMA Dove Award Nominees |publisher=[[Gospel Music Association]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718002729/http://www.watchgmctv.com/news/42nd-annual-gma-dove-award-nominees |archivedate=July 18, 2011 |accessdate=August 16, 2012 |url=http://www.watchgmctv.com/news/42nd-annual-gma-dove-award-nominees |url-status=dead }}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.doveawards.com/nominees.php |title=Nominees for the 43rd Annual GMA Dove Awards... |publisher=[[Gospel Music Association]] |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.doveawards.com%2Fnominees.php&date=2012-06-30 |archivedate=May 30, 2012 |accessdate=August 16, 2012 }}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.doveawards.com/history.php?x=artist |title=Dove Awards History Artist: MercyMe |publisher=[[Gospel Music Association]] |accessdate=August 17, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120605031050/http://www.doveawards.com/history.php?x=artist |archivedate=June 5, 2012 }} Note: User must enter \"MercyMe\" and click the \"Artist\" button to achieve desired result.\n</ref>\n\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| [[33rd GMA Dove Awards|2002]] ||rowspan=\"1\"| \"[[I Can Only Imagine (MercyMe song)|I Can Only Imagine]]\"  || Pop/Contemporary Recorded Song of the Year || {{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| [[34th GMA Dove Awards|2003]] ||rowspan=\"1\"| &ndash;  || Artist of the Year || {{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| &ndash;|| Group of the Year || {{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| ''[[Spoken For]]'' || [[Dove Award for Pop/Contemporary Album of the Year|Pop/Contemporary Album of the Year]] || {{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| [[35th GMA Dove Awards|2004]] ||rowspan=\"1\"| &ndash;  || Artist of the Year || {{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| &ndash;|| Group of the Year || {{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| \"[[Word of God Speak]]\" || Pop/Contemporary Recorded Song of the Year || {{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"| [[36th GMA Dove Awards|2005]] ||rowspan=\"1\"| &ndash;  || Artist of the Year || {{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| &ndash;|| Group of the Year || {{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| ''[[Undone (MercyMe album)|Undone]]'' || Pop/Contemporary Album of the Year || {{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| ''[[The Passion of the Christ: Songs]]'' || Special Event Album of the Year || {{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| ''MercyMe Live'' || Long Form Music Video of the Year || {{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| [[37th GMA Dove Awards|2006]] ||rowspan=\"1\"| &ndash;  || Group of the Year || {{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[38th GMA Dove Awards|2007]] ||rowspan=\"1\"| &ndash;  || Group of the Year || {{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| ''[[Coming Up to Breathe]]'' || Pop/Contemporary Album of the Year || {{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| [[40th GMA Dove Awards|2008]] ||rowspan=\"1\"| &ndash;  || Group of the Year || {{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[42nd GMA Dove Awards|2010]] ||rowspan=\"1\"| &ndash;  || Group of the Year || {{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"| \"[[All of Creation (song)|All of Creation]]\" || Pop/Contemporary Recorded Song of the Year || {{nom}}\n|-\n|colspan=\"10\" style=\"font-size:8pt\"| \"\u2014\" denotes that award was not for a work\n{{end}}\n\n==Grammy Awards==\nThe [[Grammy Award]]s are awarded annually by [[National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences|The Recording Academy]] and honor \"artistic achievement, technical proficiency and overall excellence in the recording industry, without regard to album sales or chart position\".<ref name=\"Overview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.grammy.org/recording-academy|title=Overview|publisher=Grammy.org.[[National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences|The Recording Academy]]|accessdate=June 30, 2012}}</ref> MercyMe has been nominated for one award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.grammy.com/GRAMMY_Awards/49th_Show/list.aspx |title=49th Annual Grammy Awards Winners List |publisher=Grammy.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5mpxAz2DS?url=http://www2.grammy.com/GRAMMY_Awards/49th_Show/list.aspx |archivedate=January 17, 2010 |url-status=dead |accessdate=May 2, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| {{grammy|2007}} ||rowspan=\"1\"| ''[[Coming Up to Breathe]]'' || [[Grammy Award for Best Pop/Contemporary Gospel Album|Best Pop/Contemporary Gospel Album]] || {{nom}}\n|-\n{{end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{MercyMe}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of awards received by American musician|MercyMe]]\n", "name_user": "Sandstein", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing link(s):Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/Gospel Music Associationclosed as delete (XFDcloser)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_awards_and_nominations_received_by_MercyMe"}
{"title_page": "Ben Speer", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Ben Lacy Speer\n| image              = Ben Speer.jpg\n| birth_date         = June 26, 1930\n| birth_place        = Double Springs, AL\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2017|04|07|1930|06|29}}\n| death_place        = Nashville, TN\n| resting_place      = Woodlawn Cemetery, Thompson Lane, Nashville, TN\n| occupation         = Southern Gospel Singer, Producer, Music Director\n| spouse             = {{plainlist|\n* Mildred Aline Bradley Speer, (m. 1953-1993)\n* Rebekah Long (m. 2014-2017)\n}}\n| children           = {{plainlist|\n* Stephen Speer\n* Lisa Speer Mena Harris\n* Darin Speer \n}}\n\n| parents            = G.T. and Lena Speer\n| relatives          = {{plainlist|\n[[Brock Speer]] (brother)\n* [[Mary Speer|Mary Tom Speer Reid]] (sister)\n* [[Rosa Nell Speer|Rosa Nell Speer Powell]] (sister)\n}}\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist\n   | embed = yes\n   | background = solo_singer\n   | instrument = {{flat list|\n* Vocals\n* Piano\n   }}\n   | genre = {{flat list|\n* [[Southern Gospel]]\n }}\n   | associated_acts = [[Speer Family]], [[Gaither Homecoming|Gaither Homecoming Series]]\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Ben Lacy Speer''' (June 26, 1930 \u2013 April 7, 2017)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.singingnews.com/news/ben-speer-passes-away/|title=Ben Speer Passes Away {{!}} SingingNews.com|last=Staff|website=Singing News|language=en|access-date=2017-04-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170408030133/http://www.singingnews.com/news/ben-speer-passes-away/|archive-date=2017-04-08|url-status=dead}}</ref> was a singer, musician, music publisher, and record company executive. He sang for [[The Speer Family]] for most of his career.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Speer Family |url=http://www.encyclopediaofalabama.org/face/Article.jsp?id=h-2956|work=Encyclopedia of Alabama|accessdate=27 February 2014}}</ref> Speer later became the music director of the [[Gaither Homecoming]] programs. He was born in [[Double Springs, Alabama]], the youngest child of Lena and G.T. Speer<ref name=\"GMA\">{{cite web|title=Ben Lacy Speer|url=http://www.gmahalloffame.org/site/ben-lacy-speer/|work=GMA Gospel Music Hall of Fame|accessdate=27 February 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140307000102/http://www.gmahalloffame.org/site/ben-lacy-speer/|archive-date=2014-03-07|url-status=dead}}</ref> (affectionately known as \"Mom\" and \"Dad\" Speer to most people in [[Southern gospel]] music), who originally led the group, with Speer's siblings [[Brock Speer]], [[Mary Speer|Mary Tom Speer]], and [[Rosa Nell Speer]] also participating.<ref>{{cite web|title=Grand Ole Gospel Reunion Music History - The Speer Family|url=http://www.grandolegospelreunion.com/sg-101/speer_expansion.htm|accessdate=March 6, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140307005418/http://www.grandolegospelreunion.com/sg-101/speer_expansion.htm|archive-date=2014-03-07|url-status=dead}}</ref> He died on April 7, 2017 after suffering from [[Alzheimer's Disease]].\n\n== Performing career ==\n\nFrom starting to sing at age 2, Speer went on to a career that led to his being described on the Gospel Music Association Hall of Fame website as \"one of the most enduring and outstanding lead singers and piano performers in gospel music.\"<ref name=GMA /> During his years with the [[Speer Family]], the group recorded more than 75 albums.<ref name=GMA /> In addition to singing and playing piano with the [[Speer Family]], he arranged music for them. He retired from the group in 1992, but made some appearances with it until the group itself retired.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ben Speer Biography|url=http://blog.musicscribe.com/p=139|work=MusicScribe|accessdate=28 February 2014}}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n== Technical and business career ==\n\nSpeer has contributed to both the technical and business aspects of [[Southern gospel]] music. Speer was the longtime music director for the [[Gaither Homecoming]] series.<ref name=\"SGMA\">{{cite web|title=Ben Lacy Speer|url=http://www.sgma.org/inductee_bios/ben_speer.htm|work=Southern Gospel Music Association|accessdate=28 January 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615131646/http://www.sgma.org/inductee_bios/ben_speer.htm|archivedate=15 June 2011}}</ref> \n\nThe Gospel Music Association Hall of Fame's website noted his technical accomplishments as follows: \"Ben chose experimenting with sound equipment as a hobby. He has excelled in this field and is often used as a consultant for sound by his colleagues in gospel music.\"<ref name=GMA /> As owner and chief engineer of Ben Speer Recording Studios,<ref name=GMA /> he has produced albums by the [[Florida Boys]], [[Ivan Parker]], The Weatherfords and others.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ben Speer|url=https://gaither.com/artists/ben-speer|work=Gaither|accessdate=28 February 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140208011339/http://gaither.com/artists/ben-speer|archive-date=2014-02-08|url-status=dead}}</ref> Speer began publishing [[Southern Gospel]] music in 1950, founding the Ben Speer Music Company. Among songs published by the company are \"What a Day That Will Be,\" \"I'm Standing on the Solid Rock,\" and \"Touring that City.\"\n\n===Ben Speer's Stamps Baxter School of Music===\nIn 1988, Speer revived the [[Stamps-Baxter Music Company|Stamps-Baxter School of Music]], which for many years had been an institution for training people in Southern gospel music. Now known as Ben Speer's Stamps Baxter School of Music, the school attracts students from across the United States and from other countries.<ref>{{cite web |title=About Us |url=https://www.stampsbaxterschool.com/history |website=Ben Speer's Stamps-Baxter School of Music {{!}} Home |accessdate=8 June 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=About Us|url=https://www.stampsbaxterschool.com/about.aspx|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100114045046/http://stampsbaxterschool.com/about.aspx|url-status=dead|archive-date=14 January 2010|work=Ben Speer's Stamps Baxter School of Music|accessdate=28 February 2014}}</ref> James R. Goff Jr., in his ''Close Harmony: A History of Southern Gospel'', wrote that a 1998 brochure summarized key elements of the school as follows: \"theory, harmony, song writing, sight reading, ear training, performance training, conducting, voice, piano, guitar, bass and drums are taught.\"<ref>Goff, James R. Jr. (2002). ''Close Harmony: A History of Southern Gospel.'' The University of North Carolina Press. {{ISBN|0-8078-2681-2}}</ref>  The school continues to be operated by members of the Speer family following Speer's death with the school being hosted at Middle Tennessee State University in 2018. <ref>{{cite web |title=MTSU Summer Experiences |url=http://www.mtsu.edu/camps/ |website=Middle Tennessee State University |accessdate=8 June 2018 |language=en}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web |title=2018 Ben Speer's Stamps-Baxter School of Music {{!}} Summary {{!}} powered by RegOnline |url=https://www.regonline.com/builder/site/Default.aspx?EventID=2024497& |website=www.regonline.com |accessdate=8 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Honors ==\n\nSpeer was inducted into the Gospel Music Association Hall of Fame in 1995,<ref name=GMA /> the [[Southern Gospel Music Association]] Hall of Fame in 1998<ref name=SGMA /> and the Southern Gospel Piano Roll of Honor in 2002.<ref>{{cite web|title=Four Inducted Into Southern Gospel Piano Hall of Honor|url=http://www.singingnews.com/Southern-Gospel-News/11591882/|archive-url=https://archive.today/20140306212737/http://www.singingnews.com/Southern-Gospel-News/11591882/|url-status=dead|archive-date=6 March 2014|work=singingnews|accessdate=28 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n\n<!--- See [[Wikipedia:Footnotes]] on how to create references using<ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Speer, Ben}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2017 deaths]]\n[[Category:American gospel singers]]\n[[Category:Southern gospel performers]]\n[[Category:People from Alabama]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Ben Lacy Speer\n| image              = Ben Speer.jpg\n| birth_date         = June 26, 1930\n| birth_place        = Double Springs, AL\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2017|04|07|1930|06|29}}\n| death_place        = Nashville, TN\n| resting_place      = Woodlawn Cemetery, Thompson Lane, Nashville, TN\n| occupation         = Southern Gospel Singer, Producer, Music Director\n| spouse             = {{plainlist|\n* Mildred Aline Bradley Speer, (m. 1953-1993)\n* Rebekah Long (m. 2014-2017)\n}}\n| children           = {{plainlist|\n* Stephen Speer\n* Lisa Speer Mena Harris\n* Darin Speer \n}}\n\n| parents            = G.T. and Lena Speer\n| relatives          = {{plainlist|\n[[Brock Speer]] (brother)\n* [[Mary Speer|Mary Tom Speer Reid]] (sister)\n* [[Rosa Nell Speer|Rosa Nell Speer Powell]] (sister)\n}}\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist\n   | embed = yes\n   | background = solo_singer\n   | instrument = {{flat list|\n* Vocals\n* Piano\n   }}\n   | genre = {{flat list|\n* [[Southern Gospel]]\n }}\n   | associated_acts = [[Speer Family]], [[Gaither Homecoming|Gaither Homecoming Series]]\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Ben Lacy Speer''' (June 26, 1930 \u2013 April 7, 2017)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.singingnews.com/news/ben-speer-passes-away/|title=Ben Speer Passes Away {{!}} SingingNews.com|last=Staff|website=Singing News|language=en|access-date=2017-04-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170408030133/http://www.singingnews.com/news/ben-speer-passes-away/|archive-date=2017-04-08|url-status=dead}}</ref> was a singer, musician, music publisher, and record company executive. He sang for [[The Speer Family]] for most of his career.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Speer Family |url=http://www.encyclopediaofalabama.org/face/Article.jsp?id=h-2956|work=Encyclopedia of Alabama|accessdate=27 February 2014}}</ref> Speer later became the music director of the [[Gaither Homecoming]] programs. He was born in [[Double Springs, Alabama]], the youngest child of Lena and G.T. Speer<ref name=\"GMA\">{{cite web|title=Ben Lacy Speer|url=http://www.gmahalloffame.org/site/ben-lacy-speer/|work=GMA Gospel Music Hall of Fame|accessdate=27 February 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140307000102/http://www.gmahalloffame.org/site/ben-lacy-speer/|archive-date=2014-03-07|url-status=dead}}</ref> (affectionately known as \"Mom\" and \"Dad\" Speer to most people in [[Southern gospel]] music), who originally led the group, with Speer's siblings [[Brock Speer]], [[Mary Speer|Mary Tom Speer]], and [[Rosa Nell Speer]] also participating.<ref>{{cite web|title=Grand Ole Gospel Reunion Music History - The Speer Family|url=http://www.grandolegospelreunion.com/sg-101/speer_expansion.htm|accessdate=March 6, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140307005418/http://www.grandolegospelreunion.com/sg-101/speer_expansion.htm|archive-date=2014-03-07|url-status=dead}}</ref> He died on April 7, 2017 after suffering from [[Alzheimer's Disease]].\n\n== Performing career ==\n\nFrom starting to sing at age 2, Speer went on to a career that led to his being described on the [[Gospel Music Association]] Hall of Fame website as \"one of the most enduring and outstanding lead singers and piano performers in gospel music.\"<ref name=GMA /> During his years with the [[Speer Family]], the group recorded more than 75 albums.<ref name=GMA /> In addition to singing and playing piano with the [[Speer Family]], he arranged music for them. He retired from the group in 1992, but made some appearances with it until the group itself retired.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ben Speer Biography|url=http://blog.musicscribe.com/p=139|work=MusicScribe|accessdate=28 February 2014}}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n== Technical and business career ==\n\nSpeer has contributed to both the technical and business aspects of [[Southern gospel]] music. Speer was the longtime music director for the [[Gaither Homecoming]] series.<ref name=\"SGMA\">{{cite web|title=Ben Lacy Speer|url=http://www.sgma.org/inductee_bios/ben_speer.htm|work=Southern Gospel Music Association|accessdate=28 January 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615131646/http://www.sgma.org/inductee_bios/ben_speer.htm|archivedate=15 June 2011}}</ref> \n\nThe [[Gospel Music Association]] Hall of Fame's website noted his technical accomplishments as follows: \"Ben chose experimenting with sound equipment as a hobby. He has excelled in this field and is often used as a consultant for sound by his colleagues in gospel music.\"<ref name=GMA /> As owner and chief engineer of Ben Speer Recording Studios,<ref name=GMA /> he has produced albums by the [[Florida Boys]], [[Ivan Parker]], The Weatherfords and others.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ben Speer|url=https://gaither.com/artists/ben-speer|work=Gaither|accessdate=28 February 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140208011339/http://gaither.com/artists/ben-speer|archive-date=2014-02-08|url-status=dead}}</ref> Speer began publishing [[Southern Gospel]] music in 1950, founding the Ben Speer Music Company. Among songs published by the company are \"What a Day That Will Be,\" \"I'm Standing on the Solid Rock,\" and \"Touring that City.\"\n\n===Ben Speer's Stamps Baxter School of Music===\nIn 1988, Speer revived the [[Stamps-Baxter Music Company|Stamps-Baxter School of Music]], which for many years had been an institution for training people in Southern gospel music. Now known as Ben Speer's Stamps Baxter School of Music, the school attracts students from across the United States and from other countries.<ref>{{cite web |title=About Us |url=https://www.stampsbaxterschool.com/history |website=Ben Speer's Stamps-Baxter School of Music {{!}} Home |accessdate=8 June 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=About Us|url=https://www.stampsbaxterschool.com/about.aspx|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100114045046/http://stampsbaxterschool.com/about.aspx|url-status=dead|archive-date=14 January 2010|work=Ben Speer's Stamps Baxter School of Music|accessdate=28 February 2014}}</ref> James R. Goff Jr., in his ''Close Harmony: A History of Southern Gospel'', wrote that a 1998 brochure summarized key elements of the school as follows: \"theory, harmony, song writing, sight reading, ear training, performance training, conducting, voice, piano, guitar, bass and drums are taught.\"<ref>Goff, James R. Jr. (2002). ''Close Harmony: A History of Southern Gospel.'' The University of North Carolina Press. {{ISBN|0-8078-2681-2}}</ref>  The school continues to be operated by members of the Speer family following Speer's death with the school being hosted at Middle Tennessee State University in 2018. <ref>{{cite web |title=MTSU Summer Experiences |url=http://www.mtsu.edu/camps/ |website=Middle Tennessee State University |accessdate=8 June 2018 |language=en}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web |title=2018 Ben Speer's Stamps-Baxter School of Music {{!}} Summary {{!}} powered by RegOnline |url=https://www.regonline.com/builder/site/Default.aspx?EventID=2024497& |website=www.regonline.com |accessdate=8 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Honors ==\n\nSpeer was inducted into the [[Gospel Music Association]] Hall of Fame in 1995,<ref name=GMA /> the [[Southern Gospel Music Association]] Hall of Fame in 1998<ref name=SGMA /> and the Southern Gospel Piano Roll of Honor in 2002.<ref>{{cite web|title=Four Inducted Into Southern Gospel Piano Hall of Honor|url=http://www.singingnews.com/Southern-Gospel-News/11591882/|archive-url=https://archive.today/20140306212737/http://www.singingnews.com/Southern-Gospel-News/11591882/|url-status=dead|archive-date=6 March 2014|work=singingnews|accessdate=28 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n\n<!--- See [[Wikipedia:Footnotes]] on how to create references using<ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Speer, Ben}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2017 deaths]]\n[[Category:American gospel singers]]\n[[Category:Southern gospel performers]]\n[[Category:People from Alabama]]\n", "name_user": "Sandstein", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing link(s):Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/Gospel Music Associationclosed as delete (XFDcloser)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ben_Speer"}
{"title_page": "List of awards and nominations received by Switchfoot", "text_new": "{{Expand list|date=September 2013}}\n\n{{Infobox Musician Awards\n| name                   = Switchfoot\n| image                  = \n| caption                = \n| wins                 = 31<!--PER AWARDS 'WON' MENTIONED IN THIS ARTICLE. DO NOT INFLATE-->\n| nominations            = 4<!--PER NOMINATIONS MENTIONED IN THIS ARTICLE.-->\n\n| GrammyW                = 1\n| GrammyN                = 2\n| award1 = [[ASCAP]] Awards\n| award1W = 3\n| award1N = 0\n| award2 = [[GMA Dove Award]]\n| award2W = 13\n| award2N = 2\n| award3 = [[San Diego Music Awards]]\n| award3W = 12\n| award3N = 1\n| award4 = [[Orville H. Gibson]] Guitar Awards\n| award4W = 1\n| award4N = 0\n| award5 = [[Rock on Request Awards]]\n| award5W = 1\n| award5N = 0\n}}\n\nThe following is a '''list of awards and nominations received by [[Switchfoot]]''', an American alternative rock band.\n\n==ASCAP Awards==\n[[American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers]] (ASCAP) honors its top members in a series of annual awards shows in seven different music categories: pop, rhythm and soul, film and television, Latin, country, Christian, and concert music.\n\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| 1997\n| Switchfoot\n| Best New Artist\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\" rowspan=\"2\" | 2006\n| [[Jon Foreman]]\n| Impact Award awarded \"to celebrate the success and influence of his songs in mainstream rock music\"\n| {{won}}<ref name=top40>{{cite web |url=http://cmcentral.com/news/4475.html |title=2006 ASCAP Awards results... |last=Gilbert |first=Brenten |publisher=CMCentral.com |date=April 9, 2006 |accessdate=November 24, 2009}}</ref>\n|-\n| \"Dare You to Move\"\n| Top 50 list of Most Performed Song of 2005\n| {{won}}\n|-\n{{end}}\n\n==GMA Dove Awards==\n[[GMA Dove Award]] is an accolade by the Gospel Music Association (GMA) of the United States to recognize outstanding achievement in the [[Christian music industry]].\n\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\" rowspan=\"3\"| [[35th GMA Dove Awards|2004]]\n| \"Ammunition\"\n| Rock Recorded Song of the Year\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| ''The Beautiful Letdown''\n| Rock/Contemporary Album of the Year\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| \"Meant to Live\"\n| Rock/Contemporary Recorded Song of the Year \n| {{won}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\" rowspan=\"4\"| [[36th GMA Dove Awards|2005]]\n| Switchfoot\n| Artist of the Year\n| {{won}}<ref name=\"Dove 2005\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/63285/switchfoot-leads-gospel-award-winners |title=Switchfoot Leads Gospel Award Winners |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=September 5, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| \"Dare You to Move\"\n| Rock/Contemporary Recorded Song of the Year\n| {{won}}<ref name=\"Dove 2005\"/>\n|-\n| Short Form Music Video of the Year\n| {{won}}<ref name=\"Dove 2005\"/>\n|-\n| ''Live In San Diego''\n| Long Form Music Video of the Year\n| {{won}}<ref name=\"Dove 2005\"/>\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| [[37th GMA Dove Awards|2006]]\n| \"Stars\"\n| Short Form Music Video of the Year\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| [[41st GMA Dove Awards|2010]]\n| \"Mess of Me\"\n| Rock Recorded Song of the Year\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\" rowspan=\"2\"| [[43rd GMA Dove Awards|2012]]\n| \"Dark Horses\"\n| Rock Recorded Song of the Year\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| ''Vice Verses''\n| Rock Album of the Year\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\"|[[44th GMA Dove Awards|2013]]\n| \"Afterlife\"\n| Rock/Contemporary Recorded Song of the Year\n| {{nom}}<ref name=\"dove 2013\">{{cite web |url=http://www.doveawards.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/DoveAwardNominees.FINAL_.2013.pdf |title=2013 Award Nominees |work=[[GMA Dove Awards]] |accessdate=August 24, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130828233232/http://www.doveawards.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/DoveAwardNominees.FINAL_.2013.pdf |archivedate=August 28, 2013 }}</ref>\n|-\n| align=\"center\"rowspan=\"3\"| [[45th GMA Dove Awards|2014]]\n| Switchfoot\n| Artist of the Year\n| {{nominated}}\n|-\n| \"Love Alone Is Worth the Fight\"\n| Rock/Contemporary Song of the Year\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| ''Fading West''\n| Rock/Contemporary Album of the Year\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\"rowspan=\"3\"| [[50th GMA Dove Awards|2019]]\n| \"Native Tongue\"\n| Rock/Contemporary Recorded Song of the Year\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| ''Native Tongue''\n| Rock/Contemporary Album of the Year\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| ''Native Tongue''\n| Recorded Music Packaging of the Year\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n{{end}}\n\n==Grammy Awards==\nThe [[Grammy Awards]] are awarded annually by the [[National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences]] to recognize outstanding achievement in the music industry. Switchfoot has received two Grammy nominations for their albums, and won once in 2011.\n\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| [[2001 Grammy Awards|2001]]\n| ''[[Learning to Breathe (Switchfoot album)|Learning to Breathe]]''\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Rock Gospel Album|Best Rock Gospel Album]]\n| {{nom}}<ref name=\"Grammy Nominations 2001\">{{cite web|title=2001 Grammy Awards|url=http://www.metrolyrics.com/2001-grammy-awards.html|publisher=MetroLyrics.com|accessdate=June 12, 2012}}</ref> \n|-\n| align=\"center\"| [[2011 Grammy Awards|2011]]\n| ''[[Hello Hurricane]]''\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Rock Gospel Album|Best Rock or Rap Gospel Album]]\n| {{won}}<ref name=\"Grammy Nominations 2011\">{{cite web|title=2011 Grammy Awards|url=http://www.metrolyrics.com/2011-grammy-awards.html|publisher=MetroLyrics.com|accessdate=June 12, 2012}}</ref> \n|-\n{{end}}\n\n==Orville H. Gibson Guitar Awards==\n\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| 2001\n| [[Jon Foreman]]\n| Les Paul Horizon Award <small>(for the most promising up-and-coming guitarist)</small>\n| {{won}}<ref name=\"gibson\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nyrock.com/worldbeat/02_2001/022101a.asp |title=Gibson Guitar Awards: \"And the Winner Is ...\" |publisher=nyrock.com |date=February 2002 |accessdate=September 4, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130406104108/http://www.nyrock.com/worldbeat/02_2001/022101a.asp |archivedate=April 6, 2013 }}</ref>\n|-\n{{end}}\n\n==Rock on Request Awards==\nThe [[Rock on Request Awards]] are an American annual music awards held by the music webzine ''[[Rock on Request]]''.\n\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| 2009\n| Switchfoot\n| Best Christian Artist\n| {{won}}\n|-\n{{end}}\n\n==San Diego Music Awards==\n[[San Diego Music Awards]] are held annually in [[San Diego]], [[California]] to recognize the best bands and artists in local music.\n\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\"|  1997 \n| Switchfoot\n| Best New Artist\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\" rowspan=\"2\"| 2001\n| Switchfoot\n| Best Pop Artist\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| ''Learning to Breathe''\n| Best Pop Album\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| 2002\n| Switchfoot\n| Best Adult Alternative Artist\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\" rowspan=\"2\" | 2003\n| rowspan=\"2\" | ''The Beautiful Letdown''\n| Best Pop Album\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Album of the Year\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| 2004\n| \"Dare You to Move\"\n| Song of the Year\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| 2006\n| Switchfoot\n| Artist of the Year\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| 2007 \n| ''Oh! Gravity''\n| Album of the Year\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| 2010 \n| ''Hello Hurricane''\n| Album of the Year\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| 2011\n| Switchfoot\n| Artist of the Year\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\" rowspan=\"2\"| 2012\n| Switchfoot\n| Artist of the Year\n| {{won}}<ref name=\"SDMA 2012\">{{cite web|url=http://landofbrokenhearts.org/archive/2012/08/switchfoot-wins-artist-of-the-year-at-the-san-diego-music-awards/ |title=Switchfoot Wins Artist of the Year at the San Diego Music Awards |publisher=Land of Broken Hearts |date=August 14, 2012|accessdate=September 4, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| \"Afterlife\"\n| Song of the Year\n| {{nom}}<ref name=\"SDMA 2012\"/>\n|-\n{{end}}\n\n==References==