 box candidate with party link\n   |party      = Values Party\n   |candidate  = D C Bartle\n   |votes      = 250\n   |percentage = 1.41\n   |change     = \n }}\n {{Election box majority\n   |votes      = 2,819\n   |percentage = 15.98\n   |change     = \n }}\n {{Election box turnout\n   |votes      = 17,634\n   |percentage = 70.01\n   |change     = \n }}\n {{Election box Registered electors\n   |reg. electors = 25,186\n }}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |title=Electoral Atlas of New Zealand |last=McRobie |first=Alan |year=1989 |publisher=GP Books |location=Wellington |isbn=0-477-01384-8}}\n*{{Cite book |ref=harv |last= Wilson |first= James Oakley |title= New Zealand Parliamentary Record, 1840\u20131984 |edition= 4th |origyear= First ed. published 1913 |year= 1985 |publisher= V.R. Ward, Govt. Printer |location= Wellington |oclc=154283103}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.parliament.nz/NR/rdonlyres/6F3F94F4-8126-474B-BB0B-11FC627C2F11/204/Te_Atatu1.pdf Electorate Profile]  ''Parliamentary Library''\n{{electorates of New Zealand}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Te Atatu (New Zealand electorate)}}\n[[Category:New Zealand electorates]]\n[[Category:Politics of the Auckland Region]]\n[[Category:1978 establishments in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:1996 disestablishments in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:1999 establishments in New Zealand]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Current New Zealand electorate}}\n{{EngvarB|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n[[image:Te Atatu electorate, 2014.svg|thumb|right|Te Atat\u016b electorate boundaries used since the {{NZ election link|2014}}]]\n'''Te Atat\u016b''' (before 2008 spelled '''Te Atatu''', without a [[Macron (diacritic)|macron]]) is a parliamentary [[New Zealand electorates|electorate]], returning one Member of Parliament to the [[New Zealand House of Representatives]]. The current MP for Te Atat\u016b is [[Phil Twyford]] of the [[New Zealand Labour Party|Labour Party]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.nz/en-NZ/MPP/MPs/MPs/8/d/c/50MP123551-Twyford-Phil.htm |title=New Zealand Parliament \u2013 Twyford, Phil |publisher=Parliament.nz |accessdate=4 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Population centres==\nThe 1977 electoral redistribution was the most overtly political since the Representation Commission had been established through an amendment to the ''Representation Act'' in 1886, initiated by [[Robert Muldoon|Muldoon]]'s [[Third National Government of New Zealand|National Government]].{{sfn|McRobie |1989 |pp=8\u20139, 51, 119}} As part of the [[1976 New Zealand census|1976 census]], a large number of people failed to fill in an electoral re-registration card, and census staff had not been given the authority to insist on the card being completed. This had little practical effect for people on the general roll, but it transferred [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]] to the general roll if the card was not handed in. Together with a northward shift of New Zealand's population, this resulted in five new electorates having to be created in the upper part of the [[North Island]].{{sfn|McRobie|1989|p=119}} The electoral redistribution was very disruptive, and 22 electorates were abolished, while 27 electorates were newly created (including Te Atatu) or re-established. These changes came into effect for the {{NZ election link|1978}}.{{sfn|McRobie|1989|pp=115\u2013120}}\n\nTe Atat\u016b comprises the suburbs of [[Waitakere City]] on the western side of the [[Whau River]] in [[Auckland]]. The main parts of the seat are the suburbs of [[Glendene, New Zealand|Glendene]], [[Te Atat\u016b]], [[Lincoln, Auckland|Lincoln]] and [[Massey, New Zealand|Massey]]. Boundary changes in the leadup to the [[2008 New Zealand general election|2008 election]] have seen the northern boundary edge northwards to include [[Massey East]], with a small southern block transferred to the neighbouring [[Waitakere (New Zealand electorate)|Waitakere]] seat.\n\nThe makeup of Te Atat\u016b shows that while its population is composed roughly inline with the national average: It is roughly the same ages as the nation (with slightly more residents over fifty), and its average income ($22627) is only slightly lower than the rest of New Zealand. Its main point of demographic difference with its country is ethnic \u2013 it has more Asian New Zealanders and more Pacific Islanders than the rest of the country.\n\n==History==\nThe Te Atatu electorate was created ahead of the [[1978 New Zealand general election|1978 election]] by pulling apart the seat of [[Waitemata (New Zealand electorate)|Waitemata]]; its first MP was future cabinet minister Dr [[Michael Bassett]], who had been the MP for Waitemata from [[1972 New Zealand general election|1972]] until [[1975 New Zealand general election|1975]] before an anti-labour landslide cost him his job. Bassett held the seat until his retirement in 1990, when a toxic battle to succeed Bassett in an already lean year for Labour passed one of their safe seats into the hands of [[Brian Neeson]]. Neeson himself never represented the same seat twice in succession, (having jumped ship to [[Waitakere (New Zealand electorate)|Waitakere]] in 1993, [[Waipareira|Waipareia]] in 1996, to a new, larger Waitakere seat in 1999 before being denied the chance to contest [[Helensville (New Zealand electorate)|Helensville]] in 2002), and his departure in 1993, coupled with a reversal of electoral fortune for the National Party (down from 47.8 to 35.1 percent) lead to a victory for incoming Labour MP Chris Carter. In his first three years in Parliament, Carter made news for being the first openly gay member of Parliament.\n\nWith the introduction of [[Mixed Member Proportional|MMP]] voting in 1996, Te Atat\u016b was scrapped in favour of a new seat called Waipareira, which covered the same area as Te Atat\u016b, but also included the wealthy harbourside suburbs to the north of the seat. Neeson and Carter were rematched, when the presence of former Labour MP for [[Auckland West|West Auckland]] turned [[New Zealand First]] candidate [[Jack Elder]], undermined Carter's chances and handed the seat to Neeson by fewer than a thousand votes.\n\nThree years later, Te Atatu was re-established, with the new seat focused more on the working class suburbs at the southern end of Waitakere City and Carter had no such trouble using the seat to springboard back into Parliament. In [[2002 New Zealand general election|2002]] and [[2005 New Zealand general election|2005]], because the electoral climate favoured Labour, Carter and his party dominated the seat, winning at least 49 percent of the candidate and list vote, but the Labour vote was reduced in the [[2008 New Zealand general election|2008]] election.\n\n===Members of Parliament===\n'''Key'''\n\n{{Party index link|New Zealand Labour Party}} {{Party index link|New Zealand National Party}} {{Party index link|Independent politician}} {{Party index link|Alliance (New Zealand political party)}}\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n!width=100| Election\n! style=\"width:175px;\" colspan=\"2\"| Winner\n|-\n| {{NZ election link|1978}}\n| width=5 rowspan=4 bgcolor={{New Zealand Labour Party/meta/color}}|\n| rowspan=4 | [[Michael Bassett]]\n|-\n| {{NZ election link|1981}}\n|-\n| {{NZ election link|1984}}\n|-\n| {{NZ election link|1987}}\n|-\n| {{NZ election link|1990}}\n| bgcolor={{New Zealand National Party/meta/color}}|\n| [[Brian Neeson]]\n|-\n| {{NZ election link|1993}}\n| bgcolor={{New Zealand Labour Party/meta/color}}|\n| [[Chris Carter (politician)|Chris Carter]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|<small>(Electorate abolished 1996\u20131999, see {{NZ electorate link|Waipareira}})</small>\n|-\n| {{NZ election link|1999}}\n| width=5 rowspan=3 style=\"border-bottom:solid 0 grey; background:{{New Zealand Labour Party/meta/color}}|\n| rowspan=5 | Chris Carter\n|-\n| {{NZ election link|2002}}\n|-\n| {{NZ election link|2005}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" styl