{"title_page": "Jacky winter", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2011}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = Jacky winter \n| image = Jacky Winter - Glen Davis.jpg\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22704769/0 |title=''Microeca fascinans'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Microeca\n| species = fascinans\n| authority = ([[John Latham (ornithologist)|Latham]], 1801)\n| synonyms = \n}}\n\nThe '''jacky winter''' (''Microeca fascinans'') is a small grey-brown robin found commonly throughout [[Australia]] and also in [[Papua New Guinea]]. The jacky winter acquired its name due to rapid and strong vocalisations, which sound like ''jacky-jacky winter-winter''.<ref name=Simpson>Simpson, Ken, Day, N. and Trusler, P. (6th edn., 1999). Field Guide to the Birds of Australia. Ringwood, Victoria: Penguin Books Australia ISBN 067087918-5.</ref> Their call is also often referred to as sounding like ''peter-peter-peter''.<ref name=Slater>Slater, Peter (1974) A Field Guide to Australian Birds: Passerines. Adelaide: Rigby. ISBN 085179813-6</ref> Its habitats include open woodlands and farmlands.\n\n== Taxonomy and distribution ==\n\nThe jacky winter belongs to the family of [[Australasia]]n robins and flycatchers ''[[Petroicidae]]''. This family includes around 49 species in around 19 genera that are all endemic to [[Australasia]].<ref>Gill, F. and D. Donsker, eds. (2020). IOC World Bird List (v 10.1). Doi 10.14344/IOC.ML.10.1.  http://www.worldbirdnames.org/</ref><ref>Loynes, K., Joseph, L. and Keogh, J. S. 2009. [http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1055790309002000 Multi-locus phylogeny clarifies the systematics of the Australo-Papuan robins (Family Petroicidae, Passeriformes)]. \u2013 Mol. Phyl. Evol. 53: 212-219. {{DOI|10.1016/j.ympev.2009.05.012}}</ref> The family ''[[Petroicidae]]'' evolved in a similar way to the [[Australo-Papuan]] warblers (''[[Acanthizidae]]'')\u2014the latter evolved in isolation from similar families to them, namely ''[[Parulidae]]'' and ''[[Sylviidae]]'', which occupied comparable niches in other continental regions, such as [[Central America|Central]][[South America|/South America]] and [[Eurasia]], respectively.<ref>Ericson, p. G. P., Irestedt, M. and Johansson, U.S. 2003. [http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1034/j.1600-048X.2003.03121.x/abstract?deniedAccessCustomisedMessage=&userIsAuthenticated=false Evolution, biogeography, and patters of diversification in passerine birds]. \u2013 J. Avian. Biol. 34: 3-15. {{DOI|10.1034/j.1600-048X.2003.03121.x}}</ref> ''[[Petroicidae]]'' evolved in the [[Australo-Papuan]] area to fill an ecological niche, which was already being used by New World flycatchers (''[[Tyrannidae]]'') in [[North America]] and [[South America]], and by Old World flycatchers (''[[Muscicapidae]]'') in [[Europe]], [[Africa]], and [[Asia]]. This is an example of [[convergent evolution]].<ref name=\"Chris\">Christidis, L., Irestedt, M., Rowe, D., Boles, W. E. and Norman, J. A. 2011. [http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1055790311003587 Mitochondrial and nuclear DNA phylogenies reveal a complex evolutionary history in the Australasian robin (Passeriformes: Petroicidae).] \u2013 Mol. Phyl. Evol. 61: 726-738. {{DOI|10.1016/j.ympev.2011.08.014}}</ref><ref>Sangster, G., Alstrom, P., Forsmark, E. and Olsson, U. 2010. [http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1055790310003076 Multi-locus phylogenetic analysis of Old World chats and flycatchers reveals extensive paraphyly at family, subfamily and genus level (Aves Muscicapidae)] \u2013 Mol. Phyl. Evol. 57: 380-392. {{DOI|10.1016/j.ympev.2010.07.008}}</ref>\n\nThe generic name ''Microeca'' derives from the Greek ''micros'' meaning 'small' and ''oikos'' meaning 'house'. This refers to the fact that they build the smallest nest of any Australian bird.<ref name=Helm>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling|title=Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird-names|last=Jobling|first=James A.|accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref> The specific name ''fascinans'' is Latin for 'fascinating' and derives from ''fascinare'' meaning 'to bewitch'.<ref name=Helm></ref>\n\nOther vernacular names for the jacky winter are brown flycatcher, peter peter, postboy, spinks and stumpbird.<ref name=Slater></ref><ref>Pizzey, Graham; Doyle, Roy (1980) A Field Guide to the Birds of Australia. Collins Publishers, Sydney. ISBN 073222436-5</ref>\n\nThere are three races of jacky winter found in [[Australia]]. ''Microeca fascinans fascinans'' (''leucophaea'') is the most familiar race, and is found in central and eastern [[Queensland]], [[New South Wales]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], and southeastern [[South Australia]]. There are also ''Microeca fascinans assimilis'', which is found in [[South Australia]] and south [[Western Australia]], and ''Microeca fascinans pallida'', which is found in northern and western [[Queensland]], [[Northern Territory]], and the [[Kimberley]] in Western Australia.<ref name=Simpson></ref><ref name=\"Chris\" /><ref>Morcombe, Michael (2012) Field guide to Australian birds. Pascal Press, Glebe, NSW. Revised edition. ISBN 978174021417-9</ref><ref name=\"reid\">Reid, J. R. W. and Gillen, J. S. 2013. [http://www.naturalresources.sa.gov.au/files/d137ff65-3033-48e5-8200-a2de00e18b97/cooper-catchment-2013-birds-rep.pdf. Riparian bird assembladges of Cooper Creek, South Australia]. \u2013 South Australian Arid Lands Natural Resources Management Board.</ref> ''Microeca fascinans zimmeri'' is a subspecies of jacky winter found in Papua New Guinea <ref>Bell, H. L. 2008. [http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1474-919X.1982.tb03772.x/abstract Abundance and seasonality of the savannah avifauna at Port Moresby, Papua New Guinea]. \u2013 Ibis 124: 252-274. {{DOI|10.1111/j.1474-919X.1982.tb03772.x}}</ref>\n\n== Description ==\n\nThe jacky winter is around 12 \u2013 14&nbsp;cm in length (including the tail) and its weight varies from 14 \u2013 18 g.<ref name=\"wood\">Wood, K. A, Thompson, N. and Ley, A. J. 2008. [http://search.informit.com.au/documentSummary;dn=407981259692578;res=IELHSS Breeding Territories and Breeding Success of the Jacky Winter Microeca fasinans in South-eastern Queensland]. \u2013 Australian Field Ornithology 25: 121-131. {{ISSN|1448-0107}}</ref> The plumage of ''M. f. fascinans'' includes a greyish breast with white on the bottom half, its head and back is greyish-brown, while its wings are a darker brown with white edges. The bill is black, it has a narrow eye-line and a buff [[alula]] stripe. The tail of ''M. f. fascinans'' is blackish brown with white outer feathers. Its legs are black. Subspecies ''M. f. assimilis'' is very similar to ''M. f. fascinans''; however, it is darker, with more grey over the breast and flanks, covering up the white which is seen on ''M. f. fascinans''.<ref name=\"wood\" /> ''M. f. pallida'' is smaller than the other two subspecies, being only around 13&nbsp;cm. ''M. f. pallida'' is much more pallid than the other subspecies, and is usually a sandy brown colour.<ref name=\"reid\" />\n\n== Behaviour ==\n[[File:Jacky-winter96.ogg|thumb|300px|Rush Creek, south-east Queensland]]\n\nThe jacky winter can be heard vocalising before sunrise and usually stops towards the middle of the day. Occasionally closer to sunset, it can be heard again.<ref name=\"Kea\">Keast, A. 1994. [http://www.publish.csiro.au/?paper=MU9940230 The Annual Cycle in a Vocalisation Context: a Comparison of the Eastern Yellow Robin Eopsaltria australis and the Jacky Winter Microeca leucophaea.] \u2013 Emu 94: 230-238. {{doi|10.1071/MU9940230}}</ref> During the day they can be seen perched atop trees and posts, [[preening]] their [[feathers]] or even sunning to kill the [[parasites]], which may be present in amongst the feathers.<ref>Moyer, B. R. and Wagenbach, G. E. 1995. [https://www.jstor.org/discover/10.2307/4089047?sid=21106224627453&uid=3737536&uid=4&uid=2 Sunning by Black Noddies (''Anous minutus'') may kill chewing lice (''Quadraceps hopkinsi'')]. \u2013 Auk. 112: 1073-1077. {{ISSN|0004-8038}}</ref>\n\n=== Diet ===\n\nThe jacky winter is an [[insectivore]] and a sit-and-search [[predator]], which moves amongst perches to locate food. This is a continuous activity that can cover long distances in order to find prey items.<ref name=\"rec\" /> The jacky winter has two methods of hunting, which include hawking and ground-pouncing. Hawking is when a bird flies and drops to the ground, grabbing their prey during flight, while ground-pouncing is when they fly from a perch, grabbing prey as they land.<ref name=\"mill\">Miller, J. R. and Cale, P. 2000. [http://www.esajournals.org/doi/abs/10.1890/1051-0761(2000)010%5B1732:BMAHUB%5D2.0.CO%3B2 Behavioural mechanisms and habitat use by birds in a fragmented agricultural landscape]. \u2013 Ecological Application. 10: 1732-1748. {{DOI|10.1890/1051-0761(2000)010}}</ref> Both of these hunting styles are used quite commonly by the jacky winter.<ref name=\"rec\" /><ref name=\"mill\" /><ref name=\"re\">Recher, H. F. and Davis Jr, W. E. 2002. [http://www.rswa.org.au/publications/Journal/85%282%29/recher85%282%29.pdf Foraging profile of a Salmon Gum woodland avifauna in Western Australia.] - Journal of the Royal Society of Western Australia. 85: 103-111.</ref>\n\n=== Reproduction ===\n[[File:Jacky winter nesting.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Female nesting]]\nIn many species of birds, the male plumage is quite bright and flamboyant to attract the opposite sex in hope of finding a partner to mate with. The jacky winter is instead a [[sexually monomorphic]] bird, which means that both the male and female are almost identical in appearance.<ref name=\"wood\" /> Rather than plumage playing a significant role in attracting the opposite sex, the jacky winter male uses song to attract a female during courtship.<ref name=\"Kea\" /> In the eastern states of Australia, the jacky winter breeds mostly to the west of the Great Dividing Range, where a suitable habitat of eucalyptus woodland is present. They build a small, open cup-shaped [[nest]], which is often made from grass and bark strips held together by spider webs. The nest is built in an exposed position, usually on a fork of a branch.<ref name=\"wood\" />\n\nThe breeding season of jacky winters occurs from September to November. Leading up to September, singing from the males is at its highest peak, then as the [[nestlings]] are born around late September, the singing becomes quite minimal.<ref name=\"Kea\" /> In late October, the singing increases again, lasting until early November, when the females lay a second [[brooding|brood]] of the season. By late November with the hatching of the young, the males stop singing, making vocalisations almost non-existent from then on. It stays like this until the birds have left the area.<ref name=\"Kea\" /> The nesting period lasts for 15 to 20 days, while the [[Egg incubation|incubation]] is between 16 and 18 days. Only the female will [[Egg incubation|incubate]] the eggs, while the male will help feed the young once they have hatched. 92 per cent of the time, the female will lay only two eggs per clutch.<ref name=\"wood\" />  It is uncommon for this number to vary, since many different [[environment (biophysical)|environmental]] factors determine the number of eggs per clutch in order to maximize the survival rate of fledglings from the nest.<ref>Winkler, D. W. and Walter, J. R. 1983. [https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-1-4615-6781-3_2 The determination of clutch size in precocial birds]. \u2013 Current Ornithology. 1: 33-68. {{DOI|10.1007/978-1-4615-6781-3_2}}</ref>\n\nTerritory size of the jacky winter has been recorded at 1.7 ha, which is similar to other species of ''[[Petroicidae]]'', such as the [[flame robin]] and [[scarlet robin]]. The jacky winter seems to favour habitats for breeding that contain a [[eucalyptus]] box woodland or open box woodland, which have patches of box trees and isolated live trees. Fallen logs and stumps are also favoured in habitat selection.<ref name=\"wood\" /> The jacky winter holds these territories by perching on top of these eucalyptus trees and keeping a regular sustained call. The breeding density of jacky winters is about 17.2&nbsp;ha for one pair.<ref name=\"wood\" /> The jacky winter is known to defend their territory all year around.<ref name=\"reid\" />\n\n== Status ==\n\nThe jacky winter is a common species of bird found throughout [[Australia]], and is described as a bird of [[least concern]] by the [[IUCN]] (International Union for Conservation of Nature). Like many other small woodland birds in [[Australia]], the jacky winter populations are declining and are considered to be a common species but decreasing.<ref name=\"rei\">Reid, J. R. W. 1999. [http://www.environment.nsw.gov.au/resources/nature/wedecliningbirdreport99reid.pdf Threatened and declining birds in the New South Wales Sheep-Wheat Belt: I. Diagnosis, characteristics and management]. Consultancy report to the NSW National Parks and Wildlife Service. \u2013 CSIRO Wildlife and Ecology.</ref>\n\nAll subspecies of the jacky winter in [[Australia]] are declining. ''M. f. fascinans'' is declining throughout [[eastern Australia]], including [[New South Wales]], [[Queensland]] and [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]];<ref name=\"wood\" /><ref name=\"rei\" /><ref name=\"fo\" /> ''M. f. assimilis'' is declining throughout [[Western Australia]] and parts of [[South Australia]];<ref name=\"reid\" /><ref name=\"re\" /> ''M. f. pallida'' is declining throughout parts of [[Queensland]], the [[Northern Territory]], as well as the [[Kimberley (Western Australia)|Kimberley]] in Western Australia.<ref name=\"reid\" />\n\n== Threats ==\n\nA number of species of woodland birds, such as the jacky winter, are declining and going locally [[extinct]], due to the [[habitat fragmentation|fragmentation]] and [[habitat degradation|degradation]] of their habitats. These deleterious changes are not only happening in [[Australia]], but around the world.<ref name=\"fo\">Ford, H. A. 2011. [http://www.publish.csiro.au/?paper=MU09115 The causes of decline of birds of eucalypt woodlands: advances in our knowledge over the last 10 years]. \u2013 Emu 111: 1-9. {{DOI|10.1071/MU09115}}</ref><ref>Ford, H. A., Barrett, G. W., Saunders, D. A. and Recher, H. F. 2001. [http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0006320700001014 Why have birds in the woodlands of Southern Australia declined?] - Biol. Cons. 97: 71-88.</ref><ref>Watson, J., Watson, A., Paull, D. and Freudenberger, D. 2003. [http://search.informit.com.au/documentSummary;dn=876432789629323;res=IELNZC Woodland fragmentation is causing the decline of species and functional groups of birds in southeastern Australia]. \u2013 Pac. Cons. Bio 8: 261-270. {{ISSN|1038-2097}}</ref> Since [[Europe]]an settlement in [[Australia]], much of the woodlands have been converted to [[arable land]] and [[pasture]], for crops to grow and for livestock to graze.<ref name=\"fo\" /> Grazing livestock has impacted the jacky winter by decreasing the amount of small, ground and shrub vegetation, creating a lot of bare ground. This bare ground disadvantages the ground-pouncing jacky winter because a decrease in the larger terrestrial arthropods that they feed upon occurs.<ref name=\"rec\">Recher, H. F., Davis, W. E. and Calver, M. C. 2002. [http://researchrepository.murdoch.edu.au/1009/1/Comparative_foraging_ecology_2002.pdf Comparative foraging ecology of five species of ground-pouncing birds in western Australian woodlands with comments on species decline.] \u2013 Ornithol. Sci. 1: 29-40.</ref>\n\nThe increase of bare ground, created by woodland fragmentation and degradation, can also cause nesting resources of the jacky winter to become scarce due to the increase of weeds in the area. This results in the jacky winter having to try to find another suitable habitat.<ref name=\"keas\">Keast, A. 1995. [http://rzsnsw.metapress.com/content/pv8350n413016014/ Habitat loss and species loss: the birds of Sydney 50 years ago and now.] \u2013 Aust. Zool. 30: 3-25. {{DOI|10.7882/AZ.1995.002}}</ref><ref>Keast, A. 1996. [https://www.jstor.org/discover/10.2307/4088938?sid=21106224360653&uid=3737536&uid=2&uid=4 Wing shape in insectivorous passerines inhabiting New Guinea and Australian rain-forests and eucalypt forest/eucalypt woodlands.] \u2013 Auk 113: 94-104. {{ISSN|0004-8038}}</ref><ref name=\"fo\" /> Finding suitable habitats has become quite difficult for the jacky winter as other birds thrive in these landscapes. The [[noisy miner]] (''Manorina melanocephala'') is a winner of these human-altered landscapes, and is quite aggressive towards other small [[insectivores]], such as the jacky winter. The jacky winter suffers quite negatively from the presence of the noisy miner, as it cannot outcompete it for food resources. The noisy miner has quite a negative impact on tree health, which also limits the availability of suitable nesting material for the jacky winter.<ref>Debus, S. J. S. 2008. [http://www.une.edu.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0011/30143/debus-n-miner.pdf The effect of Noisy Miners in small bush birds]: an unofficial cull and its outcome. - Pac. Cons. Bio. 14: 185-190. {{ISSN|1038-2097}}</ref>\n\n[[Climate change]] also threatens to cause the jacky winter to decline even further. A changing climate caused by [[Climate change|anthropogenic]] sources has already been determined to affect the breeding activity, the timing of [[Bird migration|migration]], and also the [[geographical]] and elevation range of birds quite significantly. These effects are seen all over the world on a number of different species.<ref>Neuh\u04d3user, M. 2007. [http://notornis.osnz.org.nz/system/files/Notornis_54_2_79.pdf Climate change and the arrival of self-introduced bird species in New Zealand]. \u2013 Notornis. 54: 11-14.</ref><ref>Meijer, T., Nienaber, U., Langer, U. and Trillmich, F. 1999. [https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/condor/v101n01/p0124-p0132.pdf Temperature and timing of egg laying of European Starlings]. \u2013 Condor. 101: 124-132 {{DOI|10.2307/1370453}}\n</ref><ref name=\"mac\">Mac Nally, R., Bennett, A. F., Thomson, J. R., Radford, J. Q., Unmack, G., Horrocks, G. and Vesk, P. A. 2009. [http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1472-4642.2009.00578.x/full Collapse of an avifauna: climate change appears to exacerbate habitat loss and degradation]. \u2013 Diversity Distrib. 15: 720-730. {{DOI|10.1111/j.1472-4642.2009.00578}}.</ref><ref>Peh, K. S. H. 2007. [http://www.bioone.org/doi/abs/10.1650/0010-5422(2007)109%5B437:PEOCCO%5D2.0.CO%3B2 Potential effects of climate change on elevational distributions of tropical birds in Southeast Asia]. \u2013 Condor. 109: 437-441. {{DOI|10.1650/0010-5422(2007)109}}</ref> What threatens the jacky winter in Australia is rising temperature and evapotranspiration, causing more droughts and increasing fire severity and frequency.<ref name=\"mac\" /><ref>Lindenmayer, D. B., Wood, J. T., Cunningham, R. B., MacGregor, C., Crane, M., Michael, M., Montague-Drake, R., Brown, B., Muntz, R. and Gill, A. M. 2008. [http://www.esajournals.org/doi/abs/10.1890/07-1943.1 Testing hypotheses associated with bird responses to wildfire]. \u2013 Ecological Application. 18: 1967-1983. {{DOI|10.1890/07-1943.1}}</ref> It is expected that these will impact availability of food, as well as safe nesting sites and refuges from predators.<ref>Ford, H. A., Walters, J. R., Cooper, C. B., Debus, S. J. S. and Doerr, V. A. J. 2009. [http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0006320709003991 Extinction debt or habitat change? \u2013 Ongoing losses of woodland birds in north-eastern New South Wales, Australia]. \u2013 Biol. Cons. 142: 3182-3190.</ref> The rising temperature has already caused birds around the world to decrease in body size. This has been interpreted as a micro-evolutionary response to global climate warming, and to the changes in nutrition associated with declining food availability and habitat quality, which the jacky winter is undergoing in southeastern Australia.<ref>Gardner, J. L., Heinsohn, R. and Joseph, L. 2009. [http://classic.rspb.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/early/2009/08/12/rspb.2009.1011.full Shifting latitudinal clines in avian body size correlate with global warming in Australian passerines]. \u2013 Proc. R. Soc. B \u2013 1-8. {{ISSN|1471-2954}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Commons category|Microeca fascinans}}\n{{Wikispecies|Microeca fascinans}}\n\n{{Petroicidae}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1033170}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:winter, jacky}}\n[[Category:Microeca|jacky winter]]\n[[Category:Birds of Australia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1801|jacky winter]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by John Latham (ornithologist)|jacky winter]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2011}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = Jacky winter \n| image = Jacky Winter - Glen Davis.jpg\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22704769/0 |title=''Microeca fascinans'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Microeca\n| species = fascinans\n| authority = ([[John Latham (ornithologist)|Latham]], 1801)\n| synonyms = \n}}\n\nThe '''jacky winter''' (''Microeca fascinans'') is a small grey-brown robin found commonly throughout [[Australia]] and also in [[Papua New Guinea]]. The jacky winter acquired its name due to rapid and strong vocalisations, which sound like ''jacky-jacky winter-winter''.<ref name=Simpson>Simpson, Ken, Day, N. and Trusler, P. (6th edn., 1999). Field Guide to the Birds of Australia. Ringwood, Victoria: Penguin Books Australia ISBN 067087918-5.</ref> Their call is also often referred to as sounding like ''peter-peter-peter''.<ref name=Slater>Slater, Peter (1974) A Field Guide to Australian Birds: Passerines. Adelaide: Rigby. ISBN 085179813-6</ref> Its habitats include open woodlands and farmlands.\n\n== Taxonomy and distribution ==\n\nThe jacky winter belongs to the family of [[Australasia]]n robins and flycatchers ''[[Petroicidae]]''. This family includes around 49 species in around 19 genera that are all endemic to [[Australasia]].<ref>Gill, F. and D. Donsker, eds. (2020). IOC World Bird List (v 10.1). Doi 10.14344/IOC.ML.10.1.  http://www.worldbirdnames.org/</ref><ref>Loynes, K., Joseph, L. and Keogh, J. S. 2009. [http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1055790309002000 Multi-locus phylogeny clarifies the systematics of the Australo-Papuan robins (Family Petroicidae, Passeriformes)]. \u2013 Mol. Phyl. Evol. 53: 212-219. {{DOI|10.1016/j.ympev.2009.05.012}}</ref> The family ''[[Petroicidae]]'' evolved in a similar way to the [[Australo-Papuan]] warblers (''[[Acanthizidae]]'')\u2014the latter evolved in isolation from similar families to them, namely ''[[Parulidae]]'' and ''[[Sylviidae]]'', which occupied comparable niches in other continental regions, such as [[Central America|Central]][[South America|/South America]] and [[Eurasia]], respectively.<ref>Ericson, p. G. P., Irestedt, M. and Johansson, U.S. 2003. [http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1034/j.1600-048X.2003.03121.x/abstract?deniedAccessCustomisedMessage=&userIsAuthenticated=false Evolution, biogeography, and patters of diversification in passerine birds]. \u2013 J. Avian. Biol. 34: 3-15. {{DOI|10.1034/j.1600-048X.2003.03121.x}}</ref> ''[[Petroicidae]]'' evolved in the [[Australo-Papuan]] area to fill an ecological niche, which was already being used by New World flycatchers (''[[Tyrannidae]]'') in [[North America]] and [[South America]], and by Old World flycatchers (''[[Muscicapidae]]'') in [[Europe]], [[Africa]], and [[Asia]]. This is an example of [[convergent evolution]].<ref name=\"Chris\">Christidis, L., Irestedt, M., Rowe, D., Boles, W. E. and Norman, J. A. 2011. [http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1055790311003587 Mitochondrial and nuclear DNA phylogenies reveal a complex evolutionary history in the Australasian robin (Passeriformes: Petroicidae).] \u2013 Mol. Phyl. Evol. 61: 726-738. {{DOI|10.1016/j.ympev.2011.08.014}}</ref><ref>Sangster, G., Alstrom, P., Forsmark, E. and Olsson, U. 2010. [http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1055790310003076 Multi-locus phylogenetic analysis of Old World chats and flycatchers reveals extensive paraphyly at family, subfamily and genus level (Aves Muscicapidae)] \u2013 Mol. Phyl. Evol. 57: 380-392. {{DOI|10.1016/j.ympev.2010.07.008}}</ref>\n\nThe generic name ''Microeca'' derives from the Greek ''micros'' meaning 'small' and ''oikos'' meaning 'house'. This refers to the fact that they build the smallest nest of any Australian bird.<ref name=Helm>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling|title=Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird-names|last=Jobling|first=James A.|accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref> The specific name ''fascinans'' is Latin for 'fascinating' and derives from ''fascinare'' meaning 'to bewitch'.<ref name=Helm></ref>\n\nOther vernacular names for the jacky winter are brown flycatcher, peter peter, postboy, spinks and stumpbird.<ref name=Slater></ref><ref>Pizzey, Graham; Doyle, Roy (1980) A Field Guide to the Birds of Australia. Collins Publishers, Sydney. ISBN 073222436-5</ref>\n\nThere are three races of jacky winter found in [[Australia]]. ''Microeca fascinans fascinans'' (''leucophaea'') is the most familiar race, and is found in central and eastern [[Queensland]], [[New South Wales]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], and southeastern [[South Australia]]. There are also ''Microeca fascinans assimilis'', which is found in [[South Australia]] and south [[Western Australia]], and ''Microeca fascinans pallida'', which is found in northern and western [[Queensland]], [[Northern Territory]], and the [[Kimberley]] in Western Australia.<ref name=Simpson></ref><ref name=\"Chris\" /><ref>Morcombe, Michael (2012) Field guide to Australian birds. Pascal Press, Glebe, NSW. Revised edition. ISBN 978174021417-9</ref><ref name=\"reid\">Reid, J. R. W. and Gillen, J. S. 2013. [http://www.naturalresources.sa.gov.au/files/d137ff65-3033-48e5-8200-a2de00e18b97/cooper-catchment-2013-birds-rep.pdf. Riparian bird assembladges of Cooper Creek, South Australia]. \u2013 South Australian Arid Lands Natural Resources Management Board.</ref> ''Microeca fascinans zimmeri'' is a subspecies of jacky winter found in Papua New Guinea <ref>Bell, H. L. 2008. [http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1474-919X.1982.tb03772.x/abstract Abundance and seasonality of the savannah avifauna at Port Moresby, Papua New Guinea]. \u2013 Ibis 124: 252-274. {{DOI|10.1111/j.1474-919X.1982.tb03772.x}}</ref>\n\n== Description ==\n\nThe jacky winter is around 12 \u2013 14&nbsp;cm in length (including the tail) and its weight varies from 14 \u2013 18 g.<ref name=\"wood\">Wood, K. A, Thompson, N. and Ley, A. J. 2008. [http://search.informit.com.au/documentSummary;dn=407981259692578;res=IELHSS Breeding Territories and Breeding Success of the Jacky Winter Microeca fasinans in South-eastern Queensland]. \u2013 Australian Field Ornithology 25: 121-131. {{ISSN|1448-0107}}</ref> The plumage of ''M. f. fascinans'' includes a greyish breast with white on the bottom half, its head and back is greyish-brown, while its wings are a darker brown with white edges. The bill is black, it has a narrow eye-line and a buff [[alula]] stripe. The tail of ''M. f. fascinans'' is blackish brown with white outer feathers. Its legs are black. Subspecies ''M. f. assimilis'' is very similar to ''M. f. fascinans''; however, it is darker, with more grey over the breast and flanks, covering up the white which is seen on ''M. f. fascinans''.<ref name=\"wood\" /> ''M. f. pallida'' is smaller than the other two subspecies, being only around 13&nbsp;cm. ''M. f. pallida'' is much more pallid than the other subspecies, and is usually a sandy brown colour.<ref name=\"reid\" />\n\n== Behaviour ==\n[[File:Jacky-winter96.ogg|thumb|300px|Rush Creek, south-east Queensland]]\n\nThe jacky winter can be heard vocalising before sunrise and usually stops towards the middle of the day. Occasionally closer to sunset, it can be heard again.<ref name=\"Kea\">Keast, A. 1994. [http://www.publish.csiro.au/?paper=MU9940230 The Annual Cycle in a Vocalisation Context: a Comparison of the Eastern Yellow Robin Eopsaltria australis and the Jacky Winter Microeca leucophaea.] \u2013 Emu 94: 230-238. {{doi|10.1071/MU9940230}}</ref> During the day they can be seen perched atop trees and posts, [[preening]] their [[feathers]] or even sunning to kill the [[parasites]], which may be present in amongst the feathers.<ref>Moyer, B. R. and Wagenbach, G. E. 1995. [https://www.jstor.org/discover/10.2307/4089047?sid=21106224627453&uid=3737536&uid=4&uid=2 Sunning by Black Noddies (''Anous minutus'') may kill chewing lice (''Quadraceps hopkinsi'')]. \u2013 Auk. 112: 1073-1077. {{ISSN|0004-8038}}</ref>\n\n=== Diet ===\n\nThe jacky winter is an [[insectivore]] and a sit-and-search [[predator]], which moves amongst perches to locate food. This is a continuous activity that can cover long distances in order to find prey items.<ref name=\"rec\" /> The jacky winter has two methods of hunting, which include hawking and ground-pouncing. Hawking is when a bird flies and drops to the ground, grabbing their prey during flight, while ground-pouncing is when they fly from a perch, grabbing prey as they land.<ref name=\"mill\">Miller, J. R. and Cale, P. 2000. [http://www.esajournals.org/doi/abs/10.1890/1051-0761(2000)010%5B1732:BMAHUB%5D2.0.CO%3B2 Behavioural mechanisms and habitat use by birds in a fragmented agricultural landscape]. \u2013 Ecological Application. 10: 1732-1748. {{DOI|10.1890/1051-0761(2000)010}}</ref> Both of these hunting styles are used quite commonly by the jacky winter.<ref name=\"rec\" /><ref name=\"mill\" /><ref name=\"re\">Recher, H. F. and Davis Jr, W. E. 2002. [http://www.rswa.org.au/publications/Journal/85%282%29/recher85%282%29.pdf Foraging profile of a Salmon Gum woodland avifauna in Western Australia.] - Journal of the Royal Society of Western Australia. 85: 103-111.</ref>\n\n=== Reproduction ===\n[[File:Jacky winter nesting.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Female nesting]]\nIn many species of birds, the male plumage is quite bright and flamboyant to attract the opposite sex in hope of finding a partner to mate with. The jacky winter is instead a [[sexually monomorphic]] bird, which means that both the male and female are almost identical in appearance.<ref name=\"wood\" /> Rather than plumage playing a significant role in attracting the opposite sex, the jacky winter male uses song to attract a female during courtship.<ref name=\"Kea\" /> In the eastern states of Australia, the jacky winter breeds mostly to the west of the Great Dividing Range, where a suitable habitat of eucalyptus woodland is present. They build a small, open cup-shaped [[nest]], which is often made from grass and bark strips held together by spider webs. The nest is built in an exposed position, usually on a fork of a branch.<ref name=\"wood\" />\n\nThe breeding season of jacky winters occurs from September to November. Leading up to September, singing from the males is at its highest peak, then as the [[nestlings]] are born around late September, the singing becomes quite minimal.<ref name=\"Kea\" /> In late October, the singing increases again, lasting until early November, when the females lay a second [[brooding|brood]] of the season. By late November with the hatching of the young, the males stop singing, making vocalisations almost non-existent from then on. It stays like this until the birds have left the area.<ref name=\"Kea\" /> The nesting period lasts for 15 to 20 days, while the [[Egg incubation|incubation]] is between 16 and 18 days. Only the female will [[Egg incubation|incubate]] the eggs, while the male will help feed the young once they have hatched. 92 per cent of the time, the female will lay only two eggs per clutch.<ref name=\"wood\" />  It is uncommon for this number to vary, since many different [[environment (biophysical)|environmental]] factors determine the number of eggs per clutch in order to maximize the survival rate of fledglings from the nest.<ref>Winkler, D. W. and Walter, J. R. 1983. [https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-1-4615-6781-3_2 The determination of clutch size in precocial birds]. \u2013 Current Ornithology. 1: 33-68. {{DOI|10.1007/978-1-4615-6781-3_2}}</ref>\n\nTerritory size of the jacky winter has been recorded at 1.7 ha, which is similar to other species of ''[[Petroicidae]]'', such as the [[flame robin]] and [[scarlet robin]]. The jacky winter seems to favour habitats for breeding that contain a [[eucalyptus]] box woodland or open box woodland, which have patches of box trees and isolated live trees. Fallen logs and stumps are also favoured in habitat selection.<ref name=\"wood\" /> The jacky winter holds these territories by perching on top of these eucalyptus trees and keeping a regular sustained call. The breeding density of jacky winters is about 17.2&nbsp;ha for one pair.<ref name=\"wood\" /> The jacky winter is known to defend their territory all year around.<ref name=\"reid\" />\n\n== Status ==\n\nThe jacky winter is a common species of bird found throughout [[Australia]], and is described as a bird of [[least concern]] by the [[IUCN]] (International Union for Conservation of Nature). Like many other small woodland birds in [[Australia]], the jacky winter populations are declining and are considered to be a common species but decreasing.<ref name=\"rei\">Reid, J. R. W. 1999. [http://www.environment.nsw.gov.au/resources/nature/wedecliningbirdreport99reid.pdf Threatened and declining birds in the New South Wales Sheep-Wheat Belt: I. Diagnosis, characteristics and management]. Consultancy report to the NSW National Parks and Wildlife Service. \u2013 CSIRO Wildlife and Ecology.</ref>\n\nAll subspecies of the jacky winter in [[Australia]] are declining. ''M. f. fascinans'' is declining throughout [[eastern Australia]], including [[New South Wales]], [[Queensland]] and [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]];<ref name=\"wood\" /><ref name=\"rei\" /><ref name=\"fo\" /> ''M. f. assimilis'' is declining throughout [[Western Australia]] and parts of [[South Australia]];<ref name=\"reid\" /><ref name=\"re\" /> ''M. f. pallida'' is declining throughout parts of [[Queensland]], the [[Northern Territory]], as well as the [[Kimberley (Western Australia)|Kimberley]] in Western Australia.<ref name=\"reid\" />\n\n== Threats ==\n\nA number of species of woodland birds, such as the jacky winter, are declining and going locally [[extinct]], due to the [[habitat fragmentation|fragmentation]] and [[habitat degradation|degradation]] of their habitats. These deleterious changes are not only happening in [[Australia]], but around the world.<ref name=\"fo\">Ford, H. A. 2011. [http://www.publish.csiro.au/?paper=MU09115 The causes of decline of birds of eucalypt woodlands: advances in our knowledge over the last 10 years]. \u2013 Emu 111: 1-9. {{DOI|10.1071/MU09115}}</ref><ref>Ford, H. A., Barrett, G. W., Saunders, D. A. and Recher, H. F. 2001. [http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0006320700001014 Why have birds in the woodlands of Southern Australia declined?] - Biol. Cons. 97: 71-88.</ref><ref>Watson, J., Watson, A., Paull, D. and Freudenberger, D. 2003. [http://search.informit.com.au/documentSummary;dn=876432789629323;res=IELNZC Woodland fragmentation is causing the decline of species and functional groups of birds in southeastern Australia]. \u2013 Pac. Cons. Bio 8: 261-270. {{ISSN|1038-2097}}</ref> Since [[Europe]]an settlement in [[Australia]], much of the woodlands have been converted to [[arable land]] and [[pasture]], for crops to grow and for livestock to graze.<ref name=\"fo\" /> Grazing livestock has impacted the jacky winter by decreasing the amount of small, ground and shrub vegetation, creating a lot of bare ground. This bare ground disadvantages the ground-pouncing jacky winter because a decrease in the larger terrestrial arthropods that they feed upon occurs.<ref name=\"rec\">Recher, H. F., Davis, W. E. and Calver, M. C. 2002. [http://researchrepository.murdoch.edu.au/1009/1/Comparative_foraging_ecology_2002.pdf Comparative foraging ecology of five species of ground-pouncing birds in western Australian woodlands with comments on species decline.] \u2013 Ornithol. Sci. 1: 29-40.</ref>\n\nThe increase of bare ground created by woodland fragmentation and degradation can also cause nesting resources of the jacky winter to become scarce due to the increase of weeds in the area. This results in the jacky winter having to try to find another suitable habitat.<ref name=\"keas\">Keast, A. 1995. [http://rzsnsw.metapress.com/content/pv8350n413016014/ Habitat loss and species loss: the birds of Sydney 50 years ago and now.] \u2013 Aust. Zool. 30: 3-25. {{DOI|10.7882/AZ.1995.002}}</ref><ref>Keast, A. 1996. [https://www.jstor.org/discover/10.2307/4088938?sid=21106224360653&uid=3737536&uid=2&uid=4 Wing shape in insectivorous passerines inhabiting New Guinea and Australian rain-forests and eucalypt forest/eucalypt woodlands.] \u2013 Auk 113: 94-104. {{ISSN|0004-8038}}</ref><ref name=\"fo\" /> Finding suitable habitats has become quite difficult for the jacky winter as other birds thrive in these landscapes. The [[noisy miner]] (''Manorina melanocephala'') is a winner of these human-altered landscapes, and is quite aggressive towards other small [[insectivores]], such as the jacky winter. The jacky winter suffers quite negatively from the presence of the noisy miner, as it cannot outcompete it for food resources. The noisy miner has quite a negative impact on tree health, which also limits the availability of suitable nesting material for the jacky winter.<ref>Debus, S. J. S. 2008. [http://www.une.edu.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0011/30143/debus-n-miner.pdf The effect of Noisy Miners in small bush birds]: an unofficial cull and its outcome. - Pac. Cons. Bio. 14: 185-190. {{ISSN|1038-2097}}</ref>\n\n[[Climate change]] also threatens to cause the jacky winter to decline even further. A changing climate caused by [[Climate change|anthropogenic]] sources has already been determined to affect the breeding activity, the timing of [[Bird migration|migration]] and also the [[geographical]] and elevation range of birds quite significantly. These are seen all over the world on a number of different species.<ref>Neuh\u04d3user, M. 2007. [http://notornis.osnz.org.nz/system/files/Notornis_54_2_79.pdf Climate change and the arrival of self-introduced bird species in New Zealand]. \u2013 Notornis. 54: 11-14.</ref><ref>Meijer, T., Nienaber, U., Langer, U. and Trillmich, F. 1999. [https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/condor/v101n01/p0124-p0132.pdf Temperature and timing of egg laying of European Starlings]. \u2013 Condor. 101: 124-132 {{DOI|10.2307/1370453}}\n</ref><ref name=\"mac\">Mac Nally, R., Bennett, A. F., Thomson, J. R., Radford, J. Q., Unmack, G., Horrocks, G. and Vesk, P. A. 2009. [http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1472-4642.2009.00578.x/full Collapse of an avifauna: climate change appears to exacerbate habitat loss and degradation]. \u2013 Diversity Distrib. 15: 720-730. {{DOI|10.1111/j.1472-4642.2009.00578}}.</ref><ref>Peh, K. S. H. 2007. [http://www.bioone.org/doi/abs/10.1650/0010-5422(2007)109%5B437:PEOCCO%5D2.0.CO%3B2 Potential effects of climate change on elevational distributions of tropical birds in Southeast Asia]. \u2013 Condor. 109: 437-441. {{DOI|10.1650/0010-5422(2007)109}}</ref> What threatens the jacky winter in Australia is increasing temperature and evapotranspiration, causing more droughts and increasing fire severity and frequency.<ref name=\"mac\" /><ref>Lindenmayer, D. B., Wood, J. T., Cunningham, R. B., MacGregor, C., Crane, M., Michael, M., Montague-Drake, R., Brown, B., Muntz, R. and Gill, A. M. 2008. [http://www.esajournals.org/doi/abs/10.1890/07-1943.1 Testing hypotheses associated with bird responses to wildfire]. \u2013 Ecological Application. 18: 1967-1983. {{DOI|10.1890/07-1943.1}}</ref> It is expected that these will impact availability of food, as well as safe nesting sites and refuges from predators.<ref>Ford, H. A., Walters, J. R., Cooper, C. B., Debus, S. J. S. and Doerr, V. A. J. 2009. [http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0006320709003991 Extinction debt or habitat change? \u2013 Ongoing losses of woodland birds in north-eastern New South Wales, Australia]. \u2013 Biol. Cons. 142: 3182-3190.</ref> The increasing temperature has already caused birds around the world to decrease in body size. This has been interpreted as a micro evolutionary response to global climate warming and the changes in nutrition associated with food availability and habitat quality which the jacky winter is undergoing in southeastern Australia.<ref>Gardner, J. L., Heinsohn, R. and Joseph, L. 2009. [http://classic.rspb.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/early/2009/08/12/rspb.2009.1011.full Shifting latitudinal clines in avian body size correlate with global warming in Australian passerines]. \u2013 Proc. R. Soc. B \u2013 1-8. {{ISSN|1471-2954}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Commons category|Microeca fascinans}}\n{{Wikispecies|Microeca fascinans}}\n\n{{Petroicidae}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1033170}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:winter, jacky}}\n[[Category:Microeca|jacky winter]]\n[[Category:Birds of Australia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1801|jacky winter]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by John Latham (ornithologist)|jacky winter]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n", "name_user": "Rogermccart", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eThreats:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jacky_winter"}
{"title_page": "Sivachandran", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{About||the Singaporean film editor|Siva Chandran}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Sivachandran\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Narayanan\n| birth_date         = \n| birth_place        = \n| occupation         = Actor, director, writer\n| othername          = M. Sivachandran\n| years active       = 1976\u20131999\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Lakshmi (actress)|Lakshmi]]|1987}}\n| parents            = \n| children           = \n}}\n'''Narayanan''', better known by his stage name '''Sivachandran''', is an Indian film actor, director, and writer.\n\n== Career ==\nSivachandran made his film debut in ''[[Pattina Pravesam]]'' (1977) as one of the lead actors.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Raman |first=Mohan |url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/kb-kollywoods-discovery-channel/article6751541.ece |title=KB: Kollywood\u2019s Discovery Channel |date=3 January 2015 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=26 January 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150501063135/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/kb-kollywoods-discovery-channel/article6751541.ece |archive-date=1 May 2015 |author-link=Mohan Raman}}</ref> He later starred in ''Annapoorani'' (1978) with [[R. Muthuraman]] in a negative role. He went on to star in notable films include ''[[Aval Appadithan]]'' (1978) and  ''[[Polladhavan (1980 film)|Polladhavan]]'' (1980).<ref name=\"A\">{{Cite web |url=https://antrukandamugam.wordpress.com/2013/08/23/sivachandran/ |title=Sivachandran |date=23 August 2013 |website=Antrukandamugam |access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> He made his directorial debut with  ''[[En Uyir Kannamma]]'' (1988) and went on to direct several films with [[Prabhu (actor)|Prabhu]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=P9oYG7HA76QC&dat=19880129&printsec=frontpage&hl=en |title=Good debut |date=29 January 1988 |work=[[The Indian Express]] |page=5}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nSivachandran was born as Narayanan. He changed his name to Sivachandran and started his acting career. The stage name is a portmaneau of \"Siva\" from [[Sivaji Ganesan]] and \"Chandran\" from [[M. G. Ramachandran]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gm2DKWPJoVw |title=\"\u0baa\u0bbe\u0bb0\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bbe\u0b9c\u0bbe \u0ba4\u0ba8\u0bcd\u0ba4 \u0bb5\u0bbe\u0baf\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc8 \u0bae\u0bb1\u0bc1\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bc7\u0ba9\u0bcd\" \u2013 Exclusive Interview With Siva Chandran {{!}} Rewind With Ramji |last=Hindu Tamil Thisai |authorlink=Hindu Tamil Thisai |date=18 November 2019 |language=ta |via=YouTube |access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> He married actress [[Lakshmi (actress)|Lakshmi]], whom he co-starred in ''[[En Uyir Kannamma]]'' (1988). He fell in love with her on the sets of the film.<ref name=\"A\" /> He colloborated with Lakshmi again in ''[[Raththa Dhanam]]'' (1988) and ''Jodi Sendhachu'' (1992), which was directed by Lakshmi herself. Sivachandran and Lakshmi adopted a  girl, Samyuktha, in 2000.<ref>{{cite news|title=\"I'll act till my last breath\" \u2013 Lakshmi |url= http://www.screenindia.com/old/20010727/rkan3.html |date= 27 July 2007 |work= Screen |accessdate=22 July 2009}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n=== As actor ===\n;Films\n{{expand list|date=April 2020}}\n<!--Ivargal Vithiyasamanavargal-->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Film\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1976 || ''Ithu Ivargalin Kathai'' || ||\n|-\n| 1977 || ''[[Pattina Pravesam]]'' || Kumaran ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|1978 || ''[[Aval Appadithan]]'' || Mano ||\n|-\n| ''Annapoorani'' || ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|1979 || ''[[Rosappu Ravikkaikari]]'' ||  Manickam ||\n|-\n| ''Pancha Kalyani'' || ||\n|-\n| ''Nee Sirithal Naan Sirippen'' || ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\"|1980 || ''Thunive Thozhan'' || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Mangala Nayagi]]'' || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Natchathiram]]'' || ||\n|-\n| ''Soundaryame Varuga Varuga''  || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Vandichakkaram]]'' || Sarathi ||\n|-\n| ''[[Polladhavan (1980 film)|Polladhavan]]'' || Chandru ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"|1981|| ''[[Ram Lakshman]]'' || Kumar ||\n|-\n| ''[[Rani Theni]]'' || Sekhar ||\n|-\n| ''Nellikani'' || ||\n|-\n| ''Nenjil Oru Mul'' || ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\"|1982 || ''[[Anandha Ragam]]'' || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Parvaiyin Marupakkam]]'' || Siva ||\n|-\n| ''Kaduvulluku Oru Kadidham'' || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Antha Rathirikku Satchi Illai]]'' || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Simla Special]]'' || Thief ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|1983 || ''[[Vellai Roja]]'' ||  Chinna Durai ||\n|-\n| ''Dhandikappata Nyayangal'' || ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\"|1984 || ''[[Anbe Odi Vaa]]'' || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Ezhuthatha Sattangal]]'' || ||\n|-\n| ''Antha June 16 Am Naal'' || ||\n|-\n| ''Antha Uravukku Satchi'' || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Naalai Unathu Naal]]'' ||  Vivekananthan / Prakash ||\n|-\n| ''[[Vamsa Vilakku]]'' || Ravi ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"|1985 || ''Sivappu Nila'' || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Navagraha Nayagi]]'' || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Naam Iruvar (1985 film)|Naam Iruvar]]'' || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Needhiyin Nizhal]]'' || Sukumar ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"|1986 || ''[[December Pookal]]'' || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Poi Mugangal]]'' || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Murattu Karangal]]'' || Rahman ||\n|-\n| ''[[Oru Iniya Udhayam]]'' || Siva ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 1987 || ''[[Kadamai Kanniyam Kattupaadu]]'' || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Mangai Oru Gangai]]'' || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Anand (1987 film)|Anand]]''  || || Also dialogue writer\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1988 || ''[[En Uyir Kannamma]]'' || Madhavan || Also director\n|-\n| ''[[Raththa Dhanam]]'' || || Also director\n|-\n| 1990 || ''[[Nyayangal Jayikkattum]]'' || Victor Raj || Also director\n|-\n| 1992 || ''Jodi Sendhachu'' || ||\n|-\n| 1995 || ''[[Kattumarakaran]]'' || Vijay Raghavan ||\n|}\n;Television\n*''Arasi'' (Sun TV)\n*''Mahalakshmi'' (Kalaignar TV)\n=== As director ===\n* ''[[En Uyir Kannamma]]'' (1988)\n* ''[[Raththa Dhanam]]'' (1988)\n* ''[[Nyayangal Jayikkattum]]'' (1990)\n* ''[[Manam Virumbuthe Unnai]]'' (1999)\n\n=== As story writer ===\n* ''[[Anbe Odi Vaa]]'' (1984)\n* ''[[Shankar Guru (1987 film)|Shankar Guru]]'' (1987)\n\n=== As dialogue writer ===\n* ''[[Anand (1987 film)|Anand]]'' (1987)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{IMDb name|8906549}}\n{{Sivachandran}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Indian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Indian film directors]]\n[[Category:Tamil male actors]]\n[[Category:Tamil film directors]]\n[[Category:Male actors in Tamil cinema]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian male actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{About||the Singaporean film editor|Siva Chandran}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Sivachandran\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Narayanan\n| birth_date         = \n| birth_place        = \n| occupation         = Actor, director, writer\n| othername          = M. Sivachandran\n| years active       = 1976\u20131999\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Lakshmi (actress)|Lakshmi]]|1987}}\n| parents            = \n| children           = \n}}\n'''Narayanan''', better known by his stage name '''Sivachandran''', is an Indian film actor, director, and writer.\n\n== Career ==\nSivachandran made his film debut in ''[[Pattina Pravesam]]'' (1977) as one of the lead actors.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Raman |first=Mohan |url=https://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/kb-kollywoods-discovery-channel/article6751541.ece |title=KB: Kollywood\u2019s Discovery Channel |date=3 January 2015 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=26 January 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150501063135/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/kb-kollywoods-discovery-channel/article6751541.ece |archive-date=1 May 2015 |author-link=Mohan Raman}}</ref> He later starred in ''Annapoorani'' (1978) with [[R. Muthuraman]] in a negative role. He went on to star in notable films include ''[[Aval Appadithan]]'' (1978) and  ''[[Polladhavan (1980 film)|Polladhavan]]'' (1980).<ref name=\"A\">{{Cite web |url=https://antrukandamugam.wordpress.com/2013/08/23/sivachandran/ |title=Sivachandran |date=August 23, 2013 |website=Antrukandamugam |access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> He made his directorial debut with  ''[[En Uyir Kannamma]]'' (1988) and went on to direct several films with [[Prabhu (actor)|Prabhu]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=P9oYG7HA76QC&dat=19880129&printsec=frontpage&hl=en |title=Good debut |date=29 January 1988 |work=[[The Indian Express]] |page=5}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nSivachandran was born as Narayanan. He changed his name to Sivachandran and started his acting career. The stage name is a portmaneau of \"Siva\" from [[Sivaji Ganesan]] and \"Chandran\" from [[M. G. Ramachandran]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gm2DKWPJoVw |title=\"\u0baa\u0bbe\u0bb0\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bbe\u0b9c\u0bbe \u0ba4\u0ba8\u0bcd\u0ba4 \u0bb5\u0bbe\u0baf\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc8 \u0bae\u0bb1\u0bc1\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bc7\u0ba9\u0bcd\" \u2013 Exclusive Interview With Siva Chandran {{!}} Rewind With Ramji |last=Hindu Tamil Thisai |authorlink=Hindu Tamil Thisai |date=18 November 2019 |language=ta |via=YouTube |access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> He married actress [[Lakshmi (actress)|Lakshmi]], whom he co-starred in ''[[En Uyir Kannamma]]'' (1988). He fell in love with her on the sets of the film.<ref name=\"A\" /> He colloborated with Lakshmi again in ''[[Raththa Dhanam]]'' (1988) and ''Jodi Sendhachu'' (1992), which was directed by Lakshmi herself. Sivachandran and Lakshmi adopted a  girl, Samyuktha, in 2000.<ref>{{cite news|title=\"I'll act till my last breath\" \u2013 Lakshmi |url= http://www.screenindia.com/old/20010727/rkan3.html |date= 27 July 2007 |work= Screen |accessdate=22 July 2009}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n=== As actor ===\n;Films\n{{expand list|date=April 2020}}\n<!--Ivargal Vithiyasamanavargal-->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Film\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1976 || ''Ithu Ivargalin Kathai'' || ||\n|-\n| 1977 || ''[[Pattina Pravesam]]'' || Kumaran ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|1978 || ''[[Aval Appadithan]]'' || Mano ||\n|-\n| ''Annapoorani'' || ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|1979 || ''[[Rosappu Ravikkaikari]]'' ||  Manickam ||\n|-\n| ''Pancha Kalyani'' || ||\n|-\n| ''Nee Sirithal Naan Sirippen'' || ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\"|1980 || ''Thunive Thozhan'' || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Mangala Nayagi]]'' || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Natchathiram]]'' || ||\n|-\n| ''Soundaryame Varuga Varuga''  || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Vandichakkaram]]'' || Sarathi ||\n|-\n| ''[[Polladhavan (1980 film)|Polladhavan]]'' || Chandru ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"|1981|| ''[[Ram Lakshman]]'' || Kumar ||\n|-\n| ''[[Rani Theni]]'' || Sekhar ||\n|-\n| ''Nellikani'' || ||\n|-\n| ''Nenjil Oru Mul'' || ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\"|1982 || ''[[Anandha Ragam]]'' || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Parvaiyin Marupakkam]]'' || Siva ||\n|-\n| ''Kaduvulluku Oru Kadidham'' || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Antha Rathirikku Satchi Illai]]'' || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Simla Special]]'' || Thief ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|1983 || ''[[Vellai Roja]]'' ||  Chinna Durai ||\n|-\n| ''Dhandikappata Nyayangal'' || ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\"|1984 || ''[[Anbe Odi Vaa]]'' || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Ezhuthatha Sattangal]]'' || ||\n|-\n| ''Antha June 16 Am Naal'' || ||\n|-\n| ''Antha Uravukku Satchi'' || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Naalai Unathu Naal]]'' ||  Vivekananthan / Prakash ||\n|-\n| ''[[Vamsa Vilakku]]'' || Ravi ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"|1985 || ''Sivappu Nila'' || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Navagraha Nayagi]]'' || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Naam Iruvar (1985 film)|Naam Iruvar]]'' || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Needhiyin Nizhal]]'' || Sukumar ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"|1986 || ''[[December Pookal]]'' || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Poi Mugangal]]'' || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Murattu Karangal]]'' || Rahman ||\n|-\n| ''[[Oru Iniya Udhayam]]'' || Siva ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 1987 || ''[[Kadamai Kanniyam Kattupaadu]]'' || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Mangai Oru Gangai]]'' || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Anand (1987 film)|Anand]]''  || || Also dialogue writer\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1988 || ''[[En Uyir Kannamma]]'' || Madhavan || Also director\n|-\n| ''[[Raththa Dhanam]]'' || || Also director\n|-\n| 1990 || ''[[Nyayangal Jayikkattum]]'' || Victor Raj || Also director\n|-\n| 1992 || ''Jodi Sendhachu'' || ||\n|-\n| 1995 || ''[[Kattumarakaran]]'' || Vijay Raghavan ||\n|}\n;Television\n*''Arasi'' (Sun TV)\n*''Mahalakshmi'' (Kalaignar TV)\n=== As director ===\n* ''[[En Uyir Kannamma]]'' (1988)\n* ''[[Raththa Dhanam]]'' (1988)\n* ''[[Nyayangal Jayikkattum]]'' (1990)\n* ''[[Manam Virumbuthe Unnai]]'' (1999)\n\n=== As story writer ===\n* ''[[Anbe Odi Vaa]]'' (1984)\n* ''[[Shankar Guru (1987 film)|Shankar Guru]]'' (1987)\n\n=== As dialogue writer ===\n* ''[[Anand (1987 film)|Anand]]'' (1987)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{IMDb name|8906549}}\n{{Sivachandran}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Indian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Indian film directors]]\n[[Category:Tamil male actors]]\n[[Category:Tamil film directors]]\n[[Category:Male actors in Tamil cinema]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian male actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Kailash29792", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sivachandran"}
{"title_page": "Ahmed Jahouh", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Ahmed Jahouh\n| fullname = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1988|7|31}}<ref name=\"SW\">{{Soccerway|ahmed-jahouh/271173|accessdate=28 April 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Al Aaroui]], [[Morocco]]<ref name=\"MK\"/>\n| height = 1.87 m<ref name=\"SW\"/>\n| position = [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|Defensive midfielder]]\n| currentclub = [[Mumbai City FC|Mumbai City]]\n| clubnumber = 5\n| youthyears1= \n| youthclubs1= \n| years1 = 2006\u20132010 | years2 = 2010\u20132015 | years3 = 2012\u20132013 | years4 = 2015\u20132016 | years5 = 2016\u20132017 | years6 = 2017\u20132020 | years7 = 2020\u2013\n| clubs1 = [[Ittihad Khemisset]] | clubs2 = [[Moghreb T\u00e9touan]] | clubs3 = \u2192 [[Al-Ittihad Kalba SC|Al-Ittihad Kalba]] (loan) | clubs4 = [[Raja Casablanca]] | clubs5 = [[Fath Union Sport|FUS Rabat]] | clubs6 = [[FC Goa|Goa]] | clubs7 = [[Mumbai City FC|Mumbai City]]\n| caps1 = | goals1 =  | caps2 = 99 | goals2 = 9 | caps3 = 9 | goals3 = 1 | caps4 = 13 | goals4 = 2 | caps5 = 19| goals5 = 1 | caps6 = 53 | goals6 = 1 | caps7 = 0 | goals7 = 0\n| nationalyears1= 2012\u20132016\n| nationalteam1= [[Morocco national football team|Morocco]]\n| nationalcaps1= 8 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n| club-update = 9 February 2020\n| ntupdate = \n}}\n\n'''Ahmed Jahouh''' (born 31 July 1988) is a Moroccan professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays for Indian club [[Mumbai City FC|Mumbai City]], as a [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|defensive midfielder]].\n\nHe has been capped by [[Morocco national football team|Morocco]] at senior international level.\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[Al Aaroui]], Jahouh started his career with [[Ittihad Khemisset]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Mon absence du CHAN est une d\u00e9ception am\u00e8re [My absence from CHAN is a bitter disappointment]|url=https://lematin.ma/journal/2014/entretien-avec-ahmed-jahouh-joueur-du-moghreb-de-tetouan_-mon-absence-du-chan-est-une-deception-amere-/194888.html|publisher=Le Matin|accessdate=28 April 2018|language=French|date=13 January 2014}}</ref>  In 2010, he joined [[Moghreb T\u00e9touan]].<ref>{{cite web|author1=Mohammed Daroulche|title=Transferts: Ahmed Jahouh enfin au Raja [Transfers: Ahmed Jahouh finally at Raja]|url=http://fr.le360.ma/sports/transferts-ahmed-jahouh-enfin-au-raja-50489|publisher=Sport 360|accessdate=28 April 2018|language=French|date=9 September 2015}}</ref> Jahouh went on to win the [[2011\u201312 Botola]] and the [[2013\u201314 Botola]] with Moghreb.<ref name=\"Indian Super League: FC Goa signs Moroccan International Ahmed Jahouh\"/> On 28 September 2012, he joined Emirati club [[Al-Ittihad Kalba SC|Al-Ittihad Kalba]] on a year long loan deal.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ahmed Jahouh Pr\u00eat\u00e9 \u00c0 Ittihad Kalba Des Emirats [Ahmed Jahouh Loaned To Ittihad Kalba From The Emirates]|url=http://sport-maroc.com/09/ahmed-jahouh-prete-a-ittihad-kalba-des-emirats/|publisher=Maroc|accessdate=28 April 2018|language=French|date=28 September 2012}}</ref> In January 2013, he was released by Kalba.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Ahmed Rizvi|title=Junior Felicio Marques joins Kalba as Ahli and Achille Emana hit a snag|url=https://www.thenational.ae/sport/junior-felicio-marques-joins-kalba-as-ahli-and-achille-emana-hit-a-snag-1.260288|publisher=The National|accessdate=28 April 2018|date=23 January 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Mercato: Ahmed Jahouh quitte le MAT et rejoint officiellement le Raja\">{{cite web|author1=Younes Taleb|title=Mercato: Ahmed Jahouh quitte le MAT et rejoint officiellement le Raja [Mercato: Ahmed Jahouh leaves MAT and officially joins Raja]|url=http://www.menara.ma/fr/actualit%C3%A9s/sport/2015/09/08/1693253-mercato-ahmed-jahouh-quitte-le-mat-et-rejoint-officiellement-le-raja.html|publisher=Menara|accessdate=28 April 2018|language=French|date=9 September 2015}}</ref> On 8 September 2015, he signed with [[Raja Casablanca]] and penned a three-year contract.<ref name=\"Mercato: Ahmed Jahouh quitte le MAT et rejoint officiellement le Raja\"/> After being used sparingly by Casablanca, he joined [[Fath Union Sport|FUS Rabat]] on 25 July 2016 on a three-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|title=Transfert: Ahmed Jahouh, officiellement joueur du FUS [Transfer: Ahmed Jahouh, officially FUS player]|url=http://sport.le360.ma/botola-pro-1/transfert-ahmed-jahouh-officiellement-joueur-du-fus-13771|publisher=Sport 360|accessdate=28 April 2018|language=French|date=25 July 2016}}</ref> On 31 October, he scored his first goal for the club in a 2\u20132 draw against Casablanca.<ref>{{cite web|title=FUS Rabat et Raja Casablanca font match nul (2-2) [FUS Rabat and Raja Casablanca draw (2-2)]|url=http://www.maroc-hebdo.press.ma/fus-rabat-raja-casablanca-match-nul-2-2/|publisher=Maroc Hebdo|accessdate=28 April 2018|language=French|date=31 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 August 2017, Jahouh joined [[Indian Super League]] club [[FC Goa]] on a year long loan deal. He became the first Moroccan footballer to play in India.<ref name=\"ISL 2017: FC Goa sign Ahmed Jahouh to add steel to their midfield\">{{cite web|title=ISL 2017: FC Goa sign Ahmed Jahouh to add steel to their midfield|url=http://www.goal.com/en-in/news/isl-2017-fc-goa-sign-ahmed-jahouh-to-add-steel-to-their/oestcmupeleq10thvj3tdsdlt|publisher=Goal|accessdate=28 April 2018|date=2 August 2017}}</ref> During the season, he did not support the logo of a sponsor (an alcoholic brand) at the back of his shirt. Jahouh, a Muslim, cited religious reasons for not having that logo.<ref name=\"Ahmed Jahouh: Views against alcohol as clean as his tackles\">{{cite web|title=Ahmed Jahouh: Views against alcohol as clean as his tackles|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/goa/ahmed-jahouh-views-against-alcohol-as-clean-as-his-tackles/articleshow/63101762.cms|publisher=The Times of India|accessdate=28 April 2018|date=28 February 2018}}</ref> However, once the season ended, he was excluded from the [[Super Cup (India)|Super Cup]] squad.<ref>{{cite web|title=FC Goa announce Super Cup squad|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/football/top-stories/fc-goa-announce-super-cup-squad/articleshow/63399608.cms|publisher=The Times of India|accessdate=28 April 2018|date=21 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nJahouh has been capped at the international level, representing the team in [[2012 Arab Nations Cup]].<ref name=\"ISL 2017: FC Goa sign Ahmed Jahouh to add steel to their midfield\"/>\n\n==Statistics==\n{{updated|match played on 9 February 2020}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[Ittihad Khemisset]]\n|2006\u201307<ref name=\"MK\">{{cite web|title=Ahmed Jahouh|url=http://mountakhab.net/www/modules/fiches_joueurs/fiche.php?id=2830|publisher=Mountakhab|accessdate=28 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130515084512/http://mountakhab.net/www/modules/fiches_joueurs/fiche.php?id=2830|archive-date=15 May 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|[[Botola]]\n|||||||||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||||\n|-\n|2007\u201308<ref name=\"MK\"/>\n|Botola\n|||||||||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||||\n|-\n|2008\u201309<ref name=\"MK\"/>\n|Botola\n|||||||||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||||\n|-\n|2009\u201310<ref name=\"FDB\">{{cite web|title=Ahmed Jahouh|url=http://www.footballdatabase.eu/football.joueurs.ahmed.jahouh.118798.en.html|publisher=Football Database|accessdate=28 April 2018}}</ref>\n|Botola\n|14||1||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||14||1\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!14!!1!!!!!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!14!!1\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[Moghreb T\u00e9touan]]\n|2010\u201311<ref name=\"FDB\"/>\n|Botola\n|20||1||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||20||1\n|-\n|[[2011\u201312 Botola|2011\u201312]]<ref name=\"FDB\"/>\n|Botola\n|26||3||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||26||3\n|-\n|[[2013\u201314 Botola|2013\u201314]]<ref name=\"FDB\"/>\n|Botola\n|28||3||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||26||3\n|-\n|[[2014\u201315 Botola|2014\u201315]]<ref name=\"FDB\"/>\n|Botola\n|25||2||0||0||9{{efn|Appearances in [[CAF Champions League]] and [[FIFA Club World Cup]]|name=CFCW}}||2||34||4\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!99!!9!!0!!0!!9!!2!!108!!11\n|-\n|[[Al-Ittihad Kalba SC|Al-Ittihad Kalba]] (loan)\n|[[2012\u201313 UAE Pro-League|2012\u201313]]<ref name=\"SW\"/>\n|[[UAE Pro-League]]\n|9||1||2||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||11||1\n|-\n|[[Raja Casablanca]]\n|[[2015\u201316 Botola|2015\u201316]]<ref name=\"FDB\"/>\n|Botola\n|13||2||1||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||14||3\n|-\n|[[Fath Union Sport|FUS Rabat]]\n|[[2016\u201317 Botola|2016\u201317]]<ref name=\"FDB\"/>\n|Botola\n|19||1||2||0||5{{efn|Appearances in [[CAF Champions League]]|name=CAF}}||1|||26||2\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[FC Goa|Goa]]\n|[[2017\u201318 Indian Super League season|2017\u201318]]<ref name=\"SW\"/>\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Indian Super League]]\n|19||0||3||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||22||0\n|-\n|[[2018\u201319 Indian Super League season|2018\u201319]]<ref name=\"SW\"/>\n|20||0||4||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||24||0\n|-\n|[[2019\u201320 Indian Super League season|2019\u201320]]<ref name=\"SW\"/>\n|13||1||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||13||1\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!52!!1!!7!!0!!0!!0!!59!!1\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career total\n!206!!15!!12!!1!!14!!3!!230!!19\n|}\n{{notelist}}\n\n==Style of play==\nJahouh plays as a [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|defensive midfielder]].<ref name=\"ISL 2017: FC Goa sign Ahmed Jahouh to add steel to their midfield\"/> He is a [[Midfielder#Central midfielder|box to box]] midfielder as well as a deep lying playmaker. ''[[Hindustan Times]]'' wrote that Jahouh is a \"strong tackler\" and has a \"strong aerial presence\".<ref name=\"Indian Super League: FC Goa signs Moroccan International Ahmed Jahouh\">{{cite web|title=Indian Super League: FC Goa signs Moroccan International Ahmed Jahouh|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/football/indian-super-league-fc-goa-signs-moroccan-international-ahmed-jahouh/story-OCpqNAxmAuLtBB1qM9alqO.html|publisher=Hindustan Times|accessdate=28 April 2018|date=2 August 2017}}</ref> His manager at Goa and Moghreb, [[Sergio Lobera]] described Jahouh as a player who is \"capable of handling the game\".<ref name=\"Ahmed Jahouh: Views against alcohol as clean as his tackles\"/>\n== Honours ==\n=== Club ===\n;[[FC Goa]]\n*[[Indian Super Cup]](1):[[2019 Indian Super Cup|2019]]<ref>{{cite web |title=FC Goa\u2019s long wait for a trophy ends|url=https://www.thehindu.com/sport/football/fc-goas-long-wait-for-a-trophy-ends/article26832013.ece |publisher=thehindu.com |accessdate=14 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{FC Goa squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jahouh, Ahmed}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Moroccan footballers]]\n[[Category:Morocco international footballers]]\n[[Category:Moroccan expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Raja Casablanca players]]\n[[Category:FC Goa players]]\n[[Category:Moghreb T\u00e9touan players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in India]]\n[[Category:Moroccan expatriate sportspeople in India]]\n[[Category:Ittihad Khemisset players]]\n[[Category:Al-Ittihad Kalba SC players]]\n[[Category:Fath Union Sport players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Ahmed Jahouh\n| fullname = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1988|7|31}}<ref name=\"SW\">{{Soccerway|ahmed-jahouh/271173|accessdate=28 April 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Al Aaroui]], [[Morocco]]<ref name=\"MK\"/>\n| height = 1.87 m<ref name=\"SW\"/>\n| position = [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|Defensive midfielder]]\n| currentclub = [[FC Goa|Goa]]\n| clubnumber = 5\n| youthyears1= \n| youthclubs1= \n| years1 = 2006\u20132010 | years2 = 2010\u20132015 | years3 = 2012\u20132013 | years4 = 2015\u20132016 | years5 = 2016\u20132017 | years6 = 2017\u2013\n| clubs1 = [[Ittihad Khemisset]] | clubs2 = [[Moghreb T\u00e9touan]] | clubs3 = \u2192 [[Al-Ittihad Kalba SC|Al-Ittihad Kalba]] (loan) | clubs4 = [[Raja Casablanca]] | clubs5 = [[Fath Union Sport|FUS Rabat]] | clubs6 = [[FC Goa|Goa]]\n| caps1 = | goals1 =  | caps2 = 99 | goals2 = 9 | caps3 = 9 | goals3 = 1 | caps4 = 13 | goals4 = 2 | caps5 = 19| goals5 = 1 | caps6 = 53 | goals6 = 1\n| nationalyears1= 2012\u20132016\n| nationalteam1= [[Morocco national football team|Morocco]]\n| nationalcaps1= 8 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n| club-update = 9 February 2020\n| ntupdate = \n}}\n\n'''Ahmed Jahouh''' (born 31 July 1988) is a Moroccan professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays for Indian club [[FC Goa]], as a [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|defensive midfielder]].\n\nHe has been capped by [[Morocco national football team|Morocco]] at senior international level.\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[Al Aaroui]], Jahouh started his career with [[Ittihad Khemisset]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Mon absence du CHAN est une d\u00e9ception am\u00e8re [My absence from CHAN is a bitter disappointment]|url=https://lematin.ma/journal/2014/entretien-avec-ahmed-jahouh-joueur-du-moghreb-de-tetouan_-mon-absence-du-chan-est-une-deception-amere-/194888.html|publisher=Le Matin|accessdate=28 April 2018|language=French|date=13 January 2014}}</ref>  In 2010, he joined [[Moghreb T\u00e9touan]].<ref>{{cite web|author1=Mohammed Daroulche|title=Transferts: Ahmed Jahouh enfin au Raja [Transfers: Ahmed Jahouh finally at Raja]|url=http://fr.le360.ma/sports/transferts-ahmed-jahouh-enfin-au-raja-50489|publisher=Sport 360|accessdate=28 April 2018|language=French|date=9 September 2015}}</ref> Jahouh went on to win the [[2011\u201312 Botola]] and the [[2013\u201314 Botola]] with Moghreb.<ref name=\"Indian Super League: FC Goa signs Moroccan International Ahmed Jahouh\"/> On 28 September 2012, he joined Emirati club [[Al-Ittihad Kalba SC|Al-Ittihad Kalba]] on a year long loan deal.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ahmed Jahouh Pr\u00eat\u00e9 \u00c0 Ittihad Kalba Des Emirats [Ahmed Jahouh Loaned To Ittihad Kalba From The Emirates]|url=http://sport-maroc.com/09/ahmed-jahouh-prete-a-ittihad-kalba-des-emirats/|publisher=Maroc|accessdate=28 April 2018|language=French|date=28 September 2012}}</ref> In January 2013, he was released by Kalba.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Ahmed Rizvi|title=Junior Felicio Marques joins Kalba as Ahli and Achille Emana hit a snag|url=https://www.thenational.ae/sport/junior-felicio-marques-joins-kalba-as-ahli-and-achille-emana-hit-a-snag-1.260288|publisher=The National|accessdate=28 April 2018|date=23 January 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Mercato: Ahmed Jahouh quitte le MAT et rejoint officiellement le Raja\">{{cite web|author1=Younes Taleb|title=Mercato: Ahmed Jahouh quitte le MAT et rejoint officiellement le Raja [Mercato: Ahmed Jahouh leaves MAT and officially joins Raja]|url=http://www.menara.ma/fr/actualit%C3%A9s/sport/2015/09/08/1693253-mercato-ahmed-jahouh-quitte-le-mat-et-rejoint-officiellement-le-raja.html|publisher=Menara|accessdate=28 April 2018|language=French|date=9 September 2015}}</ref> On 8 September 2015, he signed with [[Raja Casablanca]] and penned a three-year contract.<ref name=\"Mercato: Ahmed Jahouh quitte le MAT et rejoint officiellement le Raja\"/> After being used sparingly by Casablanca, he joined [[Fath Union Sport|FUS Rabat]] on 25 July 2016 on a three-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|title=Transfert: Ahmed Jahouh, officiellement joueur du FUS [Transfer: Ahmed Jahouh, officially FUS player]|url=http://sport.le360.ma/botola-pro-1/transfert-ahmed-jahouh-officiellement-joueur-du-fus-13771|publisher=Sport 360|accessdate=28 April 2018|language=French|date=25 July 2016}}</ref> On 31 October, he scored his first goal for the club in a 2\u20132 draw against Casablanca.<ref>{{cite web|title=FUS Rabat et Raja Casablanca font match nul (2-2) [FUS Rabat and Raja Casablanca draw (2-2)]|url=http://www.maroc-hebdo.press.ma/fus-rabat-raja-casablanca-match-nul-2-2/|publisher=Maroc Hebdo|accessdate=28 April 2018|language=French|date=31 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 August 2017, Jahouh joined [[Indian Super League]] club [[FC Goa]] on a year long loan deal. He became the first Moroccan footballer to play in India.<ref name=\"ISL 2017: FC Goa sign Ahmed Jahouh to add steel to their midfield\">{{cite web|title=ISL 2017: FC Goa sign Ahmed Jahouh to add steel to their midfield|url=http://www.goal.com/en-in/news/isl-2017-fc-goa-sign-ahmed-jahouh-to-add-steel-to-their/oestcmupeleq10thvj3tdsdlt|publisher=Goal|accessdate=28 April 2018|date=2 August 2017}}</ref> During the season, he did not support the logo of a sponsor (an alcoholic brand) at the back of his shirt. Jahouh, a Muslim, cited religious reasons for not having that logo.<ref name=\"Ahmed Jahouh: Views against alcohol as clean as his tackles\">{{cite web|title=Ahmed Jahouh: Views against alcohol as clean as his tackles|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/goa/ahmed-jahouh-views-against-alcohol-as-clean-as-his-tackles/articleshow/63101762.cms|publisher=The Times of India|accessdate=28 April 2018|date=28 February 2018}}</ref> However, once the season ended, he was excluded from the [[Super Cup (India)|Super Cup]] squad.<ref>{{cite web|title=FC Goa announce Super Cup squad|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/football/top-stories/fc-goa-announce-super-cup-squad/articleshow/63399608.cms|publisher=The Times of India|accessdate=28 April 2018|date=21 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nJahouh has been capped at the international level, representing the team in [[2012 Arab Nations Cup]].<ref name=\"ISL 2017: FC Goa sign Ahmed Jahouh to add steel to their midfield\"/>\n\n==Statistics==\n{{updated|match played on 9 February 2020}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[Ittihad Khemisset]]\n|2006\u201307<ref name=\"MK\">{{cite web|title=Ahmed Jahouh|url=http://mountakhab.net/www/modules/fiches_joueurs/fiche.php?id=2830|publisher=Mountakhab|accessdate=28 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130515084512/http://mountakhab.net/www/modules/fiches_joueurs/fiche.php?id=2830|archive-date=15 May 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|[[Botola]]\n|||||||||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||||\n|-\n|2007\u201308<ref name=\"MK\"/>\n|Botola\n|||||||||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||||\n|-\n|2008\u201309<ref name=\"MK\"/>\n|Botola\n|||||||||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||||\n|-\n|2009\u201310<ref name=\"FDB\">{{cite web|title=Ahmed Jahouh|url=http://www.footballdatabase.eu/football.joueurs.ahmed.jahouh.118798.en.html|publisher=Football Database|accessdate=28 April 2018}}</ref>\n|Botola\n|14||1||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||14||1\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!14!!1!!!!!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!14!!1\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[Moghreb T\u00e9touan]]\n|2010\u201311<ref name=\"FDB\"/>\n|Botola\n|20||1||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||20||1\n|-\n|[[2011\u201312 Botola|2011\u201312]]<ref name=\"FDB\"/>\n|Botola\n|26||3||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||26||3\n|-\n|[[2013\u201314 Botola|2013\u201314]]<ref name=\"FDB\"/>\n|Botola\n|28||3||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||26||3\n|-\n|[[2014\u201315 Botola|2014\u201315]]<ref name=\"FDB\"/>\n|Botola\n|25||2||0||0||9{{efn|Appearances in [[CAF Champions League]] and [[FIFA Club World Cup]]|name=CFCW}}||2||34||4\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!99!!9!!0!!0!!9!!2!!108!!11\n|-\n|[[Al-Ittihad Kalba SC|Al-Ittihad Kalba]] (loan)\n|[[2012\u201313 UAE Pro-League|2012\u201313]]<ref name=\"SW\"/>\n|[[UAE Pro-League]]\n|9||1||2||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||11||1\n|-\n|[[Raja Casablanca]]\n|[[2015\u201316 Botola|2015\u201316]]<ref name=\"FDB\"/>\n|Botola\n|13||2||1||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||14||3\n|-\n|[[Fath Union Sport|FUS Rabat]]\n|[[2016\u201317 Botola|2016\u201317]]<ref name=\"FDB\"/>\n|Botola\n|19||1||2||0||5{{efn|Appearances in [[CAF Champions League]]|name=CAF}}||1|||26||2\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[FC Goa|Goa]]\n|[[2017\u201318 Indian Super League season|2017\u201318]]<ref name=\"SW\"/>\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Indian Super League]]\n|19||0||3||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||22||0\n|-\n|[[2018\u201319 Indian Super League season|2018\u201319]]<ref name=\"SW\"/>\n|20||0||4||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||24||0\n|-\n|[[2019\u201320 Indian Super League season|2019\u201320]]<ref name=\"SW\"/>\n|13||1||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||13||1\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!52!!1!!7!!0!!0!!0!!59!!1\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career total\n!206!!15!!12!!1!!14!!3!!230!!19\n|}\n{{notelist}}\n\n==Style of play==\nJahouh plays as a [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|defensive midfielder]].<ref name=\"ISL 2017: FC Goa sign Ahmed Jahouh to add steel to their midfield\"/> He is a [[Midfielder#Central midfielder|box to box]] midfielder as well as a deep lying playmaker. ''[[Hindustan Times]]'' wrote that Jahouh is a \"strong tackler\" and has a \"strong aerial presence\".<ref name=\"Indian Super League: FC Goa signs Moroccan International Ahmed Jahouh\">{{cite web|title=Indian Super League: FC Goa signs Moroccan International Ahmed Jahouh|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/football/indian-super-league-fc-goa-signs-moroccan-international-ahmed-jahouh/story-OCpqNAxmAuLtBB1qM9alqO.html|publisher=Hindustan Times|accessdate=28 April 2018|date=2 August 2017}}</ref> His manager at Goa and Moghreb, [[Sergio Lobera]] described Jahouh as a player who is \"capable of handling the game\".<ref name=\"Ahmed Jahouh: Views against alcohol as clean as his tackles\"/>\n== Honours ==\n=== Club ===\n;[[FC Goa]]\n*[[Indian Super Cup]](1):[[2019 Indian Super Cup|2019]]<ref>{{cite web |title=FC Goa\u2019s long wait for a trophy ends|url=https://www.thehindu.com/sport/football/fc-goas-long-wait-for-a-trophy-ends/article26832013.ece |publisher=thehindu.com |accessdate=14 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Referenc