lbum)|Madame X]]'' (Boy Toy/Live Nation)\n* [[Nightly (band)|Nightly]] - ''Talk You Down''\n* [[X Ambassadors]] - ''[[Orion (X Ambassadors album)|ORION]]'' (KIDinaKORNER)\n* [[K Camp]] - ''Wayy 2 Kritical'' (RARE Sound/EMPIRE)\n* [[Pi'erre Bourne]] - ''The Life Of Pi'erre 4'' (SosssHouse)\n* [[Mustard (record producer)|Mustard]] - ''[[Perfect Ten (album)|Perfect Ten]]'' (10 Summers)\n* Nechie - ''SSN: Southside Nechi The Introduction\n* [[Dreamville Records|Dreamville]] & [[J. Cole]] - [[Revenge of the Dreamers III]] (Dreamville)\n* [[Machine Gun Kelly (musician)|Machine Gun Kelly]] - ''[[Hotel Diablo]]'' (EST 19XX/Bad Boy)\n* Ann Marie - ''Pretty Psycho'' (Zulu)\n* Blacc Zacc - ''Trappin Like Zacc'' (SCMG)\n* [[Cuco (musician)|Cuco]] - ''[[Para Mi (Cuco album)|Para Mi]]\n* [[Lil Durk]] - ''Love Songs 4 The Streets 2'' (OTF/Alamo)\n* Lou The Human - ''Painkiller Paradise''\n* Various Artists - ''13 Reasons Why: Season 3 (Soundtrack)''\n* [[Lana Del Rey]] - ''[[Norman Fucking Rockwell]]''\n* DaBaby - ''[[Kirk (album)|KIRK]]'' (SCMG)\n* Summer Walker - ''[[Over It (album)|Over It]]'' (LVRN)\n* Melii - ''MOTIONS'' (Rule #1)\n* Justin Rarri - ''4EVARARRi''\n* Jayla Darden - ''Onto Something'' (a sick project)\n* ROLE MODEL - ''oh, how perfect''\n* Only1Skoota - ''No Love Back''\n* [[QUIN (singer)|QUIN]] - ''LUCID'' (Fantasy Soul)\n* [[Tory Lanez]] - ''[[Chixtape 5]]'' (Mad Love)\n* BB Nobre - ''Por Fin''\n* Griselda - ''WWCD'' (Griselda/Shady)\n* Yoshi Flower - ''I Will Not Let My Love Go To Waste'' (Rock Mafia/GRDN)\n* Only The Family & Lil Durk - ''Family Over Everything'' (OTF/Alamo)\n* Arin Ray - ''Phases II''\n* Lil Poppa - ''Almost Normal'' (Rule #1)\n* [[Smino]] - ''High 4 Da Highladays'' (Zero Fatigue/Downtown)\n\n== 2020s==\n\n=== 2020 ===\n* [[Moneybagg Yo]] - ''Time Served'' (N-Less)\n* [[Selena Gomez]] - ''[[Rare (Selena Gomez album)|Rare]]''\n* [[Dreamville Records|Dreamville]] & [[J. Cole]] - [[Revenge of the Dreamers III|Revenge of the Dreamers III: Director's Cut]] (Dreamville)\n* [[Eminem]] - ''[[Music to Be Murdered By]]'' (Shady/Aftermath)\n* [[Stunna 4 Vegas]] - ''RICH YOUNGIN'' (Billion Dollar Baby)\n\n\n[[Category:Record label discographies]]\n", "name_user": "Hybrid27", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e2020", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interscope_Records_discography"}
{"title_page": "Ron Bailey (politician)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable]]\n|name        =   Ron Bailey\n|honorific-suffix = {{post-nominals|country=NZL|QSO|size=100%}}\n|image       =   Ron Bailey.jpg\n|caption     = \n|order       =   21st [[Minister of Railways (New Zealand)|Minister of Railways]]\n|term_start  =   10 September 1974\n|term_end    =   12 December 1975\n|predecessor =   [[Tom McGuigan]]\n|successor   =   [[Colin McLachlan]]\n|primeminister = [[Bill Rowling]]\n|order2      =   [[New Zealand House of Representatives|Member of the House of Representatives]] <br> for [[Heretaunga (New Zealand electorate)|Heretaunga]]\n|term_start2 =   12 December 1960\n|term_end2   =   28 November 1981\n|predecessor2=   [[Phil Holloway]]\n|successor2  =   [[Bill Jeffries]]\n|birth_date  =   15 December 1926\n|birth_place =   [[Napier, New Zealand|Napier]], New Zealand\n|death_date  =   {{death date and age|2015|04|16|1926|12|15|df=y}}\n|death_place =   [[Auckland]], New Zealand\n|restingplace= \n|restingplacecoordinates = \n|party       =   [[New Zealand Labour Party|Labour]]\n|otherparty  =   <!--For additional political affiliations-->\n|spouse      =   {{marriage|Shirley O'Neill|1948|1977|end=d.}}<br>{{marriage|Barbara McDonald|1979|2015}}\n|relations   =   \n|children    =   2\n|occupation  =   \n|profession  =   \n|religion    =   \n|signature   =   \n}}\n\n'''Ronald Leslie Bailey''' {{post-nominals|country=NZL|QSO|size=85%}} (15 December 1926 \u2013 16 April 2015) was a New Zealand politician of the [[New Zealand Labour Party|Labour Party]].\n\n==Early life==\nBailey was born in [[Napier, New Zealand|Napier]] in 1926. He grew up in various [[public works]] camps during the [[Great Depression]] and attended four different primary schools in the central North Island. After attending four different primary schools, he received his secondary education at Wairoa District High School (now [[Wairoa College]]) and [[Gisborne Boys' High School|Gisborne High School]]. His first jobs were as a clerk and a carpenter. He became a union organiser in 1956 where he inspected living conditions in the agricultural sector.<ref name=\"Dom Post obit\">{{cite news |last1=Fitzsimons |first1=Tom |title=Veteran Labour MP Ron Bailey became vocal Rogernomics supporter |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/wellington/68369079/veteran-labour-mp-ron-bailey-became-vocal-rogernomics-supporter |accessdate=17 June 2015 |work=[[The Dominion Post (Wellington)|The Dominion Post]] |date=9 June 2015 }}</ref> He and his union were staunch [[Anti-communism|Anti-communist]] and allegedly he was a member of the far-right [[World Anti-Communist League]]'s New Zealand chapter.<ref name=\"Broad\">{{cite news |author=[[Chris Trotter|Trotter, Chris]] |title=Labour's broad church still got strong support |work=[[The Timaru Herald]] |date=10 February 2017 |page=6 }}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n{{NZ parlbox header|nolist=true|align=left}}\n{{NZ parlbox\n |start      = {{NZ election link year|1960}}\n |end        = 1963\n |term       = 33rd\n |electorate = {{NZ electorate link|Heretaunga}}\n |party      = New Zealand Labour Party\n}}\n{{NZ parlbox\n |start      = {{NZ election link year|1963}}\n |end        = 1966\n |term       = 34th\n |electorate = Heretaunga\n |party      = New Zealand Labour Party\n}}\n{{NZ parlbox\n |start      = {{NZ election link year|1966}}\n |end        = 1969\n |term       = 35th\n |electorate = Heretaunga\n |party      = New Zealand Labour Party\n}}\n{{NZ parlbox\n |start      = {{NZ election link year|1969}}\n |end        = 1972\n |term       = 36th\n |electorate = Heretaunga\n |party      = New Zealand Labour Party\n}}\n{{NZ parlbox\n |start      = {{NZ election link year|1972}}\n |end        = 1975\n |term       = 37th\n |electorate = Heretaunga\n |party      = New Zealand Labour Party\n}}\n{{NZ parlbox\n |start      = {{NZ election link year|1975}}\n |end        = 1978\n |term       = 38th\n |electorate = Heretaunga\n |party      = New Zealand Labour Party\n}}\n{{NZ parlbox\n |start      = {{NZ election link year|1978}}\n |end        = 1981\n |term       = 39th\n |electorate = Heretaunga\n |party      = New Zealand Labour Party\n}}\n{{NZ parlbox footer}}\n[[File:1975 opening plaque Hamilton Railway Station, Waikato.JPG|thumb|Plaque from his period as Minister of Railways at [[Hamilton Railway Station, Waikato]] ]]\nWhen [[Phil Holloway]] unexpectedly retired from the {{NZ electorate link|Heretaunga}} electorate,<ref name=\"Dom Post obit\" /> Bailey won the Labour Party nomination and the subsequent election.{{sfn|Wilson|1985|p=181}} He served seven terms and retired in 1981, when he was succeeded by [[Bill Jeffries]].{{sfn|Wilson|1985|pp=181, 208}} Labour spent all but one of those terms in opposition, a situation he described in his valedictory speech as a \"brick wall of frustration\".<ref name=\"Dom Post obit\" />\n\nDuring his time in Parliament Bailey was noted for lobbying for a new wing for Wellington Hospital, opposing increases in railway fares in the Hutt Valley and advocating for an increase in state house building.<ref name=\"Dom Post obit\" /> Bailey was Labour's junior whip from 1966 to 1972.{{sfn|Wilson|1985|p=281}} Bailey narrowly missed out on election to cabinet following the formation of the [[Third Labour Government of New Zealand|Third Labour Government]] and was thusly given the consolation job of [[Chairman of Committees (New Zealand House of Representatives)|Chairman of Committees]] from 16 February 1973 until 10 September 1974.{{sfn|Wilson|1985|p=252}} As Chairman of Committees he deputized for the Speaker and notably chaired the session that saw the passing of Labour's short-lived [[Welfare in New Zealand#Superannuation|compulsory superannuation]] scheme. He is also reputed to have been the only Speaker to eject National leader [[Robert Muldoon]] from the House.<ref name=\"Dom Post obit\" />\n\nWhen [[Bill Rowling]] was elected Prime Minister, after [[Norman Kirk]] died suddenly, Bailey was elected to fill the vacant seat in cabinet.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cabinet Rank Fulfills Hope |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |date=7 September 1974 |page=3 }}</ref> He was appointed as both [[Minister of Railways (New Zealand)|Minister of Railways]]{{sfn|Leitch & Stott|1988|p=Appendix two \u2013 Ministers of Railways 1895\u20131988}} and [[Minister of Energy and Resources (New Zealand)|Minister of Electricity]] by Rowling from 10 September 1974 to 12 December 1975, when [[Third National Government of New Zealand|National]] came to power.{{sfn|Wilson|1985|pp=93\u201394}} He remembered his time as a minister as his best in politics.<ref name=\"Dom Post obit\" />\n\nIn 1977, Bailey was awarded the [[Queen Elizabeth II Silver Jubilee Medal]].<ref name=\"HBTQ\">{{cite book |last1=Taylor |first1=Alister |last2=Coddington |first2=Deborah |authorlink1=Alister Taylor |authorlink2=Deborah Coddington |title=Honoured by the Queen \u2013 New Zealand |year=1994 |publisher=New Zealand Who's Who Aotearoa |location=Auckland |isbn=0-908578-34-2 |page=53}}</ref>\n\n==After politics==\nBailey struggled to find permanent work when he left parliament. He worked as a real estate agent for a while but found it hard to persuade people to take on high debt. For a while, he and his wife manufactured artisan chocolate at their home. He then became a review officer for the [[Accident Compensation Corporation]] (ACC) and went to retirement when he was 66.<ref name=\"Dom Post obit\" />\n\nBailey remained politically active after exiting parliament and during the [[Fourth Labour Government of New Zealand|Fourth Labour Government]] he was the Auckland convenor of the ''Backbone Club'', a party ginger group, formed to support [[Roger Douglas]] against [[Jim Anderton]].<ref>{{cite book |last= [[Michael Bassett|Bassett]] |first= Michael |title= Working with David: Inside the Lange Cabinet |accessdate= |edition=  |origyear=  |year= 2008 |publisher= Hodder Moa  |location= Auckland |isbn= 978-1-86971-094-1 |oclc= |page= 586 (Note 2)|pages= }}</ref> He remained a friend of Douglas but never went as far as to join [[ACT New Zealand|ACT]].\n\nIn the [[1987 Birthday Honours|1987 Queen's Birthday Honours]], Bailey appointed a [[Queen's Service Order|Companion of the Queen's Service Order]] for public services,<ref>{{London Gazette |date=13 June 1987 |supp=y |issue=50950 |page=33}}</ref> and in 1990 he was awarded the [[New Zealand 1990 Commemoration Medal]].<ref name=\"HBTQ\"/>\n\n==Private life==\nBailey was married to Shirley for 29 years, when she died. They had one daughter and one son. When first elected his MP salary was so low they could not afford either a car or house. He used to travel by bicycle and the pair lived in workers' sheds alongside the [[Hutt River (New Zealand)|Hutt River]]. They were only able to purchase their own home after winning a bet on horse racing.<ref name=\"Dom Post obit\" />\n\nHis second wife was Barbara; she was the electorate secretary for [[Roger Douglas]]. They first met during the election campaign for the [[1977 Mangere by-election|Mangere by-election in 1977]]. In 1979 they married, fellow Labour MP [[Russell Marshall]] (a Methodist minister) conducted the ceremony.<ref name=\"Dom Post obit\" /> They later moved to Auckland and he died there on 16 April 2015, survived by his second wife.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://notices.nzherald.co.nz/obituaries/nzherald-nz/obituary.aspx?n=ronald-leslie-bailey&pid=174671027&fhid=12556 | title=Ronald Bailey obituary | date=20 April 2015| work=New Zealand Herald | accessdate=20 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Notes and references ==\n=== Notes ===\n{{commons category|Ron Bailey}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== References ===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Stott |first1=Bob |last2=Leitch |first2=David |year=1988|location=Auckland |title=New Zealand Railways: The First 125 Years |publisher=Heinemann Reed|isbn=0-7900-0000-8 |ref={{sfnref|Leitch & Stott|1988}}}}\n*{{Cite book |ref=harv |last= Wilson |first= James Oakley |title= New Zealand Parliamentary Record, 1840\u20131984 |edition= 4th |origyear= First ed. published 1913 |year= 1985 |publisher= V.R. Ward, Govt. Printer |location= Wellington |oclc=154283103}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{S-off}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Richard Harrison (New Zealand politician)|Richard Harrison]]}}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = [[Chairman of Committees (New Zealand House of Representatives)|Chairman of Committees of the House of Representatives]]\n | years = 1973\u20131974\n}}\n{{s-aft | after  = [[Jonathan Hunt (New Zealand politician)|Jonathan Hunt]] }}\n|-\n{{s-bef | rows=2| before = [[Tom McGuigan]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title  = [[Minister of Railways (New Zealand)|Minister of Railways]]|years=1974\u20131975}}\n{{s-aft | after  = [[Colin McLachlan]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl | title  = [[Minister of Energy and Resources (New Zealand)|Minister of Electricity]]|years=1974\u20131975}}\n{{s-aft | after  = [[Eric Holland]]}}\n|-\n{{s-par | nz}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Phil Holloway]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title  = [[Heretaunga (New Zealand electorate)|Member of Parliament for Heretaunga]]| years=1960\u20131981}}\n{{s-aft | after  = [[Bill Jeffries]]}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bailey, Ron}}\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:New Zealand Labour Party MPs]]\n[[Category:Members of the Cabinet of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:People from Napier, New Zealand]]\n[[Category:People from Upper Hutt]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Queen's Service Order]]\n[[Category:New Zealand MPs for Hutt Valley electorates]]\n[[Category:Members of the New Zealand House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:People educated at Gisborne Boys' High School]]\n[[Category:New Zealand real estate agents]]\n[[Category:People educated at Wairoa College]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable]]\n|name        =   Ron Bailey\n|honorific-suffix = {{post-nominals|country=NZL|QSO|size=100%}}\n|image       =   Ron Bailey.jpg\n|caption     = \n|order       =   21st [[Minister of Railways (New Zealand)|Minister of Railways]]\n|term_start  =   10 September 1974\n|term_end    =   12 December 1975\n|predecessor =   [[Tom McGuigan]]\n|successor   =   [[Colin McLachlan]]\n|primeminister = [[Bill Rowling]]\n|order2      =   [[New Zealand House of Representatives|Member of the House of Representatives]] <br> for [[Heretaunga (New Zealand electorate)|Heretaunga]]\n|term_start2 =   12 December 1960\n|term_end2   =   28 November 1981\n|predecessor2=   [[Phil Holloway]]\n|successor2  =   [[Bill Jeffries]]\n|birth_date  =   15 December 1926\n|birth_place =   [[Napier, New Zealand|Napier]], New Zealand\n|death_date  =   {{death date and age|2015|04|16|1926|12|15|df=y}}\n|death_place =   [[Auckland]], New Zealand\n|restingplace= \n|restingplacecoordinates = \n|party       =   [[New Zealand Labour Party|Labour]]\n|otherparty  =   <!--For additional political affiliations-->\n|spouse      =   {{marriage|Shirley O'Neill|1948|1977|end=d.}}<br>{{marriage|Barbara McDonald|1979|2015}}\n|relations   =   \n|children    =   2\n|occupation  =   \n|profession  =   \n|religion    =   \n|signature   =   \n}}\n\n'''Ronald Leslie Bailey''' {{post-nominals|country=NZL|QSO|size=85%}} (15 December 1926 \u2013 16 April 2015) was a New Zealand politician of the [[New Zealand Labour Party|Labour Party]].\n\n==Early life==\nBailey was born in [[Napier, New Zealand|Napier]] in 1926. He grew up in various [[public works]] camps during the [[Great Depression]] and attended four different primary schools in the central North Island. After attending four different primary schools, he received his secondary education at Wairoa District High School (now [[Wairoa College]]) and [[Gisborne Boys' High School|Gisborne High School]]. His first jobs were as a clerk and a carpenter. He became a union organiser in 1956 where he inspected living conditions in the agricultural sector.<ref name=\"Dom Post obit\">{{cite news |last1=Fitzsimons |first1=Tom |title=Veteran Labour MP Ron Bailey became vocal Rogernomics supporter |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/wellington/68369079/veteran-labour-mp-ron-bailey-became-vocal-rogernomics-supporter |accessdate=17 June 2015 |work=[[The Dominion Post (Wellington)|The Dominion Post]] |date=9 June 2015 }}</ref> He and his union were staunch [[Anti-communism|Anti-communist]] and allegedly he was a member of the far-right [[World Anti-Communist League]]'s New Zealand chapter.<ref name=\"Broad\">{{cite news |author=[[Chris Trotter|Trotter, Chris]] |title=Labour's broad church still got strong support |work=[[The Timaru Herald]] |date=10 February 2017 |page=6 }}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n{{NZ parlbox header|nolist=true|align=left}}\n{{NZ parlbox\n |start      = {{NZ election link year|1960}}\n |end        = 1963\n |term       = 33rd\n |electorate = {{NZ electorate link|Heretaunga}}\n |party      = New Zealand Labour Party\n}}\n{{NZ parlbox\n |start      = {{NZ election link year|1963}}\n |end        = 1966\n |term       = 34th\n |electorate = Heretaunga\n |party      = New Zealand Labour Party\n}}\n{{NZ parlbox\n |start      = {{NZ election link year|1966}}\n |end        = 1969\n |term       = 35th\n |electorate = Heretaunga\n |party      = New Zealand Labour Party\n}}\n{{NZ parlbox\n |start      = {{NZ election link year|1969}}\n |end        = 1972\n |term       = 36th\n |electorate = Heretaunga\n |party      = New Zealand Labour Party\n}}\n{{NZ parlbox\n |start      = {{NZ election link year|1972}}\n |end        = 1975\n |term       = 37th\n |electorate = Heretaunga\n |party      = New Zealand Labour Party\n}}\n{{NZ parlbox\n |start      = {{NZ election link year|1975}}\n |end        = 1978\n |term       = 38th\n |electorate = Heretaunga\n |party      = New Zealand Labour Party\n}}\n{{NZ parlbox\n |start      = {{NZ election link year|1978}}\n |end        = 1981\n |term       = 39th\n |electorate = Heretaunga\n |party      = New Zealand Labour Party\n}}\n{{NZ parlbox footer}}\n[[File:1975 opening plaque Hamilton Railway Station, Waikato.JPG|thumb|Plaque from his period as Minister of Railways at [[Hamilton Railway Station, Waikato]] ]]\nWhen [[Phil Holloway]] unexpectedly retired from the {{NZ electorate link|Heretaunga}} electorate,<ref name=\"Dom Post obit\" /> Bailey won the Labour Party nomination and the subsequent election.{{sfn|Wilson|1985|p=181}} He served seven terms and retired in 1981, when he was succeeded by [[Bill Jeffries]].{{sfn|Wilson|1985|pp=181, 208}} Labour spent all but one of those terms in opposition, a situation he described in his valedictory speech as a \"brick wall of frustration\".<ref name=\"Dom Post obit\" /> \n\nDuring his time in Parliament Bailey was noted for lobbying for a new wing for Wellington Hospital, opposing increases in railway fares in the Hutt Valley and advocating for an increase in state house building.<ref name=\"Dom Post obit\" /> Bailey was Labour's junior whip from 1966 to 1972.{{sfn|Wilson|1985|p=281}} Bailey narrowly missed out on election to cabinet following the formation of the [[Third Labour Government of New Zealand|Third Labour Government]] and was thusly given the consolation job of [[Chairman of Committees (New Zealand House of Representatives)|Chairman of Committees]] from 16 February 1973 until 10 September 1974.{{sfn|Wilson|1985|p=252}} As Chairman of Committees he deputized for the Speaker and notably chaired the session that saw the passing of Labour's shortlived [[Welfare in New Zealand#Superannuation|compulsory superannuation]] scheme. He is also reputed to have been the only Speaker to eject National leader [[Robert Muldoon]] from the House.<ref name=\"Dom Post obit\" />\n\nWhen [[Bill Rowling]] was elected Prime Minister, after [[Norman Kirk]] died suddenly, Bailey was elected to fill the vacant seat in cabinet.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cabinet Rank Fulfills Hope |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |date=7 September 1974 |page=3 }}</ref> He was appointed as both [[Minister of Railways (New Zealand)|Minister of Railways]]{{sfn|Leitch & Stott|1988|p=Appendix two \u2013 Ministers of Railways 1895\u20131988}} and [[Minister of Energy and Resources (New Zealand)|Minister of Electricity]] by Rowling from 10 September 1974 to 12 December 1975, when [[Third National Government of New Zealand|National]] came to power.{{sfn|Wilson|1985|pp=93\u201394}} He remembered his time as a minister as his best in politics.<ref name=\"Dom Post obit\" /> \n\nIn 1977, Bailey was awarded the [[Queen Elizabeth II Silver Jubilee Medal]].<ref name=\"HBTQ\">{{cite book |last1=Taylor |first1=Alister |last2=Coddington |first2=Deborah |authorlink1=Alister Taylor |authorlink2=Deborah Coddington |title=Honoured by the Queen \u2013 New Zealand |year=1994 |publisher=New Zealand Who's Who Aotearoa |location=Auckland |isbn=0-908578-34-2 |page=53}}</ref>\n\n==After politics==\nBailey struggled to find permanent work when he left parliament. He worked as a real estate agent for a while but found it hard to persuade people to take on high debt. For a while, he and his wife manufactured artisan chocolate at their home. He then became a review officer for the [[Accident Compensation Corporation]] (ACC) and went to retirement when he was 66.<ref name=\"Dom Post obit\" /> \n\nBailey remained politically active after exiting parliament and during the [[Fourth Labour Government of New Zealand|Fourth Labour Government]] he was the Auckland convenor of the ''Backbone Club'', a party ginger group, formed to support [[Roger Douglas]] against [[Jim Anderton]].<ref>{{cite book |last= [[Michael Bassett|Bassett]] |first= Michael |title= Working with David: Inside the Lange Cabinet |accessdate= |edition=  |origyear=  |year= 2008 |publisher= Hodder Moa  |location= Auckland |isbn= 978-1-86971-094-1 |oclc= |page= 586 (Note 2)|pages= }}</ref> He remained a friend of Douglas but never went as far as to join [[ACT New Zealand|ACT]].\n\nIn the [[1987 Birthday Honours|1987 Queen's Birthday Honours]], Bailey appointed a [[Queen's Service Order|Companion of the Queen's Service Order]] for public services,<ref>{{London Gazette |date=13 June 1987 |supp=y |issue=50950 |page=33}}</ref> and in 1990 he was awarded the [[New Zealand 1990 Commemoration Medal]].<ref name=\"HBTQ\"/>\n\n==Private life==\nBailey was married to Shirley for 29 years, when she died. They had one daughter and one son. When first elected his MP salary was so low they could not afford either a car or house. He used to travel by bicycle and the pair lived in workers' sheds alongside the [[Hutt River (New Zealand)|Hutt River]]. They were only able to purchase their own home after winning a bet on horse racing.<ref name=\"Dom Post obit\" /> \n\nHis second wife was Barbara; she was the electorate secretary for [[Roger Douglas]]. They first met during the election campaign for the [[1977 Mangere by-election|Mangere by-election in 1977]]. In 1979 they married, fellow Labour MP [[Russell Marshall]] (a Methodist minister) conducted the ceremony.<ref name=\"Dom Post obit\" /> They later moved to Auckland and he died there on 16 April 2015, survived by his second wife.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://notices.nzherald.co.nz/obituaries/nzherald-nz/obituary.aspx?n=ronald-leslie-bailey&pid=174671027&fhid=12556 | title=Ronald Bailey obituary | date=20 April 2015| work=New Zealand Herald | accessdate=20 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Notes and references ==\n=== Notes ===\n{{commons category|Ron Bailey}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== References ===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Stott |first1=Bob |last2=Leitch |first2=David |year=1988|location=Auckland |title=New Zealand Railways: The First 125 Years |publisher=Heinemann Reed|isbn=0-7900-0000-8 |ref={{sfnref|Leitch & Stott|1988}}}}\n*{{Cite book |ref=harv |last= Wilson |first= James Oakley |title= New Zealand Parliamentary Record, 1840\u20131984 |edition= 4th |origyear= First ed. published 1913 |year= 1985 |publisher= V.R. Ward, Govt. Printer |location= Wellington |oclc=154283103}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{S-off}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Richard Harrison (New Zealand politician)|Richard Harrison]]}}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = [[Chairman of Committees (New Zealand House of Representatives)|Chairman of Committees of the House of Representatives]]\n | years = 1973\u20131974\n}}\n{{s-aft | after  = [[Jonathan Hunt (New Zealand politician)|Jonathan Hunt]] }}\n|-\n{{s-bef | rows=2| before = [[Tom McGuigan]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title  = [[Minister of Railways (New Zealand)|Minister of Railways]]|years=1974\u20131975}}\n{{s-aft | after  = [[Colin McLachlan]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl | title  = [[Minister of Energy and Resources (New Zealand)|Minister of Electricity]]|years=1974\u20131975}}\n{{s-aft | after  = [[Eric Holland]]}}\n|-\n{{s-par | nz}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Phil Holloway]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title  = [[Heretaunga (New Zealand electorate)|Member of Parliament for Heretaunga]]| years=1960\u20131981}}\n{{s-aft | after  = [[Bill Jeffries]]}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bailey, Ron}}\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:New Zealand Labour Party MPs]]\n[[Category:Members of the Cabinet of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:People from Napier, New Zealand]]\n[[Category:People from Upper Hutt]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Queen's Service Order]]\n[[Category:New Zealand MPs for Hutt Valley electorates]]\n[[Category:Members of the New Zealand House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:People educated at Gisborne Boys' High School]]\n[[Category:New Zealand real estate agents]]\n[[Category:People educated at Wairoa College]]\n", "name_user": "J947", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: shortlived \u2192 short-lived", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ron_Bailey_(politician)"}
{"title_page": "IDonate", "text_new": "{{lowercase title}}\n'''iDonate''' may refer to:\n\n*[[iDonate (Ireland)]], an online fundraising website based in Ireland\n\n{{disambiguation}}\n", "text_old": "{{lowercase title}}\n'''iDonate''' may refer to:\n\n*[[iDonate (Ireland)]], an online fundraising website based in Ireland\n*[[iDonate (Pakistan)]], a multi-purpose non-profit based in Pakistan\n\n{{disambiguation}}\n", "name_user": "Sandstein", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing link(s):Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/IDonate (Pakistan)closed as delete (XFDcloser)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IDonate"}
{"title_page": "Tonga 0\u201322 Australia", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football match\n| image                   = \n| event                   = 2002 FIFA World Cup qualification (OFC)\n| caption                 = \n| team1                   = [[Tonga national football team|Tonga]]\n| team1association        = {{flagicon|Tonga|size=30px}}\n| team1score              = 0\n| team2                   = [[Australia national soccer team|Australia]]\n| team2association        = {{flagicon|AUS|size=30px}}\n| team2score              = 22\n| details                 = \n| date                    = {{Start date|2001|04|09|df=y}}\n| stadium                 = [[Coffs Harbour International Stadium|International Sports Stadium]]\n| city                    = [[Coffs Harbour|Coffs Harbour, New South Wales]]\n| referee                 = Harry Atisson (Vanuatu)\n| attendance              = 1,500\n| weather                 = {{convert|25.1|C}}<ref>Climate Data Online. ''Bureau of Meteorology''. 9 April 2001</ref>\n}}\nOn 9 April 2001, [[Tonga national football team|Tonga]] and [[Australia national soccer team|Australia]] played an international [[association football]] match at the [[Coffs Harbour International Stadium|International Sports Stadium]] in [[Coffs Harbour]] in the Australian state of [[New South Wales]]. The match was an [[Oceania Football Confederation]] (OFC) [[2002 FIFA World Cup qualification (OFC)|first round qualifying match]] for the [[2002 FIFA World Cup]]. Tonga, nominally the home team for this round robin qualifying match, were defeated 0\u201322 by Australia. This beat the previous international record of 20\u20130 from October 2000 when [[2000 AFC Asian Cup qualification#Group 5|Kuwait defeated Bhutan on 12 February 2000]] in [[2000 AFC Asian Cup qualification|qualification for the 2000 AFC Asian Cup]].<ref group=note>A Libyan team defeated Oman 21\u20130 in 1966, however Oman was not a FIFA member at the time</ref> The margin of defeat also beat the previous record in a FIFA World Cup qualifying match, [[2002 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 AFC First Round#Group 2|the 19\u20130 result between Iran and Guam]] in [[Tabriz]] in November 2000.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.news24.com/xArchive/Sport/Soccer/Australia-set-record-20010410 |title=Australia set record |date=10 April 2001 |work=News24 |access-date=9 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/guam-line-up-for-long-road-to-glory |title=Guam line up for long road to glory |date=31 May 2019 |website=FIFA.com |language=en-GB |access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/13/sports/soccer/as-2018-world-cup-qualifying-begins-a-first-for-bhutan.html |title=A Moment Atop the World for Bhutan\u2019s Last-Ranked Team |last=Montague |first=James |date=2015-03-12 |website=The New York Times |language=en-US |access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> The margin was surpassed two days later when Australia again prevailed, defeating a depleted [[American Samoa national football team|American Samoa]] team with a [[Australia 31\u20130 American Samoa|31\u20130 scoreline]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2001-apr-16-sp-51697-story.html |title=Fair Play Takes a Real Beating Down Under |last=Jones |first=Graham L. |date=2001-04-16 |website=Los Angeles Times |language=en-US |access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n{{more|2002 FIFA World Cup qualification (OFC)}}\n[[File:Craig Moore.jpg|thumb|alt=A man wearing a white shirt and maroon shorts stands next a football.|Craig Moore, pictured in 2008, was one of eight players called up from European leagues]]\n\nTen teams from the [[Oceania Football Confederation]] (OFC) entered the [[2002 FIFA World Cup qualification (OFC)|2002 FIFA World Cup qualification tournament]]. The teams were split into two groups of five, with Group 1 playing in Australia at the [[Coffs Harbour International Stadium|International Sports Stadium]] in [[Coffs Harbour]] on the [[New South Wales North Coast]]. Group 2 was based in [[Auckland]], New Zealand. Australia and New Zealand, traditionally the two strongest teams in the OFC, were split for the group stage. Group 1 included Australia, Fiji, Tonga, Samoa and American Samoa; of which only Australia had previously appeared at the finals of a FIFA World Cup.\n\nIn January 2001, Australian coach [[Frank Farina]] suggested that he would head into the tournament with a squad split 50/50 between Australia and Europe.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://infoweb-newsbank-com.rp.nla.gov.au/apps/news/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info%3Asid/infoweb.newsbank.com&svc_dat=AWNB&req_dat=106B704DEA529B00&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi/fmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&rft_dat=document_id%3Anews%252F1053B16E8699AD74 |title=Farina to give homeboys a chance to call the tune - Soccer |last=Cockerill |first=Michael |date=2 January 2001 |website=The Sydney Morning Herald |access-date=2020-04-09|via=NewsBank|url-access=subscription}}</ref> With the qualifying tournament occurring during the European season, a number of clubs had appealed to FIFA to stop Australia from selecting European-based players. While [[Soccer Australia]] chairman Tony Labbozzetta initially agreed to FIFA demands that European-based players not play, Farina went ahead and selected a 20-man team of which eight were European-based.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Cockerill |first=Michael |url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/121574231/ |title=Farina delays announcing squad as he ponders whether to defy FIFA edict |date=27 March 2001 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |access-date=2020-04-09 |language=en|via=Newspapers.com|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Cockerill |first=Michael |url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/121575652/ |title=Frustrated Farina leaves Okon in England |date=28 March 2001 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |access-date=2020-04-09 |language=en|via=Newspapers.com|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Even after the squad was named, a number of managers of European-based players continued to complain of being deprived of their services. In early April, after [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] player [[Mustapha Hadji]] was suspended, manager [[Gordon Strachan]] appealed for [[John Aloisi]] to be released or banned from national duty.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Tousidis |first=Meno |url=https://infoweb-newsbank-com.rp.nla.gov.au/apps/news/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info%3Asid/infoweb.newsbank.com&svc_dat=AWNB&req_dat=106B704DEA529B00&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi/fmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&rft_dat=document_id%3Anews%252F0FC2568DC62BF8D8 |title=Plea to ban Aloisi |date=4 April 2001 |work=The Advertiser |access-date=2020-04-09|location=Adelaide|url-access=subscription|via=NewsBank}}</ref>\n\nAustralian midfielder [[Con Boutsianis]] was in doubt until the week before the match as he faced a [[County Court of Victoria]] trial after being involved in an armed robbery in 1998. Ultimately he was found guilty of theft, receiving a fine of {{AUD|20,000}} and a two-year good behaviour bond; leaving him free to play.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Cockerill |first=Michael |url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/121435995/ |title=Con free to play for Socceroos after escaping jail term |date=3 April 2001 |access-date=2020-04-09 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|via=Newspapers.com|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nAhead of the match, [[Ned Zelic]] effectively ended any hope of an Australian recall when he gave an interview on Planetfootball.com. He was quoted as saying, \"Because I don't play for them (any) more, I don't care if they make it (to the World Cup finals) or not\" and that he wished he had played for Croatia, \"Now I would like to play for Croatia, but that is no longer possible.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://theworldgame.sbs.com.au/zelic-burns-his-bridges |title=Zelic burns his bridges |date=29 March 2001 |work=The World Game |publisher=Special Broadcasting Service|agency=Sportal |access-date=2020-04-09 |language=en}}</ref> \n \nWith regular Australia captain [[Paul Okon]] choosing to prioritise playing for [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] over the national team, [[Kevin Muscat]] was a surprise choice for captain. It was suggested that his disciplinary troubles at club level would rule him out as a captaincy choice.<ref name=SMH-muscatskipper>{{Cite news |last=Cockerill |first=Michael |url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/121512436/|title=Muscat the surprise skipper as Socceroos' campaign kicks off |date=9 April 2001 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |access-date=2020-04-09 |language=en|via=Newspapers.com|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nIn the first match of the qualifying tournament, Tonga had defeated [[Samoa national football team|Samoa]] 1\u20130. While this was Tonga's second match, this was Australia's first with their last match before the tournament being a 3\u20132 loss to [[Colombia national football team|Colombia]] in [[Bogot\u00e1]] in February.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ozfootball.net/ark/Socceroo/reports/vCOL2001a.html |title=Colombia 3 - Australia 2 |publisher=Soccer Australia|via=www.ozfootball.net |access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.socceroos.com.au/news/caltex-socceroos-v-colombia-fixture-history |title=Caltex Socceroos v Colombia: fixture history |date=2018-01-19 |website=Socceroos.com.au |publisher=Football Federation Australia |language=en |access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n==Match summary==\nThe scoring was opened in the third minute by midfielder [[Scott Chipperfield]] with a tap-in inside the [[six yard box]] from a Damian Mori cross. In the 12th minute, Mori headed in a cross to make the score 0\u20131. Two minutes later, John Aloisi scored, turning onto his left foot, from outside the [[penalty area]]. Kevin Muscat scored the fourth goal after 17 minutes from the penalty spot after Scott Chipperfield was brought down by [[Kilifi Uele]]. Damian Mori scored his second in the 23rd minute with an angled shot beating the goalkeeper from just outside the six yard box. John Aloisi turned in a low cross from Mori to take the score to 0\u20136 a minute later. Muscat scored his second penalty in the 30th minute when the Vanuatuan referee Harry Attison adjudged a penalty against a Tongan defender. Aloisi brought up his hat-trick in the 37th minute with a headed goal from a headed cross. Mori became the second Australian with a hat-trick two minutes later when headed in a Lindsay Wilson cross. Aloisi scored his fourth goal in the 45th minute when he headed in a cross from six yards. The first half ended with the score at 0\u201310.<ref name=soccerooseverygoal>{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.socceroos.com.au/video/aus-22-0-tonga-all-goals |title=All 22 goals from Australia v Tonga in 2001 |work=Socceroos.com.au |date=8 April 2020 |type=Video}}</ref><ref name=farinapressure>{{Cite news |last=Cockerill |first=Michael |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/121515447/?terms=australia%2Btonga%2Bcoffs |title=Farina will not bow to pressure from UK |date=11 April 2001 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald|via=Newspapers.com|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nAloisi scored his fifth goal after 51 minutes, turning the ball in after the ball bounced off several players, allowing him to get into a one-on-one with the goalkeeper. Referee Attison adjudged that [[Teu Fakava]] had handled the ball. Muscat brought up a hat-trick of penalties, putting the ball past goalkeeper [[Tuahiva Fincfeuiaki]]. Mori scored his fourth with his head inside the six yard box from a ball played by Muscat. Aloisi scored his sixth goal, converting a Wilson cross inside the six yard box. Tony Popovic put the ball in the net from corner from near the penalty spot in the 65th minute to bring the score to 0\u201315. Farina decided to make two changes in the 69th minute, bringing on [[David Zdrilic]] for Mori and [[Con Boutsianis]], in his debut, for [[Steve Corica]]. Tony Vidmar headed in a corner from Boutsianis in the 73rd minute with the score moving to 0\u201316. [[Archie Thompson]] replaced Aloisi in the 73rd minute. Zdrilic scored the 17th goal in the 77th minute after the ball was cut back into the penalty area. Thompson put the ball past the goalkeeper from a Wilson cross in the 80th minute. Muscat tapped the ball past Fincfeuiaki after the Tonga 'keeper blocked a long-range shot into his path. The score moved to 0\u201320 after the Tongan goalkeeper dropped the ball and Chipperfield scored from well inside the six yard box. Boutsianis scored his first national team goal, tucking in a shot from a tight angle after the goalkeeper blocked his initial shot. The final goal was scored in the 90th minute by Zdrilic.<ref name=soccerooseverygoal/><ref name=farinapressure/>\n\nMori's four goals took him to 26 career goals, passing [[John Kosmina]] and [[Attila Abonyi]] to top the all-time Australia international goalscoring list.<ref name=recordrout>{{Cite news |last=Gatt |first=Ray |url=https://infoweb-newsbank-com.rp.nla.gov.au/apps/news/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info%3Asid/infoweb.newsbank.com&svc_dat=AWNB&req_dat=106B704DEA529B00&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi/fmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&rft_dat=document_id%3Anews%252F0FC514C78226F443 |title=Record rout has little meaning |date=10 April 2001 |work=The Australian |access-date=9 April 2020|via=NewsBank|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n===Details===\n{{Football box\n|id           = Tonga v Australia\n|date         = {{Start date|2001|04|09|df=y}}\n|time         = 16:30 [[UTC+10:00|UTC+10]]<ref name=SMH-muscatskipper/>\n|event        = [[2002 FIFA World Cup qualification]]\n|round        = First round\n|team1        = {{fb-rt|Tonga}}\n|score1       = 0\n|team2        = {{fb-rt|AUS}}\n|score2       = 22\n|scorenote    = \n|report       = https://web.archive.org/web/20071018093926/http://fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition=4395/preliminaries/preliminary=3863/matches/match=22240/report.html\n|goals1       = \n|goals2       = \n* [[Scott Chipperfield|Chipperfield]] {{goal|3||84}}\n* [[Damian Mori|Mori]] {{goal|12||22||39||57}}\n* [[John Aloisi|Aloisi]] {{goal|14||23||36||45||51||63}}\n* [[Kevin Muscat|Muscat]] {{goal|17|pen.|28|pen.|54|pen.|83}}\n* [[Tony Popovic|Popovic]] {{goal|65}}\n* [[Tony Vidmar|T. Vidmar]] {{goal|73}}\n* [[David Zdrilic|Zdrilic]] {{goal|77||90}}\n* [[Archie Thompson|Thompson]] {{goal|79}}\n* [[Con Boutsianis|Boutsianis]] {{goal|85}}\n|stadium      = [[Coffs Harbour International Stadium|International Sports Stadium]]\n|location     = [[Coffs Harbour|Coffs Harbour, New South Wales]], Australia\n|attendance   = 1,500\n|referee      = Harry Attison ([[Vanuatu Football Federation|Vanuatu]])\n}}\n\n{| style=\"width:92%;\"\n|-\n|{{Football kit\n| alt        = \n| pattern_la = _whiteborder\n| pattern_b  = _collarwhite\n| pattern_ra = _whiteborder\n| pattern_sh = _adidaswhite\n| pattern_so = _band_white\n| leftarm    = FF0000\t\n| body       = FF0000\t\n| rightarm   = FF0000\n| shorts     = FFFFFF\n| socks      = FF0000\n| title      = Tonga\n}}\n|{{Football kit\n| pattern_b  = _thinyellowsides\n| leftarm    = 12650F\n| body       = 12650F\n| rightarm   = 12650F\n| shorts     = 12650F\n| socks      = 12650F\n| title      = Australia\n}}\n|}\n\n{| width=\"100%\"\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|1||[[Tuahiva Fincfeuiaki]]\n|-\n|2||[[Kilifi Uele]]\n|-\n|3||[[Toakai Toto]] || {{suboff|63}}\n|-\n|5||[[Filisione Taufahema]] || {{suboff|63}}\n|-\n|6||{{no wrap|[[Halapua Falepapalangi]]}}\n|-\n|9||[[Lokoua Taufahema]] || {{suboff|105}}\n|-\n|10||[[Siua Maamaloa]]\n|-\n|11||[[Akoli Mafi]]\n|-\n|16||[[Hateni Manu]]\n|-\n|17||[[Kaisani Uhatahi]]\n|-\n|19||[[Teu Fakava]]\n|-\n|colspan=2|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|4||{{no wrap|[[Unaloto-Ki-Atenoafeao Feao]]}} || {{subon|63}}\n|-\n|7||[[Solomone Moa]] || {{subon|63}}\n|-\n|8||[[Ipeni Fonua]]\n|-\n|12||[[Taniela Fonua]]\n|-\n|13||[[Falame Ilangana]]\n|-\n|14||{{no wrap|[[Lopeti Halapoi Fuimaono]]}}\n|-\n|15||[[Timoate Moleni]] || {{subon|63}}\n|-\n|18||[[Penieli Moa]]\n|-\n|20||[[Villiami Taufahema]]\n|-\n|colspan=2|'''Coach:'''\n|-\n|colspan=2|[[Gary Phillips (soccer)|Gary Phillips]] (AUS)\n|}\n|valign=\"top\"|\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%; margin: auto;\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|18||[[Clint Bolton]]\n|-\n| 2 ||[[Kevin Muscat]]\n|-\n| 3 ||[[Craig Moore]]\n|-\n| 4 ||[[Tony Popovic]]  \n|-\n| 5 ||[[Tony Vidmar]]\n|-\n| 6 ||[[Hayden Foxe]]\n|-\n| 8 ||{{no wrap|[[Scott Chipperfield]]}}\n|-\n| 9 ||[[John Aloisi]] || {{suboff|73}}\n|-\n| 10 ||[[Steve Corica]] || {{suboff|69}}\n|-\n| 16 ||[[Lindsay Wilson (soccer)|Lindsay Wilson]]\n|-\n| 19 ||[[Damian Mori]] || {{suboff|69}}\n|-\n|colspan=2|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|1||[[Michael Petkovic]]  \n|-\n|7||[[Aurelio Vidmar]]  \n|-\n|11||[[David Zdrilic]] || {{subon|69}}\n|-\n|12||[[Steve Horvat]]\n|-\n|13||[[Con Boutsianis]] || {{subon|69}}\n|-\n|14||[[Simon Colosimo]]\n|-\n|15||{{no wrap|[[Fausto De Amicis]]}}\n|-\n|17||[[Scott Miller (soccer, born 1972)|Scott Miller]]\n|-\n|20||{{no wrap|[[Archie Thompson]]}} || {{subon|73}}\n|-\n|colspan=2|'''Coach:'''\n|-\n|colspan=2|[[Frank Farina]] (AUS)\n|}\n|}\n{| width=100% style=\"font-size: 90%\"\n|\n'''Assistant referees:'''\n<br />Elise Doriri ([[Vanuatu Football Federation|Vanuatu]])\n<br />Teariki Goodwin ([[Cook Islands Football Association|Cook Islands]])\n<br />'''Fourth official:'''\n<br />Ronan Leaustic ([[Tahitian Football Federation|Tahiti]])\n|}\n\n==Reaction==\nAustralian coach Farina described the win as \"embarrassing\" and called on the OFC to review the competition format. Tonga coach [[Gary Phillips (soccer)|Gary Phillips]] questioned the need for Australia to call up so many European-based players saying, \"All up if you combine the total monetary worth of the Socceroos, and divide it by five then you have the total economy of Tonga.\"<ref name=recordrout/>\n\n[[Gordon Strachan]], [[John Aloisi]]'s manager at [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] condemned FIFA and Soccer Australia for letting Australia select his striker. Strachan was quoted in the ''Coventry Telegraph'', \"I am angry with FIFA for letting this situation occur and angry with the Australian FA but there is nothing we can do. We have already appealed to people's decency but that has not worked.\" He pointed out that other Australian players, including regular Australian captain [[Paul Okon]] and goalkeeper [[Mark Schwarzer]], were allowed to play in English football while he was denied Aloisi's services.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://infoweb-newsbank-com.rp.nla.gov.au/apps/news/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info%3Asid/infoweb.newsbank.com&svc_dat=AWNB&req_dat=106B704DEA529B00&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi/fmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&rft_dat=document_id%3Anews%252F1390A2C305C664C0 |title=Strachan anger at Aussie farce - Football|date=10 April 2001 |work=Coventry Telegraph |access-date=9 April 2020|url-access=subscription|via=NewsBank}}</ref>\n\n[[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] manager, [[Dick Advocaat]] was already angry about losing two of his players, [[Craig Moore]] and [[Tony Vidmar]], but was especially critical of Farina saying, \"It says enough about the stupidity of the situation when a team is winning 22-0 and the annoying thing is that the Australian manager clearly does not need all of his overseas players to win a game like that.\" Like Strachan, he noted that several regular first-choice players were allowed to continue playing in England.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Campbell |first=Iain |url=https://infoweb-newsbank-com.rp.nla.gov.au/apps/news/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info%3Asid/infoweb.newsbank.com&svc_dat=AWNB&req_dat=106B704DEA529B00&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi/fmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&rft_dat=document_id%3Anews%252F13917657C3821240 |title=Football: Dick fury at score point |date=10 April 2001 |work=Daily Mirror |access-date=9 April 2020|url-access=subscription|via=NewsBank}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Grahame |first1=Ewing |title=Football: Dick rages at Aussie boss after 22-0 rout |url=https://infoweb-newsbank-com.rp.nla.gov.au/apps/news/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info%3Asid/infoweb.newsbank.com&svc_dat=AWNB&req_dat=106B704DEA529B00&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi/fmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&rft_dat=document_id%3Anews%252F13918726281A7AC0 |accessdate=9 April 2020 |work=The Daily Record |date=10 April 2001|url-access=subscription|via=NewsBank}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://infoweb-newsbank-com.rp.nla.gov.au/apps/news/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info%3Asid/infoweb.newsbank.com&svc_dat=AWNB&req_dat=106B704DEA529B00&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi/fmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&rft_dat=document_id%3Anews%252F0F929EA1C6474C79 |title=Advocaat angry with Australian absenteeism - Football |date=10 April 2001 |work=The Times |access-date=9 April 2020|url-access=subscription|via=NewsBank}}</ref> Responding to Advocaat's criticism, Farina was unrepentant saying, \"Dick from Rangers has had his say and I am sure Dick has got his problems\" and \"Dick can blow as much wind out of his mouth as he likes, but it's not changing.\"<ref>{{Cite news |last=Lynch |first=Michael |url=https://infoweb-newsbank-com.rp.nla.gov.au/apps/news/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info%3Asid/infoweb.newsbank.com&svc_dat=AWNB&req_dat=106B704DEA529B00&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi/fmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&rft_dat=document_id%3Anews%252F1054617EB9E92E49 |title=Farina defiant as UK clubs demand players back |date=11 April 2001 |work=The Age |access-date=9 April 2020|url-access=subscription|via=NewsBank}}</ref>\n\nAustralian soccer writer [[Mike Cockerill|Michael Cockerill]] wrote in ''The Sydney Morning Herald'' after Australia's subsequent match against 31\u20130 win over American Samoa wrote, \"[f]ifty-three goals in two games. The record books torn to bits. It is too late to end the carnage this time around, but there should be no repetition in four years.\"<ref>{{Cite news |last=Cockerill |first=Michael |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/121517184/ |title=31\u20130 - Thompson, Socceroos tear up the record book |date=12 April 2001 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |access-date=9 April 2020|url-access=subscription|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\n==Qualification==\n{{further|2002 FIFA World Cup qualification (OFC)|Australia 31\u20130 American Samoa|2002 FIFA World Cup qualification (OFC\u2013CONMEBOL play-off)}}\nAustralia went on to defeat [[American Samoa national football team|American Samoa]] 31\u20130, [[Fiji national football team|Fiji]] 2\u20130 and [[Samoa national football team|Samoa]] 11\u20130. They finished first in their group with a maximum possible 12 points and a goal difference of +66.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Cockerill |first=Michael |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/121495061 |title=So far, so good for Farina |date=17 April 2001 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |access-date=2020-04-09|url-access=subscription|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Cockerill |first=Michael |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/121495061 |title=Ideal finish but Samoa keeper stars |date=17 April 2001 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |access-date=2020-04-09|url-access=subscription|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nIn the second stage of qualifying, Australia defeated [[New Zealand national football team|New Zealand]] with an aggregate score of 6\u20131 to win a place in the CONMEBOL\u2013OFC playoff against the fifth-placed South American team.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/australia-through-the-last-leg-78201 |title=Australia through to the last leg |date=24 June 2001 |website=FIFA.com |language=en-GB |access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Despite winning the first leg against [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] 1\u20130 in [[Melbourne]], they were beaten 3\u20130 in [[Montevideo]] to be eliminated 3\u20131 on aggregate.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Hall |first=Matthew |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2001/nov/21/worldcupfootball2002.sport |title=Australia 1 - 0 Uruguay |date=2001-11-21 |work=The Guardian |access-date=2020-04-09 |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Fahey |first=Jessica |url=http://www.theguardian.com/football/2001/nov/26/newsstory.sport1 |title=World Cup Play-Off: Uruguay 3 - 0 Australia. Uruguay win 3 - 1 on aggregate. |date=2001-11-26 |work=The Guardian |access-date=2020-04-09 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{FIFA World Cup 2002 Qualifiers}}\n{{Australia national football team matches}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tonga 0-22 Australia}}\n[[Category:2000\u201301 in OFC football]]\n[[Category:2002 FIFA World Cup qualification (OFC)]]\n[[Category:FIFA World Cup qualification matches]]\n[[Category:Australia national soccer team matches]]\n[[Category:2001 in Australian soccer]]\n[[Category:Record association football wins]]\n[[Category:April 2001 sports events in Oceania]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football match\n| image                   = \n| event                   = 2002 FIFA World Cup qualification (OFC)\n| caption                 = \n| team1                   = [[Tonga national football team|Tonga]]\n| team1association        = {{flagicon|Tonga|size=30px}}\n| team1score              = 0\n| team2                   = [[Australia national soccer team|Australia]]\n| team2association        = {{flagicon|AUS|size=30px}}\n| team2score              = 22\n| details                 = \n| date                    = {{Start date|2001|04|09|df=y}}\n| stadium                 = [[Coffs Harbour International Stadium|International Sports Stadium]]\n| city                    = [[Coffs Harbour|Coffs Harbour, New South Wales]]\n| referee                 = Harry Atisson (Vanuatu)\n| attendance              = 1,500\n| weather                 = {{convert|25.1|C}}<ref>Climate Data Online. ''Bureau of Meteorology''. 9 April 2001</ref>\n}}\nOn 9 April 2001, [[Tonga national football team|Tonga]] and [[Australia national soccer team|Australia]] played an international [[association football]] match at the [[Coffs Harbour International Stadium|International Sports Stadium]] in [[Coffs Harbour]] in the Australian state of [[New South Wales]]. The match was an [[Oceania Football Confederation]] (OFC) [[2002 FIFA World Cup qualification (OFC)|first round qualifying match]] for the [[2002 FIFA World Cup]]. Tonga, nominally the home team for this round robin qualifying match, were defeated 0\u201322 by Australia. This beat the previous international record of 20\u20130 from October 2000 when [[2000 AFC Asian Cup qualification#Group 5|Kuwait defeated Bhutan on 12 February 2000]] in [[2000 AFC Asian Cup qualification|qualification for the 2000 AFC Asian Cup]].<ref group=note>A Libyan team defeated Oman 21\u20130 in 1966, however Oman was not a FIFA member at the time</ref> The margin of defeat also beat the previous record in a FIFA World Cup qualifying match, [[2002 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 AFC First Round#Group 2|the 19\u20130 result between Iran and Guam]] in [[Tabriz]] in November 2000.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.news24.com/xArchive/Sport/Soccer/Australia-set-record-20010410 |title=Australia set record |date=10 April 2001 |work=News24 |access-date=9 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/guam-line-up-for-long-road-to-glory |title=Guam line up for long road to glory |date=31 May 2019 |website=FIFA.com |language=en-GB |access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/13/sports/soccer/as-2018-world-cup-qualifying-begins-a-first-for-bhutan.html |title=A Moment Atop the World for Bhutan\u2019s Last-Ranked Team |last=Montague |first=James |date=2015-03-12 |website=The New York Times |language=en-US |access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> The margin was surpassed two days later when Australia again prevailed, defeating a depleted [[American Samoa national football team|American Samoa]] team with a [[Australia 31\u20130 American Samoa|31\u20130 scoreline]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2001-apr-16-sp-51697-story.html |title=Fair Play Takes a Real Beating Down Under |last=Jones |first=Graham L. |date=2001-04-16 |website=Los Angeles Times |language=en-US |access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n{{more|2002 FIFA World Cup qualification (OFC)}}\n[[File:Craig Moore.jpg|thumb|alt=A man wearing a white shirt and maroon shorts stands next a football.|Craig Moore, pictured in 2008, was one of eight players called up from European leagues]]\n\nTen teams from the [[Oceania Football Confederation]] (OFC) entered the [[2002 FIFA World Cup qualification (OFC)|2002 FIFA World Cup qualification tournament]]. The teams were split into two groups of five, with Group 1 playing in Australia at the [[Coffs Harbour International Stadium|International Sports Stadium]] in [[Coffs Harbour]] on the [[New South Wales North Coast]]. Group 2 was based in [[Auckland]], New Zealand. Australia and New Zealand, traditionally the two strongest teams in the OFC, were split for the group stage. Group 1 included Australia, Fiji, Tonga, Samoa and American Samoa; of which only Australia had previously appeared at the finals of a FIFA World Cup.\n\nIn January 2001, Australian coach [[Frank Farina]] suggested that he would head into the tournament with a squad split 50/50 between Australia and Europe.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://infoweb-newsbank-com.rp.nla.gov.au/apps/news/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info%3Asid/infoweb.newsbank.com&svc_dat=AWNB&req_dat=106B704DEA529B00&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi/fmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&rft_dat=document_id%3Anews%252F1053B16E8699AD74 |title=Farina to give homeboys a chance to call the tune - Soccer |last=Cockerill |first=Michael |date=2 January 2001 |website=The Sydney Morning Herald |access-date=2020-04-09|via=NewsBank|url-access=subscription}}</ref> With the qualifying tournament occurring during the European season, a number of clubs had appealed to FIFA to stop Australia from selecting European-based players. While [[Soccer Australia]] chairman Tony Labbozzetta initially agreed to FIFA demands that European-based players not play, Farina went ahead and selected a 20-man team of which eight were European-based.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Cockerill |first=Michael |url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/121574231/ |title=Farina delays announcing squad as he ponders whether to defy FIFA edict |date=27 March 2001 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |access-date=2020-04-09 |language=en|via=Newspapers.com|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Cockerill |first=Michael |url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/121575652/ |title=Frustrated Farina leaves Okon in England |date=28 March 2001 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |access-date=2020-04-09 |language=en|via=Newspapers.com|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Even after the squad was named, a number of managers of European-based players continued to complain of being deprived of their services. In early April, after [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] player [[Mustapha Hadji]] was suspended, manager [[Gordon Strachan]] appealed for [[John Aloisi]] to be released or banned from national duty.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Tousidis |first=Meno |url=https://infoweb-newsbank-com.rp.nla.gov.au/apps/news/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info%3Asid/infoweb.newsbank.com&svc_dat=AWNB&req_dat=106B704DEA529B00&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi/fmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&rft_dat=document_id%3Anews%252F0FC2568DC62BF8D8 |title=Plea to ban Aloisi |date=4 April 2001 |work=The Advertiser |access-date=2020-04-09|location=Adelaide|url-access=subscription|via=NewsBank}}</ref>\n\nAustralian midfielder [[Con Boutsianis]] was in doubt until the week before the match as he faced a [[County Court of Victoria]] trial after being involved in an armed robbery in 1998. Ultimately he was found guilty of theft, receiving a fine of {{AUD|20,000}} and a two-year good behaviour bond; leaving him free to play.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Cockerill |first=Michael |url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/121435995/ |title=Con free to play for Socceroos after escaping jail term |date=3 April 2001 |access-date=2020-04-09 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|via=Newspapers.com|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nAhead of the match, [[Ned Zelic]] effectively ended any hope of an Australian recall when he gave an interview on Planetfootball.com. He was quoted as saying, \"Because I don't play for them (any) more, I don't care if they make it (to the World Cup finals) or not\" and that he wished he had played for Croatia, \"Now I would like to play for Croatia, but that is no longer possible.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://theworldgame.sbs.com.au/zelic-burns-his-bridges |title=Zelic burns his bridges |date=29 March 2001 |work=The World Game |publisher=Special Broadcasting Service|agency=Sportal |access-date=2020-04-09 |language=en}}</ref> \n \nWith regular Australia captain [[Paul Okon]] choosing to prioritise playing for [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] over the national team, [[Kevin Muscat]] was a surprise choice for captain. It was suggested that his disciplinary troubles at club level would rule him out as a captaincy choice.<ref name=SMH-muscatskipper>{{Cite news |last=Cockerill |first=Michael |url=http://www.newspapers.com/image/121512436/|title=Muscat the surprise skipper as Socceroos' campaign kicks off |date=9 April 2001 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |access-date=2020-04-09 |language=en|via=Newspapers.com|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nIn the first match of the qualifying tournament, Tonga had defeated [[Samoa national football team|Samoa]] 1\u20130. While this was Tonga's second match, this was Australia's first with their last match before the tournament being a 3\u20132 loss to [[Colombia national football team|Colombia]] in [[Bogot\u00e1]] in February.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ozfootball.net/ark/Socceroo/reports/vCOL2001a.html |title=Colombia 3 - Australia 2 |publisher=Soccer Australia|via=www.ozfootball.net |access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.socceroos.com.au/news/caltex-socceroos-v-colombia-fixture-history |title=Caltex Socceroos v Colombia: fixture history |date=2018-01-19 |website=Socceroos.com.au |publisher=Football Federation Australia |language=en |access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n==Match summary==\nThe scoring was opened in the third minute by midfielder [[Scott Chipperfield]] with a tap-in inside the [[six yard box]] from a Damian Mori cross. In the 12th minute, Mori headed in a cross to make the score 0\u20131. Two minutes later, John Aloisi scored, turning onto his left foot, from outside the [[penalty area]]. Kevin Muscat scored the fourth goal after 17 minutes from the penalty spot after Scott Chipperfield was brought down by [[Kilifi Uele]]. Damian Mori scored his second in the 23rd minute with an angled shot beating the goalkeeper from just outside the six yard box. John Aloisi turned in a low cross from Mori to take the score to 0\u20136 a minute later. Muscat scored his second penalty in the 30th minute when the Vanuatuan referee Harry Attison adjudged a penalty against a Tongan defender. Aloisi brought up his hat-trick in the 37th minute with a headed goal from a headed cross. Mori became the second Australian with a hat-trick two minutes later when headed in a Lindsay Wilson cross. Aloisi scored his fourth goal in the 45th minute when he headed in a cross from six yards. The first half ended with the score at 0\u201310.<ref name=soccerooseverygoal>{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.socceroos.com.au/video/aus-22-0-tonga-all-goals |title=All 22 goals from Australia v Tonga in 2001 |work=Socceroos.com.au |date=8 April 2020 |type=Video}}</ref><ref name=farinapressure>{{Cite news |last=Cockerill |first=Michael |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/121515447/?terms=australia%2Btonga%2Bcoffs |title=Farina will not bow to pressure from UK |date=11 April 2001 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald|via=Newspapers.com|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nAloisi scored his fifth goal after 51 minutes, turning the ball in after the ball bounced off several players, allowing him to get into a one-on-one with the goalkeeper. Referee Attison adjudged that [[Teu Fakava]] had handled the ball. Muscat brought up a hat-trick of penalties, putting the ball past goalkeeper [[Tuahiva Fincfeuiaki]]. Mori scored his fourth with his head inside the six yard box from a ball played by Muscat. Aloisi scored his sixth goal, converting a Wilson cross inside the six yard box. Tony Popovic put the ball in the net from corner from near the penalty spot in the 65th minute to bring the score to 0\u201315. Farina decided to make two changes in the 69th minute, bringing on [[David Zdrilic]] for Mori and [[Con Boutsianis]], in his debut, for [[Steve Corica]]. Tony Vidmar headed in a corner from Boutsianis in the 73rd minute with the score moving to 0\u201316. [[Archie Thompson]] replaced Aloisi in the 73rd minute. Zdrilic scored the 17th goal in the 77th minute after the ball was cut back into the penalty area. Thompson put the ball past the goalkeeper from a Wilson cross in the 80th minute. Muscat tapped the ball past Fincfeuiaki after the Tonga 'keeper blocked a long-range shot into his path. The score moved to 0\u201320 after the Tongan goalkeeper dropped the ball and Chipperfield scored from well inside the six yard box. Boutsianis scored his first national team goal, tucking in a shot from a tight angle after the goalkeeper blocked his initial shot. The final goal was scored in the 90th minute by Zdrilic.<ref name=soccerooseverygoal/><ref name=farinapressure/>\n\nMori's four goals took him to 26 career goals, passing [[John Kosmina]] and [[Attila Abonyi]] to top the all-time Australia international goalscoring list.<ref name=recordrout>{{Cite news |last=Gatt |first=Ray |url=https://infoweb-newsbank-com.rp.nla.gov.au/apps/news/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info%3Asid/infoweb.newsbank.com&svc_dat=AWNB&req_dat=106B704DEA529B00&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi/fmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&rft_dat=document_id%3Anews%252F0FC514C78226F443 |title=Record rout has little meaning |date=10 April 2001 |work=The Australian |access-date=9 April 2020|via=NewsBank|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n===Details===\n{{Football box\n|id           = Tonga v Australia\n|date         = {{Start date|2001|04|09|df=y}}\n|time         = 16:30 [[UTC+10:00|UTC+10]]<ref name=SMH-muscatskipper/>\n|event        = [[2002 FIFA World Cup qualification]]\n|round        = First round\n|team1        = {{fb-rt|Tonga}}\n|score1       = 0\n|team2        = {{fb-rt|AUS}}\n|score2       = 22\n|scorenote    = \n|report       = https://web.archive.org/web/20071018093926/http://fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition=4395/preliminaries/preliminary=3863/matches/match=22240/report.html\n|goals1       = \n|goals2       = \n* [[Scott Chipperfield|Chipperfield]] {{goal|3||84}}\n* [[Damian Mori|Mori]] {{goal|12||22||39||57}}\n* [[John Aloisi|Aloisi]] {{goal|14||23||36||45||51||63}}\n* [[Kevin Muscat|Muscat]] {{goal|17|pen.|28|pen.|54|pen.|83}}\n* [[Tony Popovic|Popovic]] {{goal|65}}\n* [[Tony Vidmar|Vidmar]] {{goal|73}}\n* [[David Zdrilic|Zdrilic]] {{goal|77||90}}\n* [[Archie Thompson|Thompson]] {{goal|79}}\n* [[Con Boutsianis|Boutsianis]] {{goal|85}}\n|stadium      = [[Coffs Harbour International Stadium|International Sports Stadium]]\n|location     = [[Coffs Harbour|Coffs Harbour, New South Wales]], Australia\n|attendance   = 1,500\n|referee      = Harry Attison ([[Vanuatu Football Federation|Vanuatu]])\n}}\n\n{| style=\"width:92%;\"\n|-\n|{{Football kit\n| alt        = \n| pattern_la = _whiteborder\n| pattern_b  = _collarwhite\n| pattern_ra = _whiteborder\n| pattern_sh = _adidaswhite\n| pattern_so = _band_white\n| leftarm    = FF0000\t\n| body       = FF0000\t\n| rightarm   = FF0000\n| shorts     = FFFFFF\n| socks      = FF0000\n| title      = Tonga\n}}\n|{{Football kit\n| pattern_b  = _thinyellowsides\n| leftarm    = 12650F\n| body       = 12650F\n| rightarm   = 12650F\n| shorts     = 12650F\n| socks      = 12650F\n| title      = Australia\n}}\n|}\n\n{| width=\"100%\"\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|1||[[Tuahiva Fincfeuiaki]]\n|-\n|2||[[Kilifi Uele]]\n|-\n|3||[[Toakai Toto]] || {{suboff|63}}\n|-\n|5||[[Filisione Taufahema]] || {{suboff|63}}\n|-\n|6||{{no wrap|[[Halapua Falepapalangi]]}}\n|-\n|9||[[Lokoua Taufahema]] || {{suboff|105}}\n|-\n|10||[[Siua Maamaloa]]\n|-\n|11||[[Akoli Mafi]]\n|-\n|16||[[Hateni Manu]]\n|-\n|17||[[Kaisani Uhatahi]]\n|-\n|19||[[Teu Fakava]]\n|-\n|colspan=2|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|4||{{no wrap|[[Unaloto-Ki-Atenoafeao Feao]]}} || {{subon|63}}\n|-\n|7||[[Solomone Moa]] || {{subon|63}}\n|-\n|8||[[Ipeni Fonua]]\n|-\n|12||[[Taniela Fonua]]\n|-\n|13||[[Falame Ilangana]]\n|-\n|14||{{no wrap|[[Lopeti Halapoi Fuimaono]]}}\n|-\n|15||[[Timoate Moleni]] || {{subon|63}}\n|-\n|18||[[Penieli Moa]]\n|-\n|20||[[Villiami Taufahema]]\n|-\n|colspan=2|'''Coach:'''\n|-\n|colspan=2|[[Gary Phillips (soccer)|Gary Phillips]] (AUS)\n|}\n|valign=\"top\"|\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%; margin: auto;\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|18||[[Clint Bolton]]\n|-\n| 2 ||[[Kevin Muscat]]\n|-\n| 3 ||[[Craig Moore]]\n|-\n| 4 ||[[Tony Popovic]]  \n|-\n| 5 ||[[Tony Vidmar]]\n|-\n| 6 ||[[Hayden Foxe]]\n|-\n| 8 ||{{no wrap|[[Scott Chipperfield]]}}\n|-\n| 9 ||[[John Aloisi]] || {{suboff|73}}\n|-\n| 10 ||[[Steve Corica]] || {{suboff|69}}\n|-\n| 16 ||[[Lindsay Wilson (soccer)|Lindsay Wilson]]\n|-\n| 19 ||[[Damian Mori]] || {{suboff|69}}\n|-\n|colspan=2|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|1||[[Michael Petkovic]]  \n|-\n|7||[[Aurelio Vidmar]]  \n|-\n|11||[[David Zdrilic]] || {{subon|69}}\n|-\n|12||[[Steve Horvat]]\n|-\n|13||[[Con Boutsianis]] || {{subon|69}}\n|-\n|14||[[Simon Colosimo]]\n|-\n|15||{{no wrap|[[Fausto De Amicis]]}}\n|-\n|17||[[Scott Miller (soccer, born 1972)|Scott Miller]]\n|-\n|20||{{no wrap|[[Archie Thompson]]}} || {{subon|73}}\n|-\n|colspan=2|'''Coach:'''\n|-\n|colspan=2|[[Frank Farina]] (AUS)\n|}\n|}\n{| width=100% style=\"font-size: 90%\"\n|\n'''Assistant referees:'''\n<br />Elise Doriri ([[Vanuatu Football Federation|Vanuatu]])\n<br />Teariki Goodwin ([[Cook Islands Football Association|Cook Islands]])\n<br />'''Fourth official:'''\n<br />Ronan Leaustic ([[Tahitian Football Federation|Tahiti]])\n|}\n\n==Reaction==\nAustralian coach Farina described the win as \"embarrassing\" and called on the OFC to review the competition format. Tonga coach [[Gary Phillips (soccer)|Gary Phillips]] questioned the need for Australia to call up so many European-based players saying, \"All up if you combine the total monetary worth of the Socceroos, and divide it by five then you have the total economy of Tonga.\"<ref name=recordrout/>\n\n[[Gordon Strachan]], [[John Aloisi]]'s manager at [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] condemned FIFA and Soccer Australia for letting Australia select his striker. Strachan was quoted in the ''Coventry Telegraph'', \"I am angry with FIFA for letting this situation occur and angry with the Australian FA but there is nothing we can do. We have already appealed to people's decency but that has not worked.\" He pointed out that other Australian players, including regular Australian captain [[Paul Okon]] and goalkeeper [[Mark Schwarzer]], were allowed to play in English football while he was denied Aloisi's services.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://infoweb-newsbank-com.rp.nla.gov.au/apps/news/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info%3Asid/infoweb.newsbank.com&svc_dat=AWNB&req_dat=106B704DEA529B00&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi/fmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&rft_dat=document_id%3Anews%252F1390A2C305C664C0 |title=Strachan anger at Aussie farce - Football|date=10 April 2001 |work=Coventry Telegraph |access-date=9 April 2020|url-access=subscription|via=NewsBank}}</ref>\n\n[[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] manager, [[Dick Advocaat]] was already angry about losing two of his players, [[Craig Moore]] and [[Tony Vidmar]], but was especially critical of Farina saying, \"It says enough about the stupidity of the situation when a team is winning 22-0 and the annoying thing is that the Australian manager clearly does not need all of his overseas players to win a game like that.\" Like Strachan, he noted that several regular first-choice players were allowed to continue playing in England.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Campbell |first=Iain |url=https://infoweb-newsbank-com.rp.nla.gov.au/apps/news/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info%3Asid/infoweb.newsbank.com&svc_dat=AWNB&req_dat=106B704DEA529B00&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi/fmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&rft_dat=document_id%3Anews%252F13917657C3821240 |title=Football: Dick fury at score point |date=10 April 2001 |work=Daily Mirror |access-date=9 April 2020|url-access=subscription|via=NewsBank}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Grahame |first1=Ewing |title=Football: Dick rages at Aussie boss after 22-0 rout |url=https://infoweb-newsbank-com.rp.nla.gov.au/apps/news/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info%3Asid/infoweb.newsbank.com&svc_dat=AWNB&req_dat=106B704DEA529B00&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi/fmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&rft_dat=document_id%3Anews%252F13918726281A7AC0 |accessdate=9 April 2020 |work=The Daily Record |date=10 April 2001|url-access=subscription|via=NewsBank}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://infoweb-newsbank-com.rp.nla.gov.au/apps/news/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info%3Asid/infoweb.newsbank.com&svc_dat=AWNB&req_dat=106B704DEA529B00&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi/fmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&rft_dat=document_id%3Anews%252F0F929EA1C6474C79 |title=Advocaat angry with Australian absenteeism - Football |date=10 April 2001 |work=The Times |access-date=9 April 2020|url-access=subscription|via=NewsBank}}</ref> Responding to Advocaat's criticism, Farina was unrepentant saying, \"Dick from Rangers has had his say and I am sure Dick has got his problems\" and \"Dick can blow as much wind out of his mouth as he likes, but it's not changing.\"<ref>{{Cite news |last=Lynch |first=Michael |url=https://infoweb-newsbank-com.rp.nla.gov.au/apps/news/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info%3Asid/infoweb.newsbank.com&svc_dat=AWNB&req_dat=106B704DEA529B00&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi/fmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&rft_dat=document_id%3Anews%252F1054617EB9E92E49 |title=Farina defiant as UK clubs demand players back |date=11 April 2001 |work=The Age |access-date=9 April 2020|url-access=subscription|via=NewsBank}}</ref>\n\nAustralian soccer writer [[Mike Cockerill|Michael Cockerill]] wrote in ''The Sydney Morning Herald'' after Australia's subsequent match against 31\u20130 win over American Samoa wrote, \"[f]ifty-three goals in two games. The record books torn to bits. It is too late to end the carnage this time around, but there should be no repetition in four years.\"<ref>{{Cite news |last=Cockerill |first=Michael |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/121517184/ |title=31\u20130 - Thompson, Socceroos tear up the record book |date=12 April 2001 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |access-date=9 April 2020|url-access=subscription|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\n==Qualification==\n{{further|2002 FIFA World Cup qualification (OFC)|Australia 31\u20130 American Samoa|2002 FIFA World Cup qualification (OFC\u2013CONMEBOL play-off)}}\nAustralia went on to defeat [[American Samoa national football team|American Samoa]] 31\u20130, [[Fiji national football team|Fiji]] 2\u20130 and [[Samoa national football team|Samoa]] 11\u20130. They finished first in their group with a maximum possible 12 points and a goal difference of +66.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Cockerill |first=Michael |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/121495061 |title=So far, so good for Farina |date=17 April 2001 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |access-date=2020-04-09|url-access=subscription|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Cockerill |first=Michael |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/121495061 |title=Ideal finish but Samoa keeper stars |date=17 April 2001 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |access-date=2020-04-09|url-access=subscription|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nIn the second stage of qualifying, Australia defeated [[New Zealand national football team|New Zealand]] with an aggregate score of 6\u20131 to win a place in the CONMEBOL\u2013OFC playoff against the fifth-placed South American team.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/australia-through-the-last-leg-78201 |title=Australia through to the last leg |date=24 June 2001 |website=FIFA.com |language=en-GB |access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Despite winning the first leg against [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] 1\u20130 in [[Melbourne]], they were beaten 3\u20130 in [[Montevideo]] to be eliminated 3\u20131 on aggregate.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Hall |first=Matthew |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2001/nov/21/worldcupfootball2002.sport |title=Australia 1 - 0 Uruguay |date=2001-11-21 |work=The Guardian |access-date=2020-04-09 |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Fahey |first=Jessica |url=http://www.theguardian.com/football/2001/nov/26/newsstory.sport1 |title=World Cup Play-Off: Uruguay 3 - 0 Australia. Uruguay win 3 - 1 on aggregate. |date=2001-11-26 |work=The Guardian |access-date=2020-04-09 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{FIFA World Cup 2002 Qualifiers}}\n{{Australia national football team matches}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tonga 0-22 Australia}}\n[[Category:2000\u201301 in OFC football]]\n[[Category:2002 FIFA World Cup qualification (OFC)]]\n[[Category:FIFA World Cup qualification matches]]\n[[Category:Australia national soccer team matches]]\n[[Category:2001 in Australian soccer]]\n[[Category:Record association football wins]]\n[[Category:April 2001 sports events in Oceania]]\n", "name_user": "SuperJew", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDetails:differentiate Vidmar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tonga_0%E2%80%9322_Australia"}
